<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Provision Requires Travel Repayment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted Tuesday night to require  
challengers for federal office to reimburse the government for the 
actual cost of their political travel, a provision that Democrats 
complained was aimed solely at first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was 261-167 in favor of the provision, advanced by Rep.  
John Sweeney, R-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney said the proposal was designed to make ``potential  
candidates more accountable to taxpayers.'' He said constituents 
had raised Mrs. Clinton's use of government aircraft to conduct her 
unannounced Senate campaign from New York ``as an equity issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady makes use of government aircraft, and Democrats  
said the amendment was politically motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is petty and unchivalrous,'' said Rep. Zoe Lofgren,  
D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The use of government aircraft is far more costly than a  
first-class commercial airplane ticket, on which customary federal 
reimbursement rules are based. As first lady, Mrs. Clinton travels 
with a larger retinue than is customary challengers for federal 
office. These include not only her staff but Secret Service agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Voting in favor of the measure were 215 Republicans and 46  
Democrats. Opposed were 164 Democrats, two Republicans and one 
independent. 
</P>
<P>
	The provision was inserted into legislation to overhaul the  
campaign finance laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
