<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA OKs New Kidney Transplant Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- People receiving kidney transplants will have  
a new drug available to help prevent organ rejection. 
</P>
<P>
	Rapamune won approval Wednesday from the Food and Drug  
Administration as an addition to the drugs used to suppress the 
immune system in order to prevent rejection. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA termed the drug an important addition to the limited  
number of immunosupressants available for use in kidney 
transplants. It is made by Wyeth Ayerst Laboratories in 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Approval followed two clinical studies -- one involved 719  
patients in the United States, the other with 576 patients in 
Australia, Canada, Europe and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA said side effects of the drug included an increase in  
cholesterol in the blood, which required treatment with 
lipid-lowering drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said drug comes in liquid form and the daily dose can  
be mixed with water or orange juice. 
</P>
<P>
	Rapamune is taken along with cyclosporin, another  
immunosuppressant, and corticosteroids, which reduce inflammation 
and also suppress the immune system, the FDA added. 
</P>
<P>
	The approval comes as good news for Wyeth Ayerst's parent  
company, American Home Products. 
</P>
<P>
	AHP faces lawsuits over the diet drugs Redux and Pondimin and  
recently had a recall of subpotent emergency injection kits for 
severe allergic reactions. Last summer, the company had to stop 
selling a diarrheal vaccine while the government investigated a 
possible link to dangerous bowel obstructions. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
