<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dime Bancorp To Buy Hudson United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dime Bancorp Inc. is acquiring Hudson United  
Bancorp for $1.58 billion to create one of the largest regional 
banks in the Northeast with $32 billion in assets, the companies 
announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 330 branches of the combined bank will operate under the  
DimeBank name in New York, New Jersey, Connecticut and 
Pennsylvania. The parent company, Dime United Bancorp Inc., will be 
based in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence J. Toal, chairman and chief executive officer of Dime,  
said the new bank will ``have the resources to compete effectively 
as a top-tier regional bank in attracting new business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toal will keep his titles at the new bank for three years.  
Kenneth T. Neilson, currently chairman, president, and chief 
executive officer of Hudson United, will serve as president and 
chief operating officer of the combined company. Neilson will 
replace Toal on Jan. 1, 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	By combining operations, the Dime United expects to cut $78  
million in annual costs, though few branches are expected to close. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the terms of the agreement, a new common stock will be  
created and exchanged for shares in both companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders of Hudson United will get one share of Dime United,  
worth about $30.25, for each Hudson United they hold. Shareholders 
in Dime will receive 0.585 share in the new company, worth about 
$17.70, for each share of Dime. 
</P>
<P>
	After the deal closes early next year, Dime United will pay a $1  
per share cash dividend. 
</P>
<P>
	Dime will control 13 seats of the new board of directors, while  
Hudson United will get 12. 
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading, shares of Dime rose 18 3/4 cents to $17.93 3/4  
on the New York Stock Exchange, where shares of Hudson United were 
up 43 3/4 cents to $30.56 1/4. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
