<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China To Increase Deficit Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China will increase deficit spending in the next  
year to help pull the economy out of its deflationary spiral, a 
senior official said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The boosting of internal demand will be a long-term policy,''  
said Li Rongrong, vice chairman of the State Development Planning 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Li said China would issue more government bonds to ensure that  
projects begun under a $1.2 trillion state-backed spending program 
would be completed and put into operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Li declined to say how much additional debt would be issued,  
saying it would be determined by international and domestic 
economic factors. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the government issued 100 billion yuan ($12.10  
billion) in special treasury bonds to stimulate the economy. 
Earlier this month, Beijing sold an additional 60 billion yuan 
($7.27 billion) in special bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Li said that the increased debt will not create an intolerable  
burden for the government because sources of revenue are being 
improved and other spending has been cut through bureaucratic 
reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government has made arrangements for increasing revenue on  
the one hand and saving expenditure on the other,'' Li said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
