<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 08:03:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  DaimlerChrysler Has Big Tech Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler plans to invest more  
than $49 billion by 2001 to develop new technologies that would set 
it apart in the fiercely competitive auto market, the co-chairmen 
of the company said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The German-American automaker plans to introduce 64 new  
passenger car and commercial vehicle models worldwide before the 
year 2004, co-chairmen Robert Eaton and Juergen Schrempp said at a 
news conference at the Frankfurt International Motor Show. 
</P>
<P>
	The company revised upwards its full-year sales projection to  
$155 billion from $148 billion on the basis of increased sales in 
the first eight months of the year. The company said it will sell 
more than 1 million passenger cars for the first time from the 
Mercedes-Benz and Smart brands. 
</P>
<P>
	Schrempp said the company aims to ``set the pace for further  
consolidation of the auto industry,'' adding that ``no one knows 
how many companies will be left.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the United States, the executives said the next generation  
of sport utility vehicles, high-performance SUVs, are now in the 
works. There are also plans on the next series of models under the 
Jeep brand. 
</P>
<P>
	Both DaimlerChrysler leaders defended the company's Smart  
division, which produces tiny two-passenger cars that have had 
disappointing sales in their first year in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Smart is an innovative mobility concept which is more  
needed now than ever before,'' Eaton said. ``We believe in the 
future of Smart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the news conference, the two men posed for photographs in  
front of a new Smart convertible model. The new City-Cabrio, to be 
available in March, was unveiled at the show along with a new 
diesel version. 
</P>
<P>
	The potential future for Smart was shown in a concept roadster  
that breaks out of the boxy coupe shape of the original Smart. 
Schrempp also said ``we have ideas about four-seaters'' for the 
brand. 
</P>
<P>
	A diesel version of the Smart that gets 90 miles per gallon from  
a 0.8 liter direct injection diesel engine will sell for $10,100. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has no plans to sell Smart cars in the United  
States, however. 
</P>
<P>
	The resignation disclosed Tuesday of Lars Brorsen, the head of  
the Micro Compact Car subsidiary that makes the Smart, will not 
derail development of the brand, the executives said. A successor 
will be named later this week or early next week from inside the 
company, Schrempp said 
</P>
<P>
	The Frankfurt International Motor Show opens to the public  
Thursday, but automakers held media preview days Tuesday and today 
to showcase their latest models. 
</P>
<P>
	The Frankfurt show is typically a showcase for designs aimed at  
European demands: fuel efficiency and an ability to fit into tight 
parking spaces. Automakers emphasized the small bodies of their 
models while boasting of increased interior room for passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	Chrysler made moves to enter the European market in a stronger  
way with its brand, showing off its new Neon model and PT Cruiser 
and a concept Java design. 
</P>
<P>
	The Java, which is in the same aerodynamic ``one-box'' profile  
as many of the other new models, features rear seats that are 
positioned higher than the front. The design is similar to theater 
seating, giving back-seat passengers a better view of the road. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other announcements at the show Tuesday:  
</P>
<P>
	--Audi showed the new A2 with an all-alumimum body, making it 40  
percent lighter than if it were made of steel. 
</P>
<P>
	--VW tried to build on the success of the New Beetle in the  
United States by unveiling a lower-priced model, along with a 
higher-end turbo. The cheaper version cuts about $2,700 off the 
base price of $18,900. 
</P>
<P>
	VW's Concept D car gives a look at what a luxury car from the  
German automaker known for affordability would look like. The 
smooth contours of a sedan conceal a V-10 engine. 
</P>
<P>
	--BMW's Z8 roadster builds on the James Bond-appeal of its Z3.  
The car also comes with James Bond-like gadgets -- a 
``Multi-Information Radio'' allows drivers to use one control unit 
to operate the stereo, satellite navigation system and telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	The X5 takes aim at the frenzied sport utility vehicle-market in  
the United States. The frame is based on a passenger car, which the 
carmaker says maximizes safety in case of a crash. 
</P>
<P>
	--Porsche said it will announce in a few days where it plans to  
build a new sport utility vehicle. Porsche and VW have said they 
would jointly develop an SUV for a 2002 launch under both 
companies' different brands. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 08:03:09 </DATE_TIME>
