<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 19:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants Grass Decision Said Imminent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The New Jersey Sports and  
Exposition Authority and its tenants at Giants Stadium will meet 
Friday to discuss their second experiment with a grass field and 
the possibility of installing it on a full-time basis. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Giants of the NFL and the New York-New Jersey  
MetroStars of MLS said they would support a change from the current 
artificial turf to grass, but the question has been how the NFL's 
New York Jets would vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Injuries the past two weeks to quarterback Vinny Testaverde  
(Achilles'), receiver Wayne Chrebet (broken foot) and running back 
Leon Johnson (knee) while playing on the Astroturf might convince 
the Jets to make the switch. Testaverde and Johnson were both lost 
for the year in Sunday's season-opening loss to New England. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't know what their position is,'' Giants executive  
vice president John Mara said of the Jets on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mara said the Giants and MetroStars want grass, and that the  
authority will do what the teams want, provided the three agree. 
</P>
<P>
	While Mara hopes the teams and their landlord could finalize  
plans for a grass field on Friday, authority spokesman John 
Samerjan said that is unlikely. 
</P>
<P>
	``When they agreed to experiment with a grass field, it took  
them six months to make the deal,'' Samerjan said. ``I'm trying to 
lower the expectations. I think it will take a few more meetings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the teams agree to a grass surface, they then will have  
to agree to the costs for installing and maintaining it, Samerjan 
said. It is expected installation will cost about $1 million per 
team while maintenance is estimated at about $450,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The MetroStars put up almost $2 million to pay for the grass  
field experiments, team general manager Charlie Stillitano said. If 
a grass field were put in on a permanent basis, they would only 
have to pay a share of the annual upkeep. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark Companies of Delhi, N.Y., installed the two fields used in  
the grass experiments. Scott Clark, the president of the company, 
is also expected to attend Friday's meeting, which was called to 
review this second experiment with grass. 
</P>
<P>
	That experiment ran from the spring until late August.  
</P>
<P>
	The grass field, which consists of 6,000 trays of grass put over  
the existing artificial field, was put to its biggest test from 
Aug. 20-29 when four football games were played along with a 
MetroStars' game. 
</P>
<P>
	The grass in the middle of the field turned brown and the team  
logos painted in the end zones were a little worn toward the end of 
the last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Mara felt the field held up very well, considering the  
groundskeepers were told not to do anything to make the field look 
better, such as painting the grass. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the selling points of the tray system is that the most  
used portions of the field could be replaced up to three times 
during the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The current artificial surface would be kept, just in case  
something goes wrong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 07:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
