<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> T-Bills' Interest Rates Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The interest rate on 52-week Treasury bills  
rose in Tuesday's auction to the highest level since July. 
</P>
<P>
	The discount rate was 5.0 percent, up from 4.945 percent at the  
last auction on Aug. 17. It was the highest rate since 52-week 
bills sold for 5.095 percent on July 16. 
</P>
<P>
	The bills will carry an equivalent coupon interest rate of 5.285  
percent with each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,494.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales totaled $10 billion out of bids of $28.7 billion.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 15:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' Sehorn Playing Vs. Redskins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Cornerback Jason Sehorn worked out  
Wednesday without feeling any pain in his injured left hamstring 
and said there is a chance he will play in the New York Giants' 
home opener against the Washington Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	All Sehorn has to do now is convince coach Jim Fassel, which may  
not be so easy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have sat around enough,'' Sehorn said standing outside the  
Giants locker room. ``I am tired of watching football. I'd much 
rather play the game. In my eyes, if I am ready to go, I want to 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is still some question whether Sehorn is ready. After  
missing all of last season with a knee injury, he pulled his 
hamstring a week before training camp opened and did not get back 
on the field until Friday, two days before the Giants' 
season-opening 17-13 win over Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn ran -- if you can call it that -- a couple of plays with  
the Giants' scout team on Wednesday, but it wasn't much more than 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	And just to make sure it wasn't much more than that, Fassel had  
a trainer watch him every moment just to make sure he didn't do too 
much. 
</P>
<P>
	While he said he felt fine running, Sehorn admitted he still  
felt something in his hamstring. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to run full speed,'' he said. ``Someone has to test me  
in practice. That's not the same as game speed. It's running around 
but it's not the same. Once the game begins and I have a chance to 
run, we'll know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fassel has not pushed Sehorn to get back on the field, so it  
seems to be a stretch to think the coach would let him play this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Another factor weighing against a return would be the play of  
the defense last week. It limited the Buccaneers to 254 total 
yards. The secondary also picked off four Trent Dilfer passes. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Washington gained 504 yards in total offense  
in a 41-35 overtime loss to Dallas. Quarterback Brad Johnson 
completed 20 of 33 passes for 382 yards and two touchdowns. Michael 
Westbrook had five receptions for 159 yards and two TDs, while 
fellow receiver Albert Connell had four catches for 137 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Before his knee injury, Sehorn was one of the top cover corners  
in the league, capable of taking any receiver out of a game. 
</P>
<P>
	In his own mind, Sehorn rated his chances of playing at 75-25 in  
favor. He said that translates to 50-50 for the coaching staff, 
which is precisely the way the Giants listed him on their injury 
report Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'll play,'' Sehorn said. ``I have a little  
persuasiveness to me. I'm not returning kickoff. I don't have that 
much persuasiveness to me. I think if I am healthy enough to play, 
they will let me play. I can convince him, I have to be honest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn, who injured his knee last year experimenting on a  
kickoff return, said that at no point has he asked Fassel to play 
yet, saying he has not felt right. 
</P>
<P>
	But if he does this weekend, it will be because he feels ready  
to go. 
</P>
<P>
	``When a player tells you he can play, you go OK,'' Sehorn said.  
``You have to take his word for it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 11:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of Sept. 19-25:  
</P>
<P>
	60 years ago: Production began on Howard Hawks' ``His Girl  
Friday,'' with Rosalind Russell in the female lead. Russell 
replaced Jean Arthur, who refused to take the role. 
</P>
<P>
	50 years ago: Dean Martin and Jerry Lewis made their film debut  
in ``My Friend Irma.'' 
</P>
<P>
	45 years ago: Elvis Presley released ``Good Rockin' Tonight,''  
his version of a 1948 hit by Wynonie Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	And William Holden, Audrey Hepburn and Humphrey Bogart starred  
in ``Sabrina.'' 
</P>
<P>
	35 years ago: The Beatles played the final date of their U.S.  
tour at the Paramount in New York. Bob Dylan went backstage to 
visit. 
</P>
<P>
	And the spy spoof, ``The Man From U.N.C.L.E.,'' made its debut  
on NBC. The series starred Robert Vaughn and David McCallum. 
</P>
<P>
	30 years ago: Robert Redford and Paul Newman starred in ``Butch  
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	20 years ago: ``The Onion Field'' starred James Woods, John  
Savage and Ted Danson. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Dylan's ``Slow Train Coming,'' an album of religious songs,  
hit No. 3 on the charts. It was Dylan's second platinum album. 
</P>
<P>
	And John Huston's ``Wise Blood'' starred Harry Dean Stanton and  
Ned Beatty. 
</P>
<P>
	15 years ago: ``The Cosby Show,'' starring Bill Cosby, debuted  
on NBC. 
</P>
<P>
	And Tom Hulce and F. Murray Abraham starred in ``Amadeus.''  
Abraham won an Oscar for his performance. The film also won Oscars 
for Best Picture and Best Director. 
</P>
<P>
	10 years ago: The Library of Congress announced the first 25 of  
75 films named to a new national film registry. The first group 
included ``Gone With the Wind,'' ``The Maltese Falcon,'' ``Star 
Wars'' and ``Citizen Kane.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: Paul Newman donated $200,000 to the American Red  
Cross to help victims of the civil war in Rwanda. The money came 
from after-tax profits of Newman's Own, the food company that 
supports various charities. 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: Oprah Winfrey topped Essence magazine's list of  
the nation's wealthiest African-American women. Winfrey had an 
estimated $550 million in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	And the heavy metal rock group White Zombie announced its  
breakup. The statement said: ``After 13 years, White Zombie has 
accomplished everything we set out to do and we all felt it was 
time to move on.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken 10 years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't follow it. Most of it is terrible.'' -- Former Police  
guitarist Andy Summers, referring to rock 'n' roll. 

</P>
<P>
	Five years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm being punished for being a single female, for having  
power, and being rich and saying the things I say, being a sexual 
creature -- actually not being any different from anyone else.'' -- 
Singer Madonna. 

</P>
<P>
	``Now that I'm famous, no one has to think of me as a Vietnamese  
hair product.'' -- Actor Charlie Sheen. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken one year ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``Most actors today are versatile, but they don't have that  
particular star quality that makes them unique.'' -- Film director 
Peter Bogdanovich. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 00:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cowboys Are Lett-Less for 8 Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- When the Dallas Cowboys put together their  
defensive depth chart in April, it looked pretty good. Midway 
through September, it's a mess. 
</P>
<P>
	Scratch out starting strongside linebacker Quentin Coryatt, who  
decided Tuesday he won't play this season. Nagging injuries likely 
have forced the No. 2 overall pick of the 1992 draft into 
retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Put a thin line through defensive tackle Leon Lett, who made the  
Pro Bowl last year. Lett was suspended June 4 for his fifth 
violation of the league's substance abuse policy and learned 
Tuesday he'll have to miss the first eight games. He can return for 
the Nov. 14 home game against Green Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Circle cornerbacks Deion Sanders and Kevin Smith and put  
question marks next to their names. Sanders is recovering from a 
severely sprained left big toe and Smith has a bad back. When 
either will return is a mystery. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coryatt news was a bit surprising, but not totally  
unexpected considering he hadn't worn pads since early in training 
camp. Among his aches and pains were a reconstructed shoulder and a 
strained Achilles' tendon. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had several candid discussions over the last several  
weeks,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said. ``We really wanted him to 
get comfortable in his mind with where he was with his injuries. He 
arrived at the decision that he will not be playing this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas had been playing a waiting game with the NFL regarding  
Lett. Commissioner Paul Tagliabue had told Jones he'd set the 
suspension by the opener, but took an extra week. 
</P>
<P>
	The length of Lett's previous suspensions were set by the  
league's substance abuse policy. This one was at the commissioner's 
discretion and could have been a lifetime ban. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones was hoping for a four-game punishment, the same Tagliabue  
gave the previous five-time offender, but he ended up doubling that 
in what will likely be a precedent-setting decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``The commissioner was looking for a long-term way to handle  
these types of circumstances,'' Jones said. ``I think that's what 
caused the delay. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was looking to potentially establish a standard that would  
publicly point out the seriousness and importance the league is 
placing in this area of substance abuse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tagliabue told Jones this suspension was half as long as Lett's  
previous penalty partly because he's cooperated with the after-care 
program. He'd been tested up 10 times a month for the last two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Leon was rewarded for some of the things he has been doing,''  
Jones said. ``His genuine participation in the program, his 
continued improvement, earned him the right to get to play this 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders practiced last week in hopes of playing in the  
season-opener Sunday in Washington. Instead, he watched from the 
sidelines as the Redskins passed for 382 yards. Dallas' offense 
bailed out the defense with a miraculous comeback for a 41-35 
overtime victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders may try to return Monday night against the Atlanta  
Falcons -- a prime time game against his former team, who also are 
the reigning NFC champions. But with the Cowboys having a bye the 
following weekend, there's a good chance he won't return until an 
Oct. 3 home game against Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants to see himself do more in practice and on the field  
before the game,'' coach Chan Gailey said. ``When he goes in, he 
wants to play at 100 percent, not 60 percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's status is still being resolved. Recovering from a disc  
injury without surgery is tricky. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 17:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Injury Ends Big Unit's Record Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- A sore shoulder, combined with Arizona's  
comfortable lead in the NL West, has spoiled Randy Johnson's 
longshot chance to break Nolan Ryan's record for most strikeouts in 
a season. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who has pitched more innings than any other hurler in  
baseball this year, sat out his scheduled start Wednesday night and 
won't pitch again until Saturday against Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	That means he will have only three more starts this season. He  
needs 49 strikeouts to break Ryan's 26-year-old record of 383. 
That's just over 16 strikeouts a game, a rate that seems beyond 
even the considerable reach of the 6-foot-10 left-hander. 
</P>
<P>
	The soreness isn't serious, and Johnson said trainers and  
doctors told him he could have pitched without a significant risk. 
But manager Buck Showalter decided he'd rather be cautious because 
Johnson probably will be counted on for two starts in the first 
round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told Buck that I felt I was capable of going out and  
throwing a quality game, but a few more extra days won't hurt 
either,'' Johnson said. ``I'm probably doing myself a favor and the 
team a favor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson has insisted all along that the strikeout record is not  
a big deal to him. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I struck out a dozen more people this year but I won the  
last four starts of the year, that's going to make me happy,'' he 
said earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Probably no statistic in baseball this season is more misleading  
than Johnson's 15-9 record. In seven of those losses, his teammates 
failed to provide him with more than two runs, including an 
incredible stretch when the Diamondbacks were shut out in four of 
his starts in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	In those four shutouts, Johnson had an earned-run average of  
1.41. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's numbers you don't see,'' Johnson said, ``like a  
stretch where I had 14 consecutive starts where I gave up two or 
less runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing close to that had happened to Johnson before.  
</P>
<P>
	``In 35 starts, I may have pitched 14 quality starts like that,  
but not consecutive starts,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson is the runaway leader in the majors with 335 strikeouts,  
surpassing his career high of 329 set last year with Seattle and 
Houston. He also leads both leagues in innings pitched at 249 2-3, 
and complete games with 11. He leads the National League with a 
2.52 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	But he knows that victories are what's important, which is why  
he must have been so frustrated during the stretch when his team 
wasn't scoring runs for him. But he never criticized his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``My job is based on winning, not strikeouts, not ERA, because  
ERAs are so inflated now they aren't even really talked about 
anymore,'' Johnson said. ``But wins are, and wins are how I'm 
evaluated at the end of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Johnson signed a four-year, $52.4 million contract with  
Arizona in the offseason, there were raised eyebrows around the 
league. He was 35 at the time. He's since turned 36, and many felt 
he was past his prime. 
</P>
<P>
	But his slider has been as wicked as ever this year, his  
fastball still tops 100 mph in the ninth inning, and he is just 5 
2-3 innings short of his career high of 255 1-3 innings pitched. 
His control has never been better. In 32 starts, he is averaging 
just over 11 strikeouts a game. He has walked just 66, or just over 
two per game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have more control of my pitches now,'' Johnson said. ``I  
know how to set up hitters now. That comes from maturity, watching 
the game, studying the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter has found Johnson to be even more impressive than  
advertised. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think his command is the thing that continues to impress me,  
and his stamina,'' Showalter said. ``Sometimes we don't realize how 
tough it is to do the things that he's doing. You try not to take 
things for granted or assume anything, but he just continues to do 
it outing after outing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And every fifth day, Arizona's players have known the intensity  
level would be raised a notch as Johnson sits in his locker, facing 
the wall, before taking the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going over the hitters. I'm visualizing. I almost put  
myself in a trance,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The day the Big Unit pitches is unlike any other.  
</P>
<P>
	``I can't explain what it is,'' said Damian Miller, who has  
caught all but four of Johnson's starts, ``but every fifth day it 
seems like the world stops.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
