<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Floyd Spurs Tax Deadline Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taxpayers affected by Hurricane Floyd who had  
estimated tax payments due Wednesday have gotten a 15-day extension 
from the Internal Revenue Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS said affected taxpayers with corporate, partnership or  
fiduciary returns that were due Wednesday also can file by Sept. 30 
without penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS cannot extend deadlines for employment or excise tax  
deposits, but will cancel penalties on deposits required from 
Tuesday to Sept. 22 if those deposits are made by Oct. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS said it also would suspend some enforcement activities,  
such as audits, levies and seizures, until Oct. 15 for taxpayers in 
federal disaster areas designated by President Clinton. Taxpayers 
in such areas -- Florida, Georgia, North Carolina and South 
Carolina, as of Wednesday -- may claim uninsured casualty losses on 
either amended 1998 tax returns on their 1999 forms. 
</P>
<P>
	Taxpayers seeking such relief should put ``Hurricane Floyd'' at  
the top of their returns. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
