<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Computers Used To Forecast Floyd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- All indications from the high-tech ocean buoys, the  
satellite images and the $45 million storm plane were that 
Hurricane Floyd would just brush the Florida coast. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's pretty much what happened.  
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the computer models were so consistent about the turn  
to the north that forecasters at the National Hurricane Center came 
close to declaring that Floyd would miss Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, they played it safe. While maintaining the storm would  
head north before rolling ashore, the forecasters warned residents 
all along Florida's east coast to gather supplies, protect their 
homes and head to higher ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``As it turns out, the hurricane moved pretty much as expected  
along the forecasted track,'' hurricane specialist Ed Rappaport 
said Wednesday. ``But if we had been off by 50 miles or so, if it 
had been 50 miles farther to the west, there would've been a direct 
impact on Florida.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Improvements in technology, combined with a wealth of past  
experience, have helped forecasters predict storm tracks with 
greater accuracy over the past few decades. 
</P>
<P>
	A generation ago, the three-day forecast was off by somewhere  
between 400 and 450 miles. That's now down to 200 to 250 miles, 
Rappaport said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the forecasters are slow to congratulate themselves.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're almost afraid of people thinking we're better than we  
are because then they don't allow for error,'' said Jerry Jarrell, 
director of the National Hurricane Center. ``And forecasts are just 
forecasts. They're not the gospel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not yet.  
</P>
<P>
	Computers that line two rooms inside the hurricane center in  
Miami are used by forecasters who must decide the most likely route 
a storm will take. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of readings of wind, air pressure, humidity, light,  
cloud cover and other variable are collected from around the world 
and put into computer models, based in Princeton, N.J., Washington 
and Britain. Forecasters then study those models to plot a 
hurricane's path. 
</P>
<P>
	A critical ingredient is past experience. Computer models that  
are found to be accurate are used again. 
</P>
<P>
	``The premise that we use is that the future is going to behave  
like the past,'' said hurricane center meteorologist Todd 
Kimberlain. 
</P>
<P>
	A big reason for increased accuracy in the past three years is  
the information gathered by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric 
Administration's high-altitude jet, dubbed ``Gonzo'' after the 
Muppet character. Gonzo flies miles above the storm and drops 
hundreds of small, information-gathering capsules into the storm, 
then relays the data back to forecasters. 
</P>
<P>
	It was that information that really helped forecasters predict  
with confidence Floyd would turn to the north. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the data went into the models and they kept telling us,  
`Floyd is going to turn and soon,''' Kimberlain said. 
</P>
<P>
	The aircraft makes more frequent flights, which means more  
accurate forecasts and better ways of predicting whether residents 
should pack up and head out. 
</P>
<P>
	But forecasters say there's no time in sight when humans won't  
be needed to make the call. 
</P>
<P>
	``Computer models and simulations have improved, but for the  
last four or five years the average error of the hurricane center 
forecast has been smaller than error for any of the computer 
models,'' Rappaport said. ``Which indicates that the experience and 
talent of the hurricane forecasters is critical.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Emergency officials rely on forecasters in deciding when to  
order evacuations and when to say it is safe to return home. 
Forecasters must keep in mind that about $1 million a day in 
revenue is lost for every mile of coastline that is forced to 
evacuate. They also have to keep in mind the risks of deciding 
against an evacuation. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a really awful position to be in,'' Kimberlain said.  
``You don't want to come back after the fact of people dying and 
say, `I wish we had done that.''' 
</P>
<P>
	In the case of Floyd, the storm's tremendous size and strength  
posed a forecasting challenge. Small storms often are steered by 
the winds in their area, but storms as big as Floyd can actually 
change their environment. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrell said forecasters are slow to congratulate themselves on  
an accurate forecast because some storms are just easier than 
others. Dennis, for example, made a bizarre loop off the coast of 
North Carolina last month that forecasters had a bit of trouble 
predicting. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd and the upcoming Gert, however, both appear to be pretty  
straight-forward. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe we're getting good because the storms have been easier  
and the seasons have been easier than the skill increasing,'' 
Jarrell said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
