<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Prices Rise 0.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer prices rose 0.3 percent in August as  
gasoline and other energy products shot up for a second straight 
month. But elsewhere inflation remained a no-show with clothing 
prices down for a fourth straight month and airline fares 
retreating after a big jump in July. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said today the August increase in its  
Consumer Price Index -- the most closely watched inflation gauge -- 
matched the 0.3 percent July advance. 
</P>
<P>
	In both months, energy was the big force pushing prices upward.  
For August, two-thirds of the total price increase was attributed 
to a 2.7 percent surge in energy costs. Food costs rose a much more 
modest 0.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside of the volatile energy and food categories, prices were  
up just 0.1 percent in August. 
</P>
<P>
	This performance of the ``core'' rate of inflation was even  
better than economists' expectations and will provide ammunition 
for those arguing there is no need for the Federal Reserve to boost 
interest rates for a third time. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets rallied on the price figures with rising  
demand in inflation-sensitive bond market sending yields on 30-year 
Treasury bonds down to 6.08 percent this morning from 6.12 percent 
late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Commerce Department said that  
inventories held by businesses on shelves and backlots rose by 0.3 
percent in July while business sales rose at an even faster 0.4 
percent clip. 
</P>
<P>
	That left the ratio of inventories to sales at a record low of  
1.34 months, meaning it would take that length of time to exhaust 
supplies at the current sales pace. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, consumer prices have been rising at an annual  
rate of 2.6 percent, compared to a gain of just 1.6 percent for all 
of 1998. However, all of the increase reflects higher energy costs, 
which have rebounded this year after a steep plunge in 1998 that 
reflected slumping global demand in the wake of steep recessions in 
many nations hit by a global currency crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy costs have risen at a 15.4 percent annual rate through  
August this year after having fallen 8.8 percent for all of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve boosted short-term interest rates by  
one-half percentage point over the summer. Fed Chairman Alan 
Greenspan and other Fed officials expressed concerns about the need 
to slow the U.S. economy to a more sustainable pace so that the 
lowest unemployment rates in three decades don't trigger 
inflationary wage demands. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Fed critics have said the central bank is fighting a  
phantom foe with no signs that inflation is getting out of hand. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2.7 percent jump in energy costs was even bigger than July's  
2.1 percent increase. Gasoline prices advanced 5.6 percent last 
month and are up 25.1 percent at an annual rate so far this year. 
But even with the surge, pump prices remain 9.8 percent below their 
peak reached in November 1990 after Iraq invaded Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	The 0.2 percent rise in food prices in August matched the modest  
July increase. In August, prices fell for beef, pork and fresh 
fruits. Vegetable prices were up 2.2 percent even though tomato 
prices fell by 9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Clothing prices fell by 0.3 percent, the fourth consecutive  
drop, as discounts for clothing for men and boys offset increases 
for women and girls. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline fares fell by 2.7 percent in August after having posted  
a sharp 6.5 percent increase in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Medical care costs were up 0.4 percent in August and now stand  
3.4 percent higher than a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Recreation costs, however, were unchanged for a third  
consecutive month as increases for cable television, athletic 
lessons and club memberships were offset by declines for toys, pet 
services and tickets for movies, theater and sporting events. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
