<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> London Theater: Veteran Stars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Veteran stars, new plays and the British premiere  
of the Disney smash musical ``The Lion King'' are among the theater 
offerings on tap for London this fall, an attempt to reverse what 
many have seen as a sluggish year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a less-than-colorful summer,'' conceded Bill  
Kenwright, the West End producer of ``Blood Brothers'' and many 
other shows. ``I think the autumn's going to be fascinating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It certainly will be busy.  
</P>
<P>
	Between now and Christmas, as many as 40 major openings will be  
competing for audiences. They range from highbrow, limited-run 
revivals (Tara Fitzgerald in Sophocles' ``Antigone,'' opening Oct. 
11 at the Old Vic) to the European debut of the Tony-winning ``Lion 
King,'' a $10 million behemoth that bows Oct. 19 at the Lyceum. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does feel like an incredible occasion,'' said Josette  
Bushell-Mingo, the Londoner who stars as the shaman Rafiki in the 
musical. Director Julie Taymor's 46-strong cast is entirely 
separate from the ensemble that opened to ecstatic reviews on 
Broadway nearly two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	This version, Bushell-Mingo said, is for people who cannot go to  
New York or Tokyo, where the show also can be seen. ``Everyone is 
open to the fact that this is a new English ensemble,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many major London musicals -- the Broadway transfer of ``Fosse,''  
for example -- are waiting until 2000 to escape the shadow of ``The 
Lion King,'' which sold out long ago. But an array of other new 
plays and revivals are available. 
</P>
<P>
	The musicals that are braving concurrent debuts tend to be as  
modest as ``The Lion King'' is huge (``Spend, Spend, Spend,'' with 
one-time ``Blood Brothers'' star Barbara Dickson, opening Oct. 12 
at the Piccadilly) or retreads of time-tested warhorses (``The 
Pajama Game,'' with sets by American artist Frank Stella, opening 
Oct. 4 at the Victoria Palace). 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Ayckbourn, the prolific English playwright who turned 60  
this year, opens play No. 53 at the Lyric Theater on Oct. 13. Its 
name, like most Ayckbourn material, is ``Comic Potential.'' It 
pairs English actress Janie Dee with David Soul, who starred on TV 
in ``Starsky and Hutch'' and now lives in London. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about the nature of being human -- the nature of love, the  
nature of laughter,'' writer-director Ayckbourn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other veteran dramatists joining Ayckbourn on the West End this  
fall include Ronald Harwood, with ``Quartet,'' and Alan Bennett, 
with ``The Lady in the Van.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think one has to be avant-garde all the time or  
revolutionary,'' said Harwood, the 65-year-old author of the play 
and subsequent film ``The Dresser.'' ``One simply wants to write 
plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newly opened at the Albery, ``Quartet'' takes a comic yet rueful  
look at four retired opera singers living in an English old age 
home. Donald Sinden stands out as an indomitably randy baritone 
determined to bluff and bluster his way to the grave. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett's play opens Dec. 7 at the Queen's. Its star is Maggie  
Smith, heading a cast of 12 in the role of the real-life woman who 
parked her van in Bennett's north London garden and lived in it for 
years until she died. 
</P>
<P>
	Helen Mirren opens in late November at a theater to be  
confirmed, inheriting Uta Hagen's off-Broadway role as a legendary 
writer in American dramatist Donald Margulies' ``Collected 
Stories.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anne-Marie Duff completes the cast of two under the direction of  
Howard Davies, who had a Broadway smash this past season staging 
Kevin Spacey in ``The Iceman Cometh.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zoe Wanamaker, a Broadway sensation in ``Electra,'' stars in a  
historical drama, ``Battle Royal,'' from English writer Nick 
Stafford. Opening Dec. 8 at the Royal National Theater's Lyttelton, 
the play also features Brendan Coyle, the tenderly observant 
bartender in the acclaimed Irish play ``The Weir'' by Conor 
McPherson. 
</P>
<P>
	McPherson opens his next play in December at the Royal Court  
Theater in Sloane Square, which has been rebuilt at a cost of about 
$40 million. Entitled ``Dublin Carol,'' the play stars Brian Cox, 
an alumnus of McPherson's solo show, ``St. Nicholas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joining ``Antigone'' as an eagerly awaited revival is a new  
staging of Sean O'Casey's Irish classic ``Juno and the Paycock,'' 
with film and TV actor Colm Meaney (``The Commitments,'' ``Star 
Trek: Deep Space Nine'') marking a rare return to the British 
stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``The play doesn't need rewriting,'' said Meaney, the  
46-year-old Irishman whose home is Los Angeles, explaining his 
attraction to the project. Director John Crowley's revival opens a 
six-week run Sept. 20 at the studio-sized Donmar Warehouse. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't need fixing. It's sort of there,'' Meaney said,  
``so I thought, `Why not?''' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 14:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steelers' Stewart Writes Own Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- They've changed just about everything in the  
Pittsburgh Steelers' offense -- the formations and the pass routes, 
the blocking assignments and the blitz protection, even the 
philosophy of the play calling. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest change of all might be in the quarterback, and not  
just because Kordell Stewart is no longer chained to the pocket, 
discouraged from taking off running or creating on the fly. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since Stewart became the Steelers' starter in  
1997, he can check off plays at the line of scrimmage. After being 
forced for two years to run only the plays called by offensive 
coordinators Chan Gailey and Ray Sherman, he is free to adjust the 
play to the defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if he does so to extreme.  
</P>
<P>
	Steelers coach Bill Cowher was encouraged by every aspect of  
Stewart's play in Sunday's 43-0 rout of Cleveland -- his running and 
throwing, his recognition of the defense and on-the-fly adjustments 
-- except for his frequent use of timeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart used up all three of the Steelers' first half timeouts  
by the end of the first quarter as he attempted to alter plays at 
the line of scrimmage, only to run out of time on the play clock. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart says it won't happen again. Cowher jokes that it had  
better not, if only because the lack of timeouts left the Steelers 
unable to challenge any disputed calls. Under the NFL's new instant 
replay system, a team loses a timeout if a replayed call is upheld, 
so it must have a timeout left in order to challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good news was that I could get rid of that thing you use  
to challenge plays. I didn't have to worry about it,'' Cowher said. 
``But you don't want to burn those timeouts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The answer? Cowher and new offensive coordinator Kevin Gilbride  
emphasized to Stewart that it is usually better to run the play 
that was called than to call a timeout that might be needed later 
in the half. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's probably the first time we've given Kordell a lot of  
leeway in trying to get in and out of calls,'' Cowher said. ``I 
liked what I saw. We just have to get out of the huddle faster, so 
he will have more time to get in and out of the play. We want to 
make sure we don't start utilizing those timeouts, particularly in 
the second half when they become very important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That Stewart finally has the latitude that many NFL quarterbacks  
already possess underscores how committed the Steelers are to 
getting him back on his game. 
</P>
<P>
	The catalyst of an offense that was unpredictable and big  
play-driven in 1997, largely because of Stewart's ability to cross 
up defenses with his running, Stewart felt severely restricted in 
Sherman's offense a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, he ran for only two touchdowns, or nine fewer than  
in 1997. His passing yardage dropped from 3,020 yards to 2,560; his 
TD passes declined from 21 to 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Without any provocation from their opponents, the Steelers last  
year effectively eliminated the man known as Slash from their 
playbook. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was totally different last year,'' wide receiver Hines Ward  
said. ``If we had a play called, there was no way to adjust. If we 
had a play called and the defense wasn't right to run it, we still 
ran it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
