<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Dollar Hits 3-Year Low Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar plumbed a 3 1/2-year low against the  
Japanese yen for the second day in a row Wednesday as traders sold 
dollars in a continued reaction to strong U.S. trade deficit 
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar, which dropped for the fourth straight day against  
the yen, was mixed against other major currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 104.23 yen in New York late Wednesday,  
down from 105.79 yen late Tuesday and its lowest closing level 
since Feb. 27, 1996. The dollar fell as low as 103.20 yen in Europe 
earlier in the day. Japanese markets were closed for a national 
holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the dollar bounced a little Wednesday after the  
Labor Department reported that the nation's consumer price index 
rose a moderate 0.3 percent in August. That was in line with Wall 
Street expectations and suggested that the Federal Reserve may not 
have to raise interest rates for a third time this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in the day, U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said  
the outlook for the U.S. economy remains promising, even though the 
dollar has continued to weaken in foreign-exchange markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Holders of U.S. dollars got ``no encouragement from Larry  
Summers,'' said Ricardo Gomes, head of foreign exchange at Republic 
National Bank in New York. Many traders read Summers to mean that 
the United States was unlikely to intervene in the markets to prop 
up the dollar but rather will rely on the strong U.S. economy to 
keep its currency aloft, Gomes said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar had fallen Tuesday after the U.S. government posted a  
record current-account trade deficit of $80.7 billion in the second 
quarter of this year, including a $6.3 billion deficit with Japan 
for the month of June alone. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted late Wednesday at $1.0396, up from $1.0354  
Tuesday. The British pound was quoted at $1.6147, up from $1.6072. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday,  
included 1.5434 Swiss francs, down from 1.5486; 1.4757 Canadian 
dollars, up from 1.4754. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8811 German marks, down from 1.8890; 
6.3091 French francs, down from 6.3182; 1.862.34 Italian lire, down 
from 1,865.03. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 12:20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Housing Bill Gets Negative Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bipartisan bill designed to increase  
homeownership earned a negative appraisal Wednesday from the 
assistant housing secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	William Apgar, assistant secretary at the Department of Housing  
and Urban Development, said the bill's harmful provisions ``far 
outweigh the positive -- and for that reason, the administration 
cannot endorse this legislation at this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Apgar told the House Banking Committee's housing and community  
opportunity panel that the administration supports the measure's 
attempt to make home-buying easier by untangling the web of federal 
regulations that can drive up prices. 
</P>
<P>
	And he applauded a proposal for the sale of government-owned  
properties to teachers for half of the market price. HUD Secretary 
Andrew Cuomo recently announced such a program, and sales are to 
begin within weeks, Apgar said. 
</P>
<P>
	But ``possibly the worst'' aspect of the bill, he said, is a  
proposal that would require HUD to offer its vacant or sub-par 
properties to local governments or community-based development 
corporations at steep discounts. 
</P>
<P>
	That could cost the Federal Housing Administration -- the  
government corporation that insures mortgages -- more than $3 
billion, said Apgar, who is also FHA commissioner. The program is 
also unnecessary, he said, because HUD already sells the properties 
at a discount. 
</P>
<P>
	Apgar called for inclusion of a provision that would let local  
officials use certain housing grants to help uniformed city workers 
buy homes where they are employed, ensuring that scarce funds reach 
those who need them most. 
</P>
<P>
	The national homeownership rate reached a high of 66 percent  
last year, but Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., the bill's sponsor and 
housing subcommittee chairman, said the American dream of owning a 
home was still just a dream for too many. 
</P>
<P>
	Other bill provisions would:  
</P>
<P>
	--Let residents and public housing authorities use rental  
vouchers -- used to pay rents -- for a down payment on a house or for 
mortgage payments. 
</P>
<P>
	--Create uniform standards and construction codes to improve the  
quality, safety and affordability of manufactured homes, which are 
built in factories and shipped to retail locations. 
</P>
<P>
	--Require a congressional study of the inspection process for FHA  
properties. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1776.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
