<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patagonia Founder Steps Down As CEO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VENTURA, Calif. (AP) -- The founder of the company that makes  
Patagonia outdoor clothing, famed alpinist Yvon Chouinard, is 
stepping down as chief executive officer to spend more time 
pursuing his two passions: surfing and mountain climbing. 
</P>
<P>
	Chouinard is stepping aside ``to do more of the things he likes  
to do outdoors,'' company spokeswoman Lu Setnicka said Wednesday. 
Chouinard, 60, will still own Patagonia's parent company, the Lost 
Arrow Corp. based in Ventura, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always managed this company as if it's going to be here  
for the next 100 years. It's time for me to step away from 
day-to-day operations and put people in place to ensure the 
company's continued success,'' Chouinard said in a statement to 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Crooke, most recently CEO at Pearl Izumi, a cycling and  
sports apparel company in Colorado, was named chief executive 
officer. He will move to Ventura in mid-October. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Patagonia's mail order, retail, wholesale and  
international divisions sold $180 million worth of products. Lost 
Arrow also has subsidiaries Lotus Designs, manufacturer of paddling 
products, and Water Girl, a women's surf-oriented sportswear firm. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
