<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 15:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola To Buy General Instrument </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Motorola Inc. is buying General Instrument Corp.  
for $10.66 billion in stock, uniting two technologies that may 
speed sweeping changes in home entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola, best known for making cellular phones and pagers, is  
making a bold push into the future of cable television, which will 
include a variety of ``broadband'' applications, including Internet 
access, high-definition television and telephone service. 
</P>
<P>
	General Instrument dominates the market for cable TV set-top  
boxes -- one of the key ingredients for delivering broadband 
services to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the most significant moves our company has ever  
made,'' said Edward D. Breen, chairman and chief executive officer 
of General Instrument, who will head Motorola's new broadband 
division under the deal announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	General Instrument controls 72 percent of the North American  
market for set-top boxes, according to Allied Business Intelligence 
Inc., a technology research company. Allied estimates the number of 
set-top boxes in North American homes is expected to skyrocket from 
about 20 million today to 113 million over the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	But the strongest demand is expected to come from overseas  
markets and ``will be the key to our growth and our business,'' 
Breen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's deal will likely be the first of many in the  
communication equipment industry. Companies like Scientific-Atlanta 
Inc., Lucent Technologies Inc., and Nortel Networks Corp. may be 
looking for partners. 
</P>
<P>
	The trend reflects the merger frenzy among the cable and  
television operators. Companies like AT&AMP;T Corp., which is now the 
largest cable as well as the biggest long-distance telephone 
company, can put pressure on equipment suppliers to cut prices or 
offer more products. 
</P>
<P>
	Leo Hindery, head of AT&AMP;T's Broadband and Internet Services,  
even had a hand in bringing about Motorola's acquisition of General 
Instrument. AT&AMP;T owns 20 percent of General Instrument. 
</P>
<P>
	``I gave some input how the combined company might be more  
powerful together than standing apart,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the deal holds promise for consumers, some investors  
and analysts had concerns about the terms of the deal. General 
Instrument shareholders will get about $49.81 in Motorola stock, 
that is 0.575 of a share, for each share of General Instrument they 
hold. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had the capability to hold out for a better price,'' said  
Anton Wahlman, an analyst for Warburg Dillon Read. ``I thought the 
price would have been somewhere in the low $60s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	General Instrument's Breen defended the price, saying it still  
offered investors a premium to the stock price just a few weeks 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, General Instrument's shares fell 6.4 percent, or by $3.22  
21/32 to $47.27 11/32 on the New York Stock Exchange, where 
Motorola ended off 7 percent, or by $6.56 1/4 at $86.62 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will have more products to sell at cheaper  
prices with a wider marketing reach. And using the Motorola brand 
name, the new technology could quickly earn consumers' trust. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadband programs and services will not only be available for  
televisions, but also for wireless phones, hand-held computers, 
video games and other devices. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key thing is this is going to be an appliance that  
provides an ability to access broadband information from any 
place,'' said Ragu Gurumurthy, a principal with the consulting firm 
Booz-Allen &AMP; Hamilton. ``Motorola can create different types of 
devices people can carry with them to access broadband services 
from the train, beach or hotel. You don't have to ever be tethered 
to anything.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 11:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Owners: No Vote on Expos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- Baseball owners will not vote this week  
on the proposed sale of the Montreal Expos, team president Claude 
Brochu said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Proposed deals for the Cincinnati Reds, Kansas City Royals and  
Oakland Athletics remain on the agenda, with the Reds' sale likely 
to pass, according to a senior baseball official speaking on the 
condition he not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear whether transactions involving the Royals and  
Athletics would be approved or put off, the official said before 
the start of today's ownership committee meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Montreal's situation is tied to a new ballpark. While New York  
art dealer Jeffrey Loria heads a group that wants to buy the team 
from Brochu's group, baseball will not bring the deal to a vote 
until stadium financing is in place. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything has to be signed, sealed and delivered,'' Brochu  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	While a group in northern Virginia has been interested in buying  
the Expos, baseball commissioner Bud Selig has said his first 
choice is to keep the team in Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	The current plan is for the government to help finance a  
ballpark by using about $5.3 million a year in tourism funds for 
20-30 years to back a $67 million bond issue. 
</P>
<P>
	While owners originally intended to meet for two days, there was  
a chance they would end tonight, because of concerns about getting 
home with Hurricane Floyd heading north. 
</P>
<P>
	The $67 million sale of a controlling interest in the Reds from  
Marge Schott to three of the team's limited partners headed the 
list of deals for owners to consider. 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Lindner, who owns the Great American Insurance Co., will  
take over as the controlling owner from Schott, who repeatedly has 
infuriated baseball with inflammatory statements about minorities 
and women. The deal, in which 36.7 percent of the Reds' shares 
would be sold, values the franchise at $181.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	George Strike and William Reik, two of the Reds' current limited  
partners, are helping fund Lindner's bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Save Mart Foods chairman Bob Piccinini is the lead investor in a  
group reached a $122.4 million agreement in May to purchase the 
Athletics from Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann for $122.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Piccinini's group, put together by former A's executive Andy  
Dolich, includes Hall of Famer Reggie Jackson, must close on the 
deal by the end of the season or it expires. Oakland Mayor Jerry 
Brown has lobbied Selig and even considered coming to Cooperstown 
but decided against it, Brown spokeswoman Stacey Wells said. 
</P>
<P>
	During his meeting with the ownership committee, Piccinini  
emphasized his group's attributes, not the deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``Baseball, I don't think, reacts very positively to threats,''  
Piccinini said. 
</P>
<P>
	New York investor Miles Prentice agreed Nov. 13 to buy the  
Royals for $75 million from a trust that acquired the franchise 
following the death of founder Ewing Kauffman in 1993. But some 
baseball officials are concerned Prentice's group doesn't have 
enough money to operate the team successfully and some are worried 
his group, which has more 40 investors, is too large. 
</P>
<P>
	Owners are expected to vote on a restructuring plan that would  
reduce the American and National league presidents to figureheads 
by shifting control of umpires, player discipline and scheduling to 
the commissioner's office. 
</P>
<P>
	NL president Len Coleman, angry with the change, intends to  
resign after the World Series, several high-ranking baseball 
officials said last week and an announcement could be made at the 
meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	The intentions of AL president Gene Budig, who has been a less  
forceful presence than Coleman, are not known. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, baseball officials told the players' association  
they will examine the idea of a World Cup more closely in the next 
two months before deciding whether to go ahead with a tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll know more in about six weeks,'' union head Donald Fehr  
said after the annual meeting of the international committee 
established by players and owners in their 1996 labor agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball officials have talked for a decade about a World Cup, a  
tournament with major leaguers who would play for national teams 
from the United States, Japan and other countries. Fehr said 
discussions had not yet progressed to the point where the sides had 
even begun to think about when to start the event or even a format. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball plans to increase its international presence by  
starting the 2000 season in Tokyo with two games between the 
Chicago Cubs and New York Mets on March 29-30. They would be the 
first regular season games played outside North America. 
</P>
<P>
	After having the Baltimore Orioles play an exhibition game in  
Cuba in March, the first by a major league team in 40 years, 
baseball opened outside the United States and Canada for the first 
time when San Diego played Colorado in April at Monterrey, Mexico. 
The Padres and Mets played a three-game series in Monterrey in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball officials are discussing a more widespread program of  
exhibition games in the Caribbean next spring, but it's too early 
to determine if there will be a return trip to Cuba, according to 
one official familiar with the meeting who spoke on the condition 
he not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	The owners' meeting, the first since January, are dominated by  
franchise sales and a restructuring plan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
