<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Heavy rain and thunderstorms from Hurricane Floyd pounded the  
East Coast Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind gusts to 40 mph and heavy rain hit parts of North Carolina,  
South Carolina, southeastern Georgia and northeastern Florida. The 
heaviest rainfall was in the Carolinas, where it fell at the rate 
of 1 to 2 inches per hour, making flooding a threat. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere across the East, tropical moisture from Floyd  
interacted with a stationary front extending from Maine to Florida, 
causing a steady line of rain showers and thunderstorms from New 
England into the Carolinas. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain across the mid-Atlantic states and the northeastern United  
States was much lighter than the storms associated with Floyd in 
the Carolinas. 
</P>
<P>
	To the west, a second stationary front produced rain showers and  
thunderstorms over parts of the central and southern Plains, from 
southern Kansas and Colorado southward into eastern New Mexico, 
western Texas and Oklahoma, and Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	All other parts of the country had quiet weather due to a large  
area of high pressure from the Midwest to the Pacific Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Clear to partly cloudy skies and dry weather were the rule  
across the Ohio, Tennessee, and Mississippi valleys. Clouds were 
thicker across parts of the Great Lakes. 
</P>
<P>
	To the west, areas in the northern Rockies had either clear or  
partly cloudy skies and dry conditions, while low clouds persisted 
along the immediate West Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures around the nation ranged from 27 in West  
Yellowstone, Mont., to a midday high of 90 in Marathon, Fla. The 
highest heat index was 103 in Marathon, Fla., and the lowest wind 
chill was 19 in Laramie, Wyo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
