<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Opposes Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It takes a village to raise a child, but it  
takes a Republican tax cut to unite New York Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	The top four potential Democratic mayoral contenders -- including  
one of the city's top Puerto Rican officials, Bronx Borough 
President Fernando Ferrer -- appeared Wednesday with Hillary Rodham 
Clinton to denounce a proposed Republican tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	They said the proposal would devastate federal funding for New  
York schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, eyeing a race for the Democratic Senate nomination  
from New York, and Ferrer stood shoulder to shoulder during the 
news conference, an apparent symbol of her desire to mend fences 
with the Puerto Rican community. Mrs. Clinton angered many Puerto 
Ricans by opposing the clemency granted by President Clinton to a 
group of FALN activists. 
</P>
<P>
	Also present were Public Advocate Mark Green, City Comptroller  
Alan Hevesi and City Council Speaker Peter Vallone -- all likely 
rivals in the next mayoral election in 2001. The news conference 
was held at United Federation of Teachers headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kind of unity you see before you -- among all of us -- is  
because we know what's at stake, and the federal budget has a 
direct impact on what happens here in the city and the state,'' 
said Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who is exploring a run for  
the Republican Senate nomination, supports using the federal budget 
surplus for targeted tax cuts and targeted spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans think the $800 billion federal budget surplus should  
go back to the taxpayers. President Clinton has said he will veto 
the proposal altogether. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
