<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Baseball Coach Lauds Costner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texas baseball coach Augie Garrido says the  
painful winces on Kevin Costner's face in the baseball movie ``For 
Love of the Game'' are real. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's one scene where you'll see about two or three pitches.  
There must be 140 more that he threw that day on the cutting room 
floor,'' said Garrido, who was technical adviser for the film. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kevin threw every strike, threw every curve ball. He does love  
the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garrido and Costner have been friends since 1992, when Garrido  
was the coach at Cal-State Fullerton and the movie star was invited 
to help dedicate the school's new baseball stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Garrido said the two rarely talk about Costner's  
professional life in Hollywood, he knew the star of ``Bull Durham'' 
and ``Field of Dreams'' was thinking about making another baseball 
movie. 
</P>
<P>
	``For Love of the Game'' opened Wednesday in Los Angeles and  
will have its Texas premiere here Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't think I was going to be part of it until I got a call  
from the executive producer,'' Garrido said. ``It was like 
fulfilling a friend's request to help him. It wouldn't be any 
different than your neighbor coming over and asking for help 
painting his fence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only it's not every day your neighbor asks for help on a  
big-budget motion picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``Augie was the first person I thought of to help on this  
film,'' Costner said. ``I trust him implicitly on all fronts. 
Inside and outside the lines of baseball, Augie is a true friend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garrido helped set up the movie's baseball scenes, finding  
former major leaguers and current minor leaguers to put in uniform. 
The crew also hired the real ball boys for the New York Yankees, 
Garrido said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We agreed to make this as authentic as we could,'' Garrido  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Costner, who plays aging pitcher Billy Chapel near the end of  
his career, comes off like the real thing, Garrido said. 
</P>
<P>
	Garrido said he didn't have to teach Costner how to act and  
throw like a big-league pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the character by the time the film ended,'' Garrido  
said. ``Including having a very sore arm.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
