<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 23:10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> De La Hoya Needs Trinidad for Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- If Oscar De La Hoya is destined for greatness,  
Felix Trinidad might be the fighter who helps get him there. 
</P>
<P>
	The questions that linger about De La Hoya in the ring figure to  
be settled one way or another Saturday night when he and Trinidad 
meet in what should be the most lucrative non-heavyweight fight in 
boxing history. 
</P>
<P>
	When it's over, De La Hoya will either be proclaimed as one of  
the greatest welterweights of recent times or exposed as a very 
good fighter who was the beneficiary of some very careful 
promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every champion has their moment,'' De La Hoya said. ``This  
fight will have a huge impact in my boxing career. It will put me 
right up there with the greats.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Trinidad, De La Hoya has finally found a ring equal to test  
his skills in a fight that features a rare matchup of 26-year-old 
undefeated welterweight champions who are both at their peak. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also found an opponent who may for once be just as  
confident entering the ring that he is going to win as De La Hoya 
has been in his 31 previous fights. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a more complete boxer than De La Hoya,'' Trinidad said.  
``I feel Oscar is overrated. I'm going to put him on the level he 
really is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya, who will earn $15 million to $10 million for  
Trinidad, is a 6-5 favorite in this city's sports books, evidence 
that oddsmakers are having just as tough a time figuring out a 
winner as is the boxing public. 
</P>
<P>
	Both fighters are big punchers with suspect chins, and it's very  
possible the winner will have to pick himself off the canvas before 
the fight is over. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to prove something new and show people something  
they haven't seen from me before,'' De La Hoya said. ``It's time to 
prove to myself what talent I have and what boxing ability I 
possess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fight has generated such interest that all 12,000 tickets  
were scooped up by casinos before the public ever got a chance to 
go to the box office window. Another 30,000 people will watch on 
closed circuit at various hotels, while promoters say at least 1 
million homes will spend $49.95 to buy the fight on pay-per-view. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside of the heavyweight ranks, it's the biggest fight since  
Sugar Ray Leonard was fighting the likes of Thomas Hearns and 
Marvelous Marvin Hagler in the 1980s. It's also the most 
anticipated 147-pound fight since Leonard stopped Hearns in the 
14th round Sept. 16, 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Oscar wins this fight, he's the biggest thing in boxing in  
decades,'' HBO boxing executive Lou DiBella said. 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya, of course, is the driving force behind the  
promotion. The 1992 Olympic gold medalist also holds the record for 
most buys of a non-heavyweight fight (800,000) when he fought 
Pernell Whitaker on April 12, 1997, in a fight that grossed $34 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	In seven previous pay-per-view fights, De La Hoya has earned  
promoters some $150 million in television revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad, the IBF champion since 1993, doesn't have the same  
recognition among casual fans despite the fact he has won all 35 of 
his fights, 30 by knockout, and has a reputation for a fearsome 
right hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad spent 3 1/2 months, most of it in his native Puerto Rico,  
training under his father, Felix Trinidad Sr. He sparred 219 
rounds, some of them against cruiserweights to get used to De La 
Hoya's punching power. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has weaknesses and I am going to take full advantage of  
those weaknesses,'' Trinidad said through an interpreter. 
</P>
<P>
	Both fighters seemed confident Wednesday before and after a  
marathon press conference that was the last public appearance for 
each before Friday evening's weigh-in. 
</P>
<P>
	The press conference not only featured a full card of fighters  
and obligatory fight officials, but also two promoters in Bob Arum 
and Don King. Arum is the main promoter for the fight, while King 
has a smaller role as Trinidad's promoter. 
</P>
<P>
	That didn't stop King from spending an hour or so when he got  
his chance at the podium to introduce his fighter. King challenged 
Arum to a $1 million bet, one that Arum rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Putting Felix into the ring with Oscar De La Hoya means you're  
risking a lot more than $1 million,'' Arum told King. 
</P>
<P>
	Because both fighters are champions, the two camps had to  
negotiate with Nevada boxing officials on such things as what type 
of gloves would be worn and who would enter the ring first. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad's camp wanted Reyes gloves and will have them, while De  
La Hoya will get into the ring last and be introduced last. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
