<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 10:34:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D'Antoni Tells of Sinking Feeling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- When Mike D'Antoni walked into Dan Issel's office,  
he immediately got a sinking feeling. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's sitting there and the lawyer is sitting right beside  
him,'' D'Antoni said Tuesday after being fired as the Denver 
Nuggets' head coach. ``I don't think I've got any violations around 
the city, so I'm thinking, `I could be in a little trouble here.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Issel, Denver's vice president and general manager, elevated  
himself to head coach in a move that D'Antoni said left him feeling 
blindsided and ``ticked off.'' However, he also said he was 
probably naive. 
</P>
<P>
	``You learn a lot, that's for sure,'' said D'Antoni, who went  
14-36 in his only season with the Nuggets. ``About people and 
loyalty and different things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though highly successful as a coach in the Italian League,  
D'Antoni seemed to have trouble winning the respect of his players. 
Issel said D'Antoni's overseas experience didn't carry much weight 
with players in the image-conscious NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the coach today in the NBA does not have the respect of the  
players, you've got no shot,'' Issel said. ``This isn't that Mike 
did a bad job. Mike didn't have a chance to do a bad job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Issel said Nuggets owner Donald Sturm gave him a three-year  
contract with an option for a fourth year if the team is 
successful. 
</P>
<P>
	D'Antoni had two years left on a three-year contract and will  
not remain with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm mainly worried about what the heck I'm going to do with  
all the free time,'' D'Antoni said. ``I went straight home after 
Dan fired me and turned on the TV. I've already seen three 
`Matlock' reruns, and that's too many for anybody. I'm bored to 
tears. I've got to find another coaching job somewhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Issel seems to have the same itch. He coached the Nuggets for 2 1/2  
seasons before retiring in January 1995. At the time, he vowed 
never to coach again. 
</P>
<P>
	``The environment is much different now than it was then,''  
Issel said. ``To be real honest with you, the media criticism 
really affected me the first time around. I think I understand that 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Nuggets have had only minimal success since Issel led them  
to the Western Conference semifinals in 1994. They threatened to 
set an NBA futility mark before finishing 11-71 in 1997-98 and 
improved only slightly during last year's lockout-shortened season. 
</P>
<P>
	Since his first coaching retirement in 1995, Issel has worked in  
radio and television as a basketball analyst, and he returned the 
team as vice president and general manager in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	His major moves in the past year have included signing  
free-agent forward Antonio McDyess and making trades for All-Star 
point guard Nick Van Exel and Denver native Chauncey Billups. He 
also orchestrated a multiplayer trade with Boston this summer that 
brought talented swingman Ron Mercer to Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a good situation,'' Mercer said. ``I really  
didn't know the former coach too well. I think Dan hit a key point. 
The players have to respect the coach. That's one thing that stands 
out the most. I respect Dan. He's a straightforward guy. I respect 
that a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For all his front office maneuvering, Issel still inherits a  
young team with several unproven players, but said he has learned 
from his earlier coaching experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's more mature, and I don't mean in age,'' Issel's wife,  
Cheri, said. ``I think if he's ever going to be prepared, he is now 
prepared to coach this team in the right way and enjoy it. The last 
time, he did not enjoy it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Issel was one of Denver's most popular players in his 11 seasons  
with the Nuggets from 1975-85. He was inducted into the Basketball 
Hall of Fame in 1993 and is still Denver's career rebounding 
leader. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
