<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Could Siphon Bush Votes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Pat Buchanan on the brink of bolting,  
Republicans fear that a strong third-party presidential campaign by 
the conservative contender would siphon support from the GOP 
nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	A new poll fuels their fears.  
</P>
<P>
	``If he wins the Reform Party nomination, he has $12 million and  
a spot in the presidential debates -- and he can cause real problems 
for Republicans,'' said GOP strategist Scott Reed, who ran Bob 
Dole's failed 1996 presidential bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan will announce his plans in October, though advisers are  
making preparations for him to abandon the GOP. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pew Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press, which polled  
1,205 adults from Sept. 1 -12, found Buchanan could hurt 
Republicans if the matchup tightens between Democratic front-runner 
Al Gore and GOP favorite George W. Bush of Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	In a head-to-head comparison, Bush leads Gore 54 percent to 39  
percent. In a three-way matchup, 9 percent supported Buchanan while 
the Bush-Gore margin changed little -- 50 percent for Bush, 35 
percent for Gore. But underlying numbers suggest that Buchanan 
would eat away at Bush's base. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the registered voters who chose Buchanan in the three-way  
heat, 60 percent had selected the Texas governor in the two-way 
matchup and just 29 percent had selected the vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	``More Bush supporters than Gore voters migrate to Buchanan,''  
says the Pew analysis of the poll, which has a margin of error of 
plus or minus 3 percentage points. In a close Gore-Bush race ``a 
Reform Party bid by the conservative commentator might mean trouble 
for Bush.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strategists in both parties expect the 2000 presidential  
campaign to be a close race. Republicans are pointing fingers over 
the prospect of Buchanan complicating the picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question now is: Who lost Buchanan?'' Reed said.  
</P>
<P>
	Party chairman Jim Nicholson plans to meet with Buchanan this  
month, though he doesn't expect to dissuade him. Party leaders are 
pinning their hopes on GOP conservatives recruited to warn Buchanan 
that his candidacy could help elect Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson spokesman Cliff May said Buchanan needs to realize  
that bolting will ``harm the most important conservative causes he 
has worked for all these years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has asked Buchanan to remain in the party. His supporters  
are urging contacts in Buchanan's circle to do their best to 
convince him to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan has argued in a blitz of interviews that the GOP  
nomination is rigged in favor of Bush and his more moderate views. 
If he bolts, Buchanan told CNN, ``I will believe that I have a 
chance to win it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His sister and top adviser, Bay Buchanan, met with federal  
elections officials this week to determine whether he could earn 
matching money as a Reform Party candidate. The tentative answer 
was yes, she said, which suits her plans: Raise enough in private 
donations to qualify for federal matching funds and use a $6 
milllion budget to try to qualify for the ballot in the 29 states 
and the District of Columbia where the Reform Party doesn't already 
have access. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic officials say they realize that Buchanan could hurt  
their nominee, especially if a dip in the economy gives his 
populist protectionism views resonance. Buchanan is courting 
Teamsters and a number of small industrial unions -- and his 
advisers have discussed putting a labor-orientated Democrat on the 
ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a disproportionate number of Buchanan voters would  
come from Bush, although Buchanan's protectionism views will allow 
him to pick up some votes from old-labor Democrats,'' said Roger 
Stone, a GOP consultant who closely monitors the Reform Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet many Democrats insist they would welcome a Buchanan bid.  
</P>
<P>
	``It gives the Hezbollah wing of the Republican Party a place to  
go,'' Democratic consultant Dane Strother said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan's strong anti-abortion views would make him an  
unwelcome intruder to some Reform Party activists, particularly 
supporters of Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura. The nation's top 
elected Reform Party official, Ventura is trying to recruit an 
alternative to Buchanan who could do well enough in 2000 to 
maintain the party's eligibility for federal matching money. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reform Party nominee will get $12.6 million in federal money  
for 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Buchanan bolts, the person he hurts the most is himself. If  
he leaves the party, they won't have anything to do with him again. 
Second, he will lose the election because the American people are 
not in sync with his ultraconservative agenda. And, third, there is 
no way he will take over the Reform Party,'' warned Phil Madsen, a 
Ventura adviser and foe of Reform Party founder Ross Perot. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Perot backers are urging Buchanan to run, setting the stage  
for an internal third-party fight. ``The worst he does is come in 
No. 2 in the general election,'' said the party's 1996 vice 
presidential candidate Pat Choate. 
</P>
<P>
	He predicted that Bush loses the most votes to Buchanan unless  
the commentator's support exceeds 10 percentage points -- when Gore 
would begin to suffer just as much. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
