<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Charges To Be Filed vs. Rodman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Former NBA star Dennis Rodman,  
arrested last month following a disturbance at a waterfront 
restaurant and bar, won't face misdemeanor drunkenness charges in 
connection with the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Tori Richards, a spokesperson for the Orange County district  
attorney's office, said Wednesday the decision was made because 
evidence did not show Rodman was so drunk that he would not be able 
to care for his own safety. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the standard we must prove in court before a jury,''  
Richards said. ``We reached this conclusion after talking with 
police and reviewing statements from five witnesses who were at the 
bar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newport Beach police originally recommended Rodman be charged  
because he was offered a chance to leave the restaurant and didn't, 
according to Sgt. Mike McDermott. 
</P>
<P>
	Waived by the Los Angeles Lakers last April after a stormy seven  
weeks with the team, the 38-year-old Rodman was released on his own 
recognizance after spending several hours in jail following his 
arrest outside the restaurant Aug. 21. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they made the right call,'' Rodman's attorney, Paul S.  
Meyer, said from his office in Costa Mesa. ``The potential criminal 
charges evaporated in the light of all the facts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We appreciate the willingness of the office of the district  
attorney to engage in an independent and thorough review. This 
matter has now been put to rest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also arrested at the time of the disturbance was Donn Emerson,  
36, who was charged Wednesday with obstructing a police officer and 
possession of marijuana, both misdemeanors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The marijuana was discovered when he was booked, there were  
11.5 grams in his pocket,'' Richards said. ``Apparently, Mr. 
Emerson was not letting police officers conduct their interviews, 
and he was getting in the way. Police repeatedly asked him to step 
back, and he refused to do so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, Emerson faces a maximum of one year in jail and a  
$100 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Restaurant owner Ralph Furra, whose wife, Julie, was managing  
the bar at the time, said a woman apparently was taunting Rodman. 
He responded, and then the woman's boyfriend grabbed Rodman. 
</P>
<P>
	Police were called and asked Rodman to take a taxi home, but he  
refused. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 11:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brooks &AMP; Dunn Up for Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- It's as close as country music gets to a  
sure thing. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, presenter Tanya Tucker announced Kix Brooks and Ronnie  
Dunn as the best vocal duo without bothering to look at the 
winner's card. 
</P>
<P>
	She was right.  
</P>
<P>
	For seven consecutive years, the duo of Brooks &AMP; Dunn has won  
the award. And they're up for No. 8 when the 33rd annual Country 
Music Assocation Awards are broadcast live Sept. 22 on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	``There've been times when we've won duo of the year when we've  
sincerely been embarrassed,'' said Dunn, grinning at the peculiar 
problem of having so much success it seems unseemly sometimes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can be perceived as being a little one-sided.''  
</P>
<P>
	Since teaming up in 1991 at the urging of Arista Records head  
Tim DuBois, the two former solo aspirants have fashioned themselves 
into an efficient hit machine and sold more than 16 million albums. 
In 1996, they became the only duo in CMA history to win the top 
award of best entertainer. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunn, 46, from Coleman, Texas, has one of the most powerful  
voices in Nashville, and is the lead singer on the bulk of the 
Brooks &AMP; Dunn hits. Brooks, 44, from Shreveport, La., is the more 
dynamic live performer. 
</P>
<P>
	For their new album ``Tight Rope,'' longtime Brooks &AMP; Dunn  
collaborator Don Cook worked on the songs featuring Brooks, while 
Dunn brought in Byron Gallimore (Tim McGraw, Jo Dee Messina) for 
his numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	That would seem to indicate a team drifting apart. Just the  
opposite, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	``That freedom, as much as people are ready to latch on to any  
hint of a rift with us, actually is the dynamic that keeps us 
together,'' Dunn said. ``Because you can express your individuality 
and still come together and make it a Brooks &AMP; Dunn record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another success strategy: Songwriters who want to work with the  
duo are invited to join them on tour, instead of working in 
Nashville, which is the common practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``You spend all day sitting there in those buses a lot of times,  
waiting for the show,'' Dunn said. ``So why not utilize that time? 
And if you have a co-writer out there as motivation, a lot of times 
that'll help you get to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks added: ``Kids and wives and all that stuff you need to  
pay attention to when you're home, and it's hard to pay attention 
to it when you've got somebody over there trying to write a song 
with you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of their first hits was ``Boot Scootin' Boogie,'' which  
benefited from the country music line dancing craze of the early 
1990s. They are adept at ballads (``Neon Moon'') and especially 
good at cranking out aggressive rockers like ``Hard Workin' Man'' 
and ``Rock My World (Little Country Girl).'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in 1996, the duo pitched a curve ball. They released ``My  
Maria,'' a 1973 pop hit by B.W. Stevenson. Varying the formula with 
a pop remake was seen as a gamble at the time. But it went straight 
to No. 1, launched the ``Borderline'' album, and got people taking 
about them again instead of looking for something new. 
</P>
<P>
	The duo is using a similar strategy for ``Tight Rope.'' The  
leadoff single is ``Missing You,'' a No. 1 pop hit for John Waite 
in 1984. The song is shaping up as another country smash hit for 
Brooks &AMP; Dunn. 
</P>
<P>
	The hit comes just in time to give the duo a boost with CMA  
Awards voters. This year's challengers are The Kinleys, The Lynns, 
Montgomery Gentry and The Warren Brothers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kinleys and Montgomery Gentry present the strongest threat  
to Brooks &AMP; Dunn's dominance of the best vocal duo honor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've always felt like we're vulnerable,'' Dunn said. ``No one  
is more prone and set and prepared to lose any more than we are. 
We've been losing since the first platinum record we had. ... 
</P>
<P>
	``Insecurity is probably the greatest motivator in any field.  
It's ours.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 11:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
