<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance Industry Wary of Floyd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hurricane Floyd's anticipated wake of costly  
damages is expected to shine a spotlight on changes to the 
insurance industry in the seven years since Hurricane Andrew tore 
across southern Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	While companies have taken steps to ensure they can pay claims,  
they've also cut back on coverage, leaving some to fear that 
policyholders could be forced to foot more of the bill if their 
property is destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	The $15 billion in damages caused by Andrew after it swept  
across the southern tip of Florida in 1992 forced about 10 regional 
insurance companies out of business. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, many insurance companies have taken precautions  
against a similar catastrophe by taking out reinsurance policies, a 
kind of insurance policy for an insurance company. 
</P>
<P>
	``The insurance industry wasn't prepared for Andrew,'' said John  
Oxendine, Georgia's insurance commissioner. ``The insurance 
companies were absorbing a lot of the liability themselves because 
they hadn't taken out reinsurance policies. The industry is much 
more prepared now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many companies also simply stopped issuing policies that  
included hurricane damage liability along the coastlines of such 
frequently hit states as Florida, South Carolina and North 
Carolina. Those that continued to write hurricane policies 
increased the premiums as well as the deductibles that must be paid 
in the event of hurricane-related damages. In some cases, the 
deductibles were raised from as little as 1 percent of the damage 
costs to as much as 5 percent, experts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxendine said Georgia required insurers to cover coastline  
regions if they wanted to write policies in the heavily populated 
and extremely lucrative Atlanta area, located inland. ``If they 
said they weren't going to insure on the coast in Savannah, we 
said, 'That's fine, but you're not going to insure in Atlanta 
either,''' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	States such as North Carolina and South Carolina, which lack a  
major population center similar to Atlanta, were unable to use that 
as leverage against the insurers, Oxendine said. 
</P>
<P>
	In eastern Virginia, where Floyd is expected to pass over the  
heavily populated Chesapeake Bay region, Ken Schrad, a spokesman 
for the state Corporate Commission's Bureau of Insurance said that 
many insurance companies have taken steps to prevent overexposure 
to a catastrophe that could bankrupt them. 
</P>
<P>
	He added, however, that since Andrew, ``anyone who needed  
insurance was able to get it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Florida, state Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson issued a  
warning to insurers, which raised rates sharply after Hurricane 
Andrew seven years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to put the insurance companies on notice: if you think  
you're going to use Hurricane Floyd as an excuse to jack up rates, 
you have another thing coming,'' Nelson said. 
</P>
<P>
	His department will run sting operations with investigators  
posing as homeowners to catch any unscrupulous adjusters. He 
cautioned homeowners to be sure they see adjusters' licenses and be 
wary of price gouging. 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance experts said the storm would have to hit several  
densely populated, heavily developed areas to drain the $341 
billion in surplus funds currently available to the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``In terms of the financial resources based on the surplus  
numbers, the industry should be well prepared financially to handle 
the potential avalanche of claims that might arise,'' said Dave 
Dasgupta, a spokesman for the Insurance Services Office, an 
insurance data company. He said the industry can thank the booming 
stock market for the vast sum of money available to pay out claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Others aren't as certain about the industry's ability to cover  
the number of claims that could arise in the wake of Floyd, a 
hurricane that at one point was three times the size of Andrew. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may have some struggles, despite the strength of the  
insurance industry,'' said John Eager, director of claims services 
for the National Association of Independent Insurers, a trade 
association. ``Depending on the magnitude of the loss, it could 
take us right to the brink.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eager noted that that Andrew's damage occurred primarily in low-  
to middle-income neighborhoods, a factor that kept the property 
damage losses lower than if the storm had struck farther north, 
along the wealthy coastline near Miami. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
