<HEADLINE> Bradley Seeks Support in Minn. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Buoyed by strong showings in recent polls,  
Democrat Bill Bradley sought support and spending money for his 
presidential campaign Wednesday, saying he has a better chance at 
the White House than Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	The former New Jersey senator was pleased by polls in New  
Hampshire and New York showing a tight race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I truly think things are beginning to move,'' Bradley said.  
</P>
<P>
	Bradley met with 200 people and hoped many would volunteer on  
his behalf. He stressed campaign themes of reducing the number of 
poor children, extending health coverage to more people, reforming 
the campaign finance system and properly managing the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the gathering, he explained to reporters why people  
should vote for him: ``Because they believe my leadership would 
improve the quality of life for millions of Americans and they 
think I have a better chance to win in a general election,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Bradley's schedule was a $250-a-person fund-raiser at the  
Minneapolis Club and a $1,000-a-person dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	A Bradley aide, R.T. Rybak, said the campaign hoped to take in  
$100,000 in the short visit. But Rybak said the trip mainly was an 
organizing stop and a sign that Bradley considered Minnesota an 
important state. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore and Republican Texas Gov. George W. Bush also came to  
Minnesota for short stops and fund-raisers over the past few 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley told supporters he wanted to run a campaign in a  
different kind of way, meeting voters face-to-face. He asked for 
help making personal contacts, not commercials. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of those who attended Bradley's event were familiar faces  
from Sen. Paul Wellstone's campaigns. Wellstone, D-Minn., was an 
early Bradley supporter. His wife, Sheila Wellstone, introduced 
Bradley and asked supporters to do for him what they had done for 
Wellstone: work hard to elect him. 
</P>
<P>
	Dick Heglund, a Minneapolis activist who attended the event,  
called Bradley ``the only hope that the Democrats have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Gore is going no place fast,'' he said. Heglund, a retired  
teacher, said he would help Bradley as much as his schedule 
allowed. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly Goren, the chairwoman of the political science department  
at St. Catherine's College, said she might work for Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he can beat George W. and I'm not sure Al Gore can,''  
she said. Goren said she is worried Gore has been tainted by his 
alliance with President Clinton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
