<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holocaust Memorial Breaks Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel's Holocaust memorial broke ground  
Wednesday on a new Hall of Names, where millions of Holocaust 
victims will be documented in millions of pages of testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Baron Benjamin de Rothschild, a French wine maker who chairs the  
fund financing the new building, helped lay the cornerstone with 
Education Minister Yossi Sarid and Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction on addition to Yad Vashem, estimated to cost $3.1  
million dollars, is scheduled to begin in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope this will infuse information not only to Jewish people,  
but to people across the world, so this does not happen again,'' 
Rothschild said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nazis and their allies murdered at least six million Jews in  
German-occupied Europe between 1939 and 1945. Many members of the 
widespread Rothschild banking clan perished in the Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Hall of Names is part of the ``Yad Vashem 2001'' plan to  
renovate the aging memorial. The plan includes a new gateway and 
visitors' center, an International School for Holocaust Studies and 
a new archives building. 
</P>
<P>
	A model of the new Hall of Names showed a three-circle  
structure. Most of the building will house millions of pages of 
testimony naming victims of the Holocaust. It will also house a 
computerized database. 
</P>
<P>
	Yad Vashem Chairman Avner Shalev said he and his colleagues  
hoped the collection of Holocaust testimony would soon reach five 
million pages. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
