<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corrections Dept. Has Bodyguard Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- A bodyguard unit has been created to protect  
Arizona's top corrections officials, including the prison chief, 
who officials say barely survived an assassination plot by prison 
gang members last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Corrections Director Terry Stewart created the nine-member  
Protective Services Unit in April with temporary funding. 
</P>
<P>
	To continue the unit, the state asked for $400,000 in a  
supplemental budget request, which The Associated Press obtained 
through state open records laws. If approved, the funding would 
kick in during the fiscal year that begins July 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The budget request says the unit has responded to 29 threats  
made against Corrections Department employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Most cases involved attempts to intimidate or threaten  
department employees or their relatives or reports that gang 
members planned to kidnap or attack employees, said Gary Phelps, 
the department's chief of staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said Stewart's life is in danger because of get-tough  
policies on imprisoned gang members, who have been separated from 
other prisoners or transferred to prisons in other states. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a sense they want to strike back,'' Phelps said  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The budget request points to a case in which three gang members  
were accused of plotting to kill Stewart. Officials said the men 
were within moments of gunning down Stewart last summer as he ate 
at a restaurant but were scared off by police officers. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges were dropped in February after a key prosecution  
witness refused to answer questions about the plot in court. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
