<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Web Sites for Bonds Popping Up / On the Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors seeking information about stocks on  
the Internet easily can gain access to thousands of sites at any 
given moment, including ones that let them trade around the clock. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds are a different story.  
</P>
<P>
	Those looking to trade, price or conduct general research online  
may sometimes find more data about the tuxedo-clad, martini-sipping 
secret agent named James or the Missouri senator named Christopher, 
after typing ``bonds'' into a search engine. 
</P>
<P>
	This information gap may be attributed to the fact that the  
stock market has been so hot in recent years and investors are far 
more interested in the double-digit returns of equities. But it 
probably also has to do with volume -- there are far more 
outstanding bond issues than stock and most are in over-the-counter 
markets rather than exchanges, which makes them more difficult to 
sort through and track. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just in the corporate market alone, there are 300,000 to  
400,000 bonds listed,'' said Michael Dorfsman, a spokesman for the 
Bond Market Association, a New York-based trade group, ``and most 
bonds don't trade on any given day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the market's magnitude, however, there is still more  
bond information available online today than a year ago -- or even 
six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Useful Web sites have been slowly popping up. Some financial  
institutions have been augmenting their sites to include more 
information about investing in the credit markets, and a few major 
online brokerages have been providing individual investors with 
trading areas that contain more timely information. 
</P>
<P>
	While still greatly underused, experts like Thomas O'Connell,  
president of Discover Brokerage Direct in San Francisco, predict 
online fixed-income activity will increase as stocks turn more 
volatile and eventually end their long bull market. 
</P>
<P>
	He told a Bond Market Association (BMA) meeting earlier this  
year that bonds eventually will have a strong online presence 
because investors like the option of all-day trading. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, those wishing to develop a working knowledge about  
bonds can obtain some useful information through a few growing Web 
sites. 
</P>
<P>
	A good place to start may be www.investinginbonds.com, which is  
run by BMA. The site starts off with bond basics: types of debt 
securities traded; their suggested presence in an investment 
portfolio; and up-to-date reports analyzing market trends. There 
are price quotes available on some actively traded municipal and 
investment-grade corporate bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Also covering the basics is www.bondsonline.com, run by  
Twenty-First Century Municipals Inc. an online information services 
company based in Mercer Island, Washington. It includes specialized 
sections on Treasuries, savings bonds, municipals, corporates, 
zero-coupon bonds and collateralized mortgage obligations. Price 
quotes and research reports are available. 
</P>
<P>
	A quick overview of current prices and yields for a variety of  
bond categories can be obtained at www.cnnfn.com. Its ``bond 
center'' also provides current news reports about bonds, interest 
rates and the economy. Another good source: www.cbsmarketwatch.com. 
</P>
<P>
	The official site for Treasury bond information is  
www.publicdebt.treas.gov. It includes all types of government bond 
information, including a calculator to determine exactly what the 
public debt was on any given day for the past four years. 
</P>
<P>
	For the more sophisticated investor willing to pay a monthly  
fee, there are www.bradynet.com and www.convertbond.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradynet includes complete information on Eurobonds, global  
issues and emerging markets derivatives as well as bond information 
for specific countries an extensive analytic tools. Among the 
issued tracked: Brady bonds, named for former U.S. Treasury 
Secretary Nicholas Brady, which allowed 18 countries over the last 
10 years to repay their debt by repackaging defaulted loans into 
new bonds, partly backed by U.S. Treasury bonds. Service starts at 
$99.95 per month. 
</P>
<P>
	Convertbond provides a wide range of information about  
convertible bonds, which are publicly traded income-bearing 
securities that can be converted into common stock of companies 
issuing them. Brokerage accounts can be opened. Membership options 
start at $10 per year. 
</P>
<P>
	A good place to trade bonds online is www.etrade.com, run by the  
online broker ETrade Group Inc. Its relatively new Bond Center 
lists thousands of corporates, munis and Treasuries for sale. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
