<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Developer Barred From Paying Jurors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge ruled that millionaire developer Abraham  
Hirschfeld cannot give jurors money after his murder-for-hire 
trial, a question that came up after he offered $2,500 to each 
member of a jury that deadlocked on an earlier trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Hirschfeld's attorney said state Supreme Court Justice Carol  
Berkman has no authority to tell the defendant what he may do as a 
private citizen after trial if he is acquitted, and some legal 
authorities said he had a point. 
</P>
<P>
	Her order was issued Monday and reaffirmed Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	While acknowledging that Hirschfeld's gifts to jurors might not  
be strictly illegal, Berkman said the actions ``don't pass the 
smell test.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said she was just trying to ensure a fair trial. She  
said she did not want potential jurors coming to court and 
wondering, ``Will I get paid for this case, and how much?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the case before Berkman, Hirschfeld is charged with trying to  
hire a hitman to kill former business partner Stanley Stahl. Stahl 
died of natural causes this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, the quirky parking lot tycoon -- whose offer  
to give Paula Jones $1 million to settle her lawsuit against 
President Clinton was rebuffed -- gave $2,500 to 10 members of a 
jury that deadlocked over whether he was guilty of tax fraud. Two 
jurors turned down the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Hirschfeld's lawyer, Arthur Aidala, said nothing gives a judge  
the authority to tell jurors what they may not do after they are 
discharged from service. If they want to accept a gift from 
Hirschfeld, that is their right, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't order people not to do something because it smells  
bad,'' said Professor H. Richard Uviller of Columbia University's 
Law School. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
