<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 10:33:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Luise Rainer: A Legend Looks Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Luise Rainer was in San Francisco with husband  
Clifford Odets in 1938 when she got news of her second consecutive 
Academy Award for best actress. But a night of triumph soon became 
one of tears. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clifford had just had a great fight with me and told me how no  
good I was and all that,'' Rainer says of her stormy marriage to 
the seminal American playwright of ``Awake and Sing'' and ``Waiting 
for Lefty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``By golly,'' she says, her recollection clear, her exuberance  
unbridled, ``I phoned home (in Los Angeles) and was told I must 
come home right away because the papers were asking, `Was I 
shunning or not caring about the Academy?' I hadn't even dreamed of 
getting another Academy Award, and there I was unhappy in my 
private life and miserable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In those days, winners were announced hours before the ceremony  
began at around 11 p.m. So despite her domestic distress, Rainer 
had enough time to drive to Los Angeles and accept her trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember Odets drove me three times around the Biltmore,  
where the Oscars were given out, because I was so full of tears.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rainer sits forward, as if ready for her close-up, in a regally  
appointed apartment that this particular afternoon functions almost 
as a stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Her innate theatricality undimmed by the years, Rainer doesn't  
so much answer as emote when asked about her emotionally charged 
and often enigmatic life. 
</P>
<P>
	Once known as the ``Viennese teardrop,'' Rainer did what might  
seem unimaginable: Having made history as the first performer ever 
to win back-to-back Academy Awards -- for ``The Great Ziegfeld'' 
(1936) and ``The Good Earth'' (1937) -- she simply walked out of 
show biz and superstardom. 
</P>
<P>
	Five decades later, at 89, she's an aging yet animated beauty in  
a profession that prizes youth. ``It's so ridiculous,'' she says. 
``Today, if you are 31, you're told you can't do a 30-year-old.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1930s, she was a European emigre to the West Coast who  
replaced Myrna Loy in a little-known film called ``Escapade'' and 
went on to beat out Norma Shearer and Greta Garbo for the Oscar. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are few very beautiful people,'' says Rainer. ``Garbo  
was one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When I got two Oscars, they thought, `Oh, they can throw me  
into anything,''' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	But the diminutive theater-trained performer from Dusseldorf,  
Germany, fell foul of MGM impresario Louis B. Mayer and found that 
life on the post-Oscar fast track was a labor not necessarily of 
love. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a seven-year contract that I broke and went away,'' says  
Rainer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a machine, practically, a tool in a big, big factory,  
and I could not do anything. I wanted to film `Madame Curie,' but 
Mayer forbade me; I wanted to do `For Whom the Bell Tolls,' but 
(producer David O.) Selznick took Ingrid Bergman and brought her to 
Hemingway and I didn't know Hemingway. 
</P>
<P>
	``And so I left,'' she says. ``I just went away. I fled; yes, I  
fled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ernest Hemingway may be one of the few 20th-century greats whom  
Rainer did not know. 
</P>
<P>
	George Gershwin taught her to sing ``Summertime'' during a drive  
up the California coast. Bertolt Brecht wrote a play for her, ``The 
Caucasian Chalk Circle,'' and offered her the part of Grusha, now 
considered a defining theater role. She turned it down. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't like Brecht. I never did,'' she says. ``I think he  
wrote some beautiful plays. But I didn't like the black and the 
white, that the rich were black and always went down to hell and 
the poor were white and went up to heaven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She prefers Anton Chekhov. ``He finds many, many colors in his  
human beings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In her 20s she befriended the great photographer Alfred  
Stieglitz, and married Clifford Odets, only to divorce him after 
four years. ``I think my first husband suffered under my career,'' 
she says. ``He loved me, I think, as much as he could love.'' After 
the divorce, they remained together for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Federico Fellini and Luchino Visconti were among the  
directors who sought her out, even though she had largely left 
acting behind and married Robert Knittel, an English book publisher 
who was her husband for 45 years until his death a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
	And now, a career that ended in the 1940s has been resurrected  
in director Karoly Makk's ``The Gambler,'' a minor adaptation of 
the Dostoyevsky story, in which she plays a lively grandmother 
opposite Michael Gambon, Dominic West and Polly Walker. 
</P>
<P>
	``Supposedly, I stole the film, which is a nice idea,'' she  
says. ``I like stealing a film.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Is she glad to be back in the movies?  
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I missed it,'' she says. ``It's been terrible not to do  
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, ``I was very happy without working,'' she adds. ``I  
painted, then I wrote; my husband and I traveled a lot. I always 
did something, always.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dressed in a lemon-colored pantsuit, she springs from a chair in  
her elegant Chelsea apartment to show a visitor her paintings. One 
of them is a 1973 portrait of a granddaughter now in her 20s and 
pregnant. Rainer will become a great-grandmother shortly before she 
turns 90 in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere sits a row of boxes made by Rainer that recall the  
work of the artist Joseph Cornell. ``He was mad about me,'' she 
says. ``He made a teardrop, a beautiful box, and I left them all 
behind. I didn't know who he was. 
</P>
<P>
	Then she shows off a collection of stones largely found while  
mountain climbing. ``I do everything for a little and then I get 
tired of it, and I don't do it anymore,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oscars sit on a top shelf in her sun-drenched study, one  
slightly shorter than the other. (``Buttock fatigue,'' is Rainer's 
droll explanation.) 
</P>
<P>
	``Leave them alone,'' she says, preferring to point out other  
honors -- commendations from the German and Austrian governments, a 
1944 letter from the American Red Cross honoring her. 
</P>
<P>
	She began her career on the European stage under the tutelage of  
the celebrated director Max Reinhardt, then made a few films in 
Germany before being brought to Hollywood in the mid-1930s. 
</P>
<P>
	``Film is a fantastic medium, but I was unaware of that when I  
walked out after three years,'' she says. ``I was unaware until 
much later how many human beings I was able to reach with the 
little I did and how many humans seemed to be grateful or happy 
that I was permitted to give. All of that only came much, much 
later to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an era in which screen goddesses tended to stick to one  
persona, Rainer reinvented herself with the versatility of a Meryl 
Streep. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``The Great Ziegfeld,'' she was Anna Held, first wife to the  
impresario Florenz Ziegfeld. More than six decades later, her teary 
telephone call congratulating Ziegfeld on his second marriage is 
considered a classic. It is also considered the scene that won her 
the Oscar. 
</P>
<P>
	The next year, she donned peasant garb to play O-lan, the  
virtuous spouse in ``The Good Earth,'' adapted from Pearl S. Buck's 
novel. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing more wonderful to give out, to give out what  
is in you,'' says Rainer. ``I still get fan mail from 50 years ago 
-- not from now, not from `The Gambler.' I still get two to five 
letters a day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While many people her age might stay close to home, she is  
always on the move. Last September, she spoke at a retrospective of 
her work at London's National Film Theater. Her beaded brocade cap 
is a frequent sight at major opening nights, unless she's on the 
road visiting friends and relatives in the United States or heading 
to a South African safari. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's full of life. She's full of energy,'' says Nicholas  
Dromgoole, an English dance critic and friend of Rainer. 
</P>
<P>
	On the street, ``She's like a power walker; it's difficult to  
keep up with her,'' says another friend, Michael Tilson Thomas, the 
American conductor. 
</P>
<P>
	Memoirs? ``I can't do it. There's too much; I don't know where  
to start. I've written 125 typewritten pages, and I'm at age 22.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps there are far too many adventures still ahead to let her  
dwell on the past. 
</P>
<P>
	``I function like an animal,'' she says. ``I function by  
instinct, by intuition. 
</P>
<P>
	``And why not? I'm alive.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
