<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Many Sent to Summer School in Error </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Scoring errors on school tests last spring may  
have resulted in as many as 3,000 pupils being sent to summer 
school by mistake, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rudy Crew, the city schools chancellor, announced the problem in  
a news release Tuesday, but declined to answer questions. An aide 
estimated that about 10 percent of the 300,000 tests were graded 
erroneously by test publisher CTBMcGraw-Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	The Monterey, Calif.-based company confirmed that similar  
scoring errors had occurred elsewhere in the country, but spokesman 
Steven Weiss refused to say where. 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss said the scoring mistake was a mathematical error that  
occurred when individual students' raw scores were compared with a 
national norm. He said students' scores would rise modestly when 
recalibrated. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials said they were told of the discrepancy this  
week by CTB-McGraw Hill. The board is still trying to determine how 
many children were affected and doesn't plan to notify students 
until a figure is confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Crew on Tuesday also called for an independent audit of  
CTB-McGraw Hill, which received more than $2 million from the 
school board in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The scoring mistakes add yet another kink in Crew's plan to end  
automatic promotion of failing students. 
</P>
<P>
	Test scores last spring had determined that 35,000 students had  
failed the year and would have to attend summer school. In 
mid-August, Crew said most summer schoolers would pass on to the 
next grade. 
</P>
<P>
	But he had to revise his estimate this month, saying 60 percent  
of summer school students would have to repeat their current grade. 
The change was largely the result of 14,000 students who either 
didn't show up at summer school or who didn't take the tests. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
