<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Motorola Inc., down 6 9/16 at 86 5/8  
</P>
<P>
 *General Instrument Corp., down 3 29/128 to 47 35/128 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola has offered about $11 billion to acquire General  
Instrument. Shareholders of General Instrument apparently believed 
the company merited a higher price, while Motorola shareholders 
worried the deal would dilute the value of their stock. 

</P>
<P>
 *Boston Scientific Corp., down 8 5/16 at 27    	
</P>
<P>
	The medical device maker warned Wall Street late Tuesday that  
third-quarter revenues will be lower than expected. Boston 
Scientific cited the recall of its Rotablator systems and 
lower-than-expected sales of stents. 

</P>
<P>
 *Bestfoods, up 4 3/16 at 53 1/8  
</P>
<P>
 *H.J. Heinz &AMP; Co., up 1 7/16 at 44 5/8 
</P>
<P>
	Bestfoods denied a report it is in merger talks with Heinz. Such  
a combination would create the world's third-largest food company. 

</P>
<P>
 *NCR Corp., down 2 7/8 at 34    	
</P>
<P>
	Shares fell for a second session after an analyst with McDonald  
&AMP; Co. cut his 1999 and 2000 earnings estimates, citing weakness in 
NCR's general-purpose computer business. The company said business 
fell in the third quarter, but the decline should be short-lived. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Oracle Corp., down 2 3/4 at 42 11/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Oracle earned 16 cents per share in its fiscal first-quarter, in  
line with Wall Street's official estimates but 2 cents shy of the 
unofficial ``whisper'' estimate. Oracle's revenue also fell short 
of some estimates. 

</P>
<P>
 *Visio Corp., up 6 3/8 at 39 7/8    	
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Corp. will acquire Visio in a stock swap valued at  
$1.3 billion. Visio designs Microsoft-based software programs to 
give users drawing and technical diagram capabilities. 

</P>
<P>
 *E-Net Inc., down 3/8 at 4 1/4    	
</P>
<P>
	IXC Communications, the operator of a coast-to-coast Internet  
backbone, may acquire a 20 percent stake in E-Net as part of a 
marketing pact. E-Net develops hardware and software network 
technology. 




  	   	
