<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Case May Run Ravens' Offense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OWINGS MILLS, Md. (AP) -- A month ago, Stoney Case was a  
quarterback looking for a job. Now he's one snap away from running 
the Baltimore Ravens' offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Case had nowhere to turn after the Indianapolis Colts cut him  
after their first exhibition game. He finally found a home in 
Baltimore, where he was promptly assigned the No. 4 spot on the 
depth chart behind Scott Mitchell, Tony Banks and Wally Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just hoping to get picked up by somebody quickly where I  
could go in and compete for a roster spot,'' Case recalled 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after Case signed a one-year, $400,000 contract, the Ravens  
released Richardson. Case displaced Banks as the backup to Scott 
Mitchell on the strength of two straight miracle finishes in 
exhibition games in which he threw the winning touchdown passes in 
the final minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell struggled mightily in the Ravens' 27-10 season-opening  
loss to the St. Louis Rams, and now many fans are clamoring for 
coach Brian Billick to give the starting job to Case. 
</P>
<P>
	Billick is impressed with how Case has learned the system, and  
has plenty of nice things to say about the talent and poise of the 
fourth-year player. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got all the parts. Size, vision, athleticism,  
intelligence, quick release strong arm,'' Billick said. ``He's done 
some excellent things out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Billick is sticking with Mitchell for Sunday's game against  
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	``Scott Mitchell is the starting quarterback. If Scott gets  
hurt, Stoney Case will go in,'' Billick said. ``But right now, I 
can't imagine why Scott Mitchell would come out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Mitchell plays as poorly as last week -- 17-for-40 for 188  
yards and two interceptions -- then he might suffer the same fate as 
last year, when he was benched by Detroit Lions coach Bobby Ross 
after two games. 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, one of the reasons Case decided to sign with Baltimore  
is that Mitchell and Banks have absolutely no history with Billick 
or the Ravens. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went to Jacksonville, and they definitely had a franchise  
quarterback (Mark Brunell),'' Case said. ``Here, there were a bunch 
of guys with one-year contracts and a new coaching staff and a new 
offense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Case, 29, has made a career out of being a backup. Since being  
drafted in the third round in 1995 by Arizona, he has played in 
four games, starting one, and hasn't thrown a pass in an NFL game 
since 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	After riding the bench as the third-string quarterback in  
Arizona last season, Case signed a two-year, $2 million contract 
with Indianapolis that included a $500,000 signing bonus. But the 
Colts released him after signing Steve Walsh as a backup to Peyton 
Manning. 
</P>
<P>
	Things couldn't have worked out better for Case, who kept the  
half-million bucks the Colts gave him and worked his way up the 
depth chart in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things have been going pretty well for me. I've gotten some  
breaks and I've played well when I've had the chance,'' Case said. 
</P>
<P>
	He has no idea when his next opportunity will come up, but he  
plans to be ready to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm always ready to go, doesn't matter if No. 3, or 2 or 1,''  
Case said. ``I'm going to prepare as if I'm the starter. Whether I 
play or not, I can't control anything but myself.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
