<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Odwalla Juices Get New Look </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HALF MOON BAY, Calif. (AP) -- Nearly three years ago, Odwalla  
Inc. was on the brink of disaster, known more for a deadly E. coli 
outbreak than for its ``Strawberry C Monster,'' ``Femme Vitale'' 
and ``Rooty Fruity'' juice drinks. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the company that helped establish the premium natural juice  
and fruit smoothie category is trying to set itself apart from 
competitors such as Fresh Samantha and Naked Juice, which grabbed 
market share while Odwalla was mired in lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Odwalla has unveiled a new, slimmer bottle with a screw cap and  
a bolder, more colorful label. The bottles cost twice as much to 
make, but the drinks' prices -- usually between about $1.69 and 
$2.99 -- will remain the same. To compensate, the 16-ounce version 
now holds 15.2 ounces and the old 12-ounce contains 11 ounces. 
</P>
<P>
	Some customers have called to complain about the smaller sizes,  
but others have praised the new caps, which replaced a snap-off 
version that leaked, company spokeswoman Erin Markey said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new design also provides for a longer shelf-life. The old  
bottles kept juice fresh for 12-17 days, depending on the flavor. 
These new bottles, which are also recyclable, have a nylon lining 
and keep juice fresh for 22-30 days, Odwalla says. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Hemphill of the New York-based Beverage Marketing Corp.,  
which compiles and analyzes sales data, anticipates Odwalla's sales 
will reach $67 million by year's end. That would represent a 13 
percent increase over 1998 sales of $59.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some companies never recover from something like that and I  
think they have,'' Hemphill said. ``It certainly takes time to win 
back the confidence of consumers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the company's stock, which closed Wednesday at $7.37 1/2,  
has been stuck at less than half of what it traded for in 1996, 
before a Colorado girl died and 66 others were sickened by bacteria 
in Odwalla's unpasteurized apple juice. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Odwalla's immediate apology and product recall --  
Chairman and CEO Stephen Williamson says trucks were picking up 
juice from stores a half-hour after the company learned of the E. 
coli link -- sales plunged. 
</P>
<P>
	Odwalla later began flash pasteurizing its apple juices, a  
process it said keeps juices fresher and more nutritious than 
traditional pasteurization. And this week, it expanded the process 
to the citrus line, selling both flash pasteurized and fresh 
versions of orange, grapefruit and tangerine drinks. 
</P>
<P>
	Odwalla's sales had been growing at about 40 percent a year  
before the outbreak, which depressed sales to about 10 percent of 
what they had been. It took until this latest fiscal year for sales 
to exceed 1996 levels, Williamson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's product line has expanded to include energy bars  
and dairy-free shakes, a wellness drink loaded with vitamin C and 
echinacea to fight colds, and several fruit and vegetable blends. 
One of the latest, to be introduced to stores on Sept. 30, is 
``Serious Energy,'' combines exotic mushrooms, green tea and 
ginseng. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Odwalla expects to lose money the first half of 1999,  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a scar and it's going to be here forever,'' Williamson  
said. ``It's important that we remember that, express our sorrow 
and behave in a responsible way.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
