<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mostly Lower; Dow Down 0.31 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower today as a tame report  
on inflation only briefly eased fears that the Federal Reserve will 
raise interest rates. Technology shares led the decline, giving up 
some of Tuesday's sharp gains, and the dollar's continued weakness 
against the Japanese yen also undercut stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 0.31 at 10,910.02. The index had fallen back from 
an early gain of 103 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was down 4.80 at 1,331.49, while the Nasdaq composite 
index was down 30.13 at 2,838.16, after climbing more than 23 
points on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks initially rose today after the Labor Department reported  
that the August increase in its Consumer Price Index -- the most 
closely watched inflation gauge -- matched the 0.3 percent July 
advance. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding the big gains in the gasoline and energy categories,  
prices rose a mere 0.1 percent in August, well below what Wall 
Street economists had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The news initially calmed worries that the Fed will need to  
boost interest rates for the third time this year as it tries to 
prevent inflation from escalating. Financial stocks, which can 
benefit from stable interest rates, rose. J.P. Morgan gained 1 3/4 to 
123 3/4, and Chase Manhattan rose 1 1/8 to 78 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	But continued weakness in the dollar helped turn stocks lower  
again. 
</P>
<P>
	Today in New York, the dollar was trading at 104.29 yen, down  
from 105.79 yen late Tuesday and the lowest level against the 
Japanese currency in more than three years. Although the dollar has 
held up well against European currencies, its slide against the yen 
has added to the pressure on stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors fear a weaker dollar because it makes imports more  
expensive, setting the stage for price inflation. It can also make 
foreign investors in U.S. stocks more likely to put their money in 
domestic investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The inflation-sensitive bond market fluctuated wildly, with  
yields on 30-year Treasury bonds dropping to 6.08 percent after the 
release of the consumer price report, then edging back up to 6.11 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Oracle fell 3 9/16 to 41 7/8 after the company's fiscal  
first-quarter earnings, reported after markets closed Tuesday, 
failed to meet the most optimistic predictions of Wall Street 
analysts. Oracle earned 16 cents per share, in line with the 
published earnings estimates, but short of the ``whisper'' number, 
an unofficial forecast circulated among Wall Street traders. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP;  
Co. in Kansas City, said the Nasdaq's decline was to be expected 
after the index bounded to a new closing high of 2,887.06 last 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``A limited number of technology stocks have led the Nasdaq  
higher,'' he said. Some of the leading technology shares already 
have risen so far that ``they are prone to pullbacks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues were nearly even with decliners on the New York  
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 377.72 million shares at 
midday, ahead of Tuesday's volume. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was down 0.37 at  
437.87. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
