<HEADLINE> Some Wayne State Faculty Walk Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The union representing faculty and staff at Wayne  
State University called for a one-day strike on Thursday as it 
tries to gain a more favorable labor contract with the 
30,000-student school. 
</P>
<P>
	Jan Thompson, executive director of Local 6075 of the American  
Association of University Professors-American Federation of 
Teachers, said Wednesday the walkout would ``show our resolve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wayne State will remain open, said Provost Marilyn Williamson.  
</P>
<P>
	The 1,687 faculty and staff members at Wayne State are covered  
by the AARP-AFT contract, but only 463 -- about 27 percent -- are 
union members, Ms. Williamson said. The school thinks it can cover 
their work for one day. 
</P>
<P>
	The faculty and staff have been working without a contract since  
July 31. They continued working on day-to-day contract extensions 
until Tuesday, when they voted for the one-day strike, Ms. Thompson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The union also voted to go on strike indefinitely if a contract  
was not reached by Sept. 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Williamson said she hoped state-mediated bargaining would  
produce a new contract before then. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides have yet to reach agreement on salaries, the  
length of the new contract and the union's proposal that all newly 
hired faculty members join the union for at least one year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
