<HEADLINE> Puerto Rico To Show De La Hoya Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- You can't afford the pay-per-view  
rate to see this weekend's championship boxing match? It's free in 
Puerto Rico. 
</P>
<P>
	The Puerto Rican government said Wednesday it would foot the  
bill for 8,000 poor residents to watch the match between San Juan 
native Felix ``Tito'' Trinidad and Oscar De La Hoya. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable TV subscribers would otherwise have to pay $50 to see the  
fight. 
</P>
<P>
	The public screening of Saturday's fight will cost the  
government $72,000, Senate President Charlie Rodriguez said at a 
news conference. The fight will be beamed by satellite from Las 
Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad is one of Puerto Rico's most popular athletes, and  
excitement over the match has been building since it was announced 
in June. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tito Fever,'' as local radio stations have dubbed it,  
coincides with a recent burst of nationalism fueled by protests 
against the U.S. military and the release of 11 pro-independence 
activists jailed in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya is an American, while Trinidad is a San Juan native.  
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez said lawmakers would distribute 8,000 free tickets on  
a first-come, first-served basis on the capitol steps Thursday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez, who is running for San Juan mayor, said the tickets  
were meant for poor families, but said the government would not 
require proof of a low income. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
