<DOCNO> APW19990915.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 07:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AmeriCorps Management Is Faulted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal officials running one of President  
Clinton's favorite programs -- the AmeriCorps national volunteer 
service program -- have promised to fix its problems so many times 
they have begun to ``sound like a broken record,'' the chairman of 
a House subcommittee says. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Peter Hoekstra, R-Mich., said he does not doubt that  
thousands of young Americans have done good work through the 
program, which awards college tuition assistance in exchange for 
volunteer service. But he said administrators have failed to 
deliver what was promised. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many AmeriCorps programs are spending taxpayer dollars  
inappropriately,'' Hoekstra said during a hearing Tuesday before 
his panel, the House Committee on Education and the Workforce 
subcommittee on oversight and investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoekstra cited a report from an Indiana student in the Terre  
Haute Tribune-Star that program organizers told her ``she could 
count baby-sitting, lifeguarding and choir practice as AmeriCorps 
volunteerism. Now her education award is in jeopardy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the investigator in charge of keeping track of AmeriCorps  
said serious management problems continue to trouble the program, 
which Clinton places among his administration's great achievements. 
</P>
<P>
	Audits of the Corporation for National Service, which runs the  
AmeriCorps program, ``revealed that the corporation's financial 
management is inadequate,'' said Luise S. Jordan, the corporation's 
inspector general. 
</P>
<P>
	AmeriCorps has been a favorite target of some Republicans in  
Congress who say it's silly to pay students to do volunteer work. 
The House voted to eliminate the $533 million that Clinton 
requested for AmeriCorps in the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. The 
Senate has not yet acted. 
</P>
<P>
	A former chairman of the Corporation for National Service's  
board, defending the program, said it has been working hard to 
correct problems. Furthermore, the program's decentralized 
structure gives state commissions a major role in management and 
oversight of local programs, said Bob Rogers, a Republican who was 
chairman from 1996 to last June. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because there are literally thousands of sites at which  
AmeriCorps members serve, it is not feasible, nor was it ever 
envisioned, that the corporation would directly monitor every local 
site,'' Rogers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In such a decentralized structure there will always be a small  
number of incidents of unscrupulous conduct by program 
administrators. And when those people are caught, they are dealt 
with accordingly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan said the Corporation for National Service began an effort  
to straighten out its affairs in December, but ``at this time, I 
have no evidence from which I can provide any assurance that the 
material weaknesses have been corrected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That has resulted numerous problems, she said, including poor  
monitoring of volunteer activities at some sites. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, one volunteer received AmeriCorps stipend checks  
even though he was an inmate of an out-of-state prison, Jordan 
said. The volunteer and his project director stole about $4,600 by 
failing to report the volunteer's incarceration and cashing the 
checks. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive director of another AmeriCorps program falsely  
certified that his son had earned two education grants although the 
young man had never served in AmeriCorps. That director also stole 
cash from volunteers by charging them bogus ``activity fees.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 07:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-POWs Seek Slave Labor Redress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Claiming they were forced into slave labor by  
Japanese companies, 500 American ex-prisoners of war are seeking an 
apology and millions of dollars from their captors. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawsuit, which seeks class-action status, was filed Monday in  
U.S. District Court in Albuquerque, N.M., against five Japanese 
companies. It was described at a New York news conference Tuesday 
as the first aimed at Japanese industrial firms that used POWs to 
produce war goods between 1942 and 1945. 
</P>
<P>
	Such actions are illegal under the Geneva Convention and various  
treaties that Japan's wartime government promised to honor, said 
Eli J. Warach, a lawyer for the plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit embraces families and estates of POWs who died, asks  
compensation for labor and injuries, and would bar the defendants 
from doing business in the United States, but names no money 
figure. 
</P>
<P>
	``Millions and millions. You can't put a price tag on this,''  
said Warach. ``This is filed not for revenge -- although there is 
some anger -- but to get justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, Japanese embassy spokesman Tsuyochi Yamamoto said  
he could not comment on a U.S. legal matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we are well aware of the fact that during World War II we  
committed serious mistakes in colonizing neighboring countries and 
causing tremendous damage and suffering to many countries, 
including the United States,'' Yamamoto said. 
</P>
<P>
	A State Department official, who asked not to be identified,  
said the 1951 peace treaty between Japan and the former Allied 
Powers included settlement provisions for most claims over Japan's 
actions during the war. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said, the United States compensated ``victims of  
Japanese aggression'' under a program that began in 1948 and 
expired in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants, Kawasaki Heavy Industries, Ltd.; Mitusi &AMP; Co.,  
Inc.; Mitsubishi International Corp.; Nippon Steel Corp., and Showa 
Denko, were described as the five largest users of POWs in coal 
mines, factories and shipping docks. The five earned $291 billion 
last year, according to the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday in California, three former POWs filed a similar  
lawsuit under a new state law seeking reparation from Mitsubishi 
Corp., the Japanese company that allegedly held them captive during 
World War II. The three also allege they were enslaved. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. records show more than 50,000 Americans, 36,000 military  
and 14,000 civilians, were prisoners of Japan during World War II. 
Of those, 14,000 military and 1,500 civilians died from disease, 
maltreatment and other causes. 
</P>
<P>
	Warach said his lawsuit comes more than 50 years after the war  
because evidence and information withheld by U.S. agencies during 
the Cold War was only recently declassified. 
</P>
<P>
	Several ex-POWs also said U.S. officials warned them in 1945 not  
to discuss their experiences. 
</P>
<P>
	Slave labor differs from forced labor in that victims are denied  
payment, adequate food and other necessities, and kept confined 
when not working, Warach said. The POWs said they were supposed to 
earn pay but never saw any. 
</P>
<P>
	Ex-POWs at the news conference backed the allegations with  
personal memories. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Reuter, 79, of Oxon Hill, Md., who survived the infamous  
``Bataan Death March'' in the Philippines, nearly wept in recalling 
that he learned only after Japan's surrender that U.S. Marines had 
fought a bloody island-hopping campaign across the South Pacific. 
</P>
<P>
	``Essentially, it meant they were using me to replace a Japanese  
who was trying to kill my brother,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit was filed in New Mexico partly because many of the  
victims had been National Guardsmen there before being sent to the 
Philippines. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
