<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Politics 2000 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A nationwide group of religious leaders  
Wednesday urged presidential candidates to adhere to a ``Framework 
of Civility'' during the 2000 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The Interfaith Alliance, an organization of religious leaders  
representing about 100,000 supporters from a wide range of 
religious faiths, announced that it sent a letter to all major 
presidential candidates asking them to endorse a code of ethical 
conduct for their campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Framework of Civility'' urges candidates to ``reject  
personal attacks, innuendo or stereotyping'' opponents. It also 
asks them to ``avoid all references ... likely to dehumanize those 
holding opinions different'' from their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are calling on presidential candidates to put their faith  
in action by supporting this `Framework of Civility' which embodies 
the values and principles held by people of faith,'' said Rev. 
Welton Gaddy, Interfaith Alliance's executive director. 
</P>
<P>
	The Alliance wants the candidates to apply the same standards to  
their staffs as well. It asks them to not condone staff members' 
``degrading, disparaging or demeaning'' personal attacks on 
opposition candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``These questions will be asked of all the candidates and we  
expect a response,'' said Amber Khan, Alliance spokeswoman. 
``Candidates must take responsibility for the impact and culture 
they create through their campaigning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Alliance asked campaigns that do not endorse the ``Framework  
of Civility'' to write their own codes of conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Former American Red Cross president  
Elizabeth Dole, flexing her organizational muscle, said Wednesday 
she's garnered campaign leaders in each of Iowa's 99 counties. 
</P>
<P>
	The move demonstrates that her campaign has developed  
organizational strength crucial to success in next winter's 
precinct caucuses, and builds on her third-place showing in last 
month's GOP straw poll, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign eventually will have an organizational presence at  
the precinct level, Dole told The Associated Press in an interview. 
The state has more than 2,000 precincts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to take it to the next level,'' said Dole. ``That  
shows a very high level of energy and commitment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to luring traditional Republicans, Dole said she's  
attracted new people to politics, particularly women and young 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're building an invisible army of new supporters,'' Dole  
said. ``I welcome these first-time activists to our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Next winter's caucuses are neighborhood meetings where activists  
declare their preference, and often become a full evening of 
political arguments. They require far more commitment than voting 
in a primary. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Bob Dole got in hot water earlier this  
year when he questioned whether his wife, GOP presidential hopeful 
Elizabeth Dole, could raise enough money to be viable in the 2000 
race. Now, it seems, he's at it again. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Kansas senator, in Wednesday's Rochester Democrat and  
Chronicle, said the distance between front-runner Texas Gov. George 
W. Bush and his rivals for the GOP nomination might be 
insurmountable. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one anticipated this much of a spread,'' the 1996 GOP  
presidential nominee told the paper, while saying the situation 
could change quickly: ``One day can be a lifetime in politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole also said his wife was having trouble raising funds and  
that he was not sure how long she would be in the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am counting on her to go further,'' he said. ``We'll just  
have to wait to see what develops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Associated Press Writers Douglas Kiker and Mike Glover  
contributed to this report. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
