<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man, Pizza Hut Settle Over Slaying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A man acquitted of killing his wife and her  
manager at a Pizza Hut restaurant has settled a claim against the 
company for failing to provide adequate security and protection for 
$500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Richard Miller was acquitted of killing Nancy Marie  
Miller, 25, and Steven J. Snow, 35, at the Brandon restaurant in 
May 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	He filed a civil lawsuit against the Dallas-based company three  
months later. The case had been scheduled for trial next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Pizza Hut resolved the case without admitting fault, Jay  
Allison, company spokesman, said Wednesday. He said Pizza Hut was 
concerned about Miller's children and pleased it didn't have to 
endure a lengthy public trial. Pizza Hut is owned by Tricon Global 
Restaurants, which also owns KFC and Taco Bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said Miller killed his wife and Snow in a jealous  
rage and then staged the robbery, taking more than $800 from the 
safe. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, 33, maintains he drove to the restaurant to check on his  
wife when she didn't come home from her waitressing shift. Inside 
the restaurant, her and Snow dead from gunshot wounds to the head. 
</P>
<P>
	A defense witness testified at Miller's trial she saw two people  
matching the descriptions of Ms. Miller and Snow in the restaurant 
doorway the night they died. They appeared to be arguing with a man 
who was not Miller, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one else has been charged with the killings, and the  
investigation ended after Miller's acquittal, authorities said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
