<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Korea Earns $1B in Missile Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- North Korea has sold at least 490  
Soviet-style Scud missiles to Pakistan, India and Middle Eastern 
countries since 1991, a South Korean scholar said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The sales have earned the Asian country $1 billion a year in  
badly needed cash, said Kim Chul-hwan, a professor at the Korean 
National Defense University 
</P>
<P>
	``North Korea builds missiles for exports,'' he said at an  
international seminar. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington has identified North Korea as the world's No. 1  
exporter of missile equipment and technology. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, the North's communist government pledged to freeze  
testing of its long-range missiles during talks with the United 
States on improving relations. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim said North Korea completed plants in 1991 that enable the  
country to produce up to 150 Scud-B and Scud-C missiles a year. 
</P>
<P>
	So far North Korea has sold 160 Scud-Bs to Iran, 100 to Iraq and  
18 to the United Arab Emirates, Kim said. The Scud-B is believed to 
have been modified from the old Soviet design and to have a range 
of 210 miles, the distance between New York and Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Syria has bought 150 North Korean Scud-Cs, which have a range of  
341 miles. Iran bought 42, and India bought 20, Kim said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1996, the United States has held a series of talks with  
North Korea on curbing its development and export of missiles. 
North Korea has rebuffed U.S. demands, saying self-defense is the 
inalienable right of any sovereign nation. 
</P>
<P>
	It reportedly has demanded $1 billion annually for three years  
in return for stopping exports of missiles and missile technology. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 09:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Roddy Doyle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- Three years have passed since the world  
last heard from Roddy Doyle, who from his coarse-witted debut, 
``The Commitments,'' has always rooted his best-selling books in 
the everyday urban Dublin he knows so well. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle's ear for authentically earthy, screenplay-friendly  
dialogue remains evident in his latest novel. But in many ways, ``A 
Star Called Henry'' takes the schoolteacher-turned-author into 
ambitious new territory certain to win him new fans -- and lose him 
some old ones. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle is billing the novel as the first in a trilogy to follow  
the larger-than-life travails of Dublin slum kid Henry Smart and, 
through him, to depict the divisive, bloody birth of an independent 
Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to emulate Charles Dickens, to write about a very old  
man, and go right from the very beginning of his life to the end. 
It became a bigger book than I thought it would be,'' Doyle, 41, 
said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle has no feel for how compelling his fictional hero will  
prove to others, ``but I've become so engrossed in the character 
that I won't let Henry Smart go until he's finished,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Like so many of his creations, Doyle -- with his close-shaven  
head, round wire-framed specs and single stud earring -- gives 
people the impression of being a fairly dogged, stubborn Dub 
himself. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been crafting his new trilogy since 1995, when he  
finished ``The Woman Who Walked Into Doors,'' about a Dublin mother 
trapped in a brutally abusive marriage. He considers that his best 
book, though it fared least well overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	He claims not to care how well ``Henry'' sells internationally  
either, though it has already received immediate critical acclaim 
in his homeland and risen to the top of best-seller lists. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sales is no way to measure the success of anything, except  
maybe bread,'' he said dismissively. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle takes lasting comfort from the worldwide triumph of  
``Paddy Clarke Ha Ha Ha,'' his 1993 portrait of a boy coping with 
the collapse of his parents' marriage, which won the Booker, 
Britain's top literary prize. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll never write a more successful book than `Paddy Clarke.' I  
know that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Combined with the enduring popularity of his career-launching  
trilogy of wisecracking tales set in his native north Dublin -- 
``The Commitments,'' ``The Snapper'' and ``The Van'' -- Doyle today 
has the financial freedom to write what he wants. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Henry,'' Doyle is at his most grim, brutal and morally  
gray. His portrait of tenement life in early 20th-century Dublin, 
in which the child Henry must survive as a rat-catching, 
cattle-thieving orphan, makes the crushing poverty of Frank 
McCourt's 1950s Limerick in ``Angela's Ashes'' seem downright 
comfy. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry is a survivor, intelligent and strong beyond his years. He  
also has a hint of both Leonard Zelig and Forrest Gump in him: He's 
near the center of threshold events, but never really in the frame. 
</P>
<P>
	A natural born killer, Henry survives the rebel Easter Rising of  
1916 and graduates into the ranks of Irish Republican Army leader 
Michael Collins' hand-picked assassins, executing men in their beds 
or on lonely roadsides as part of the rebels' merciless and 
ultimately successful campaign to wrest most of Ireland from 
Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	Along the way, Doyle cuts Ireland's founding fathers down to  
size and skewers several romantic notions held sacred by Irish 
nationalism. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry describes the original leaders of the IRA and its  
affiliated Sinn Fein party as ``a little gang of cranky nuts and 
bad poets'' made attractive only by the British authorities' 
tendency to execute them. 
</P>
<P>
	Eamon de Valera appears briefly alongside Henry who, nonplussed,  
notes simply that the future leader of the Irish Republic was 
wearing red socks and smelled bad. 
</P>
<P>
	By the bitter end of this breakneck-paced novel, Henry has  
discovered that his leaders have no intention of making Ireland a 
more equal or free society. His protege in the IRA, Ivan, has 
graduated from landless country bumpkin into a scheming 
power-broker and racketeer lording it over his home county of 
Tipperary. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have cattle, land, a cut of the creameries, pubs. Every  
bloody thing. I'm even on the Sunday collections. ... Nobody works 
without the nod from Ivan,'' he tells Henry, who in the same 
illusion-shattering conversation learns his bosses in Dublin want 
him dead. 
</P>
<P>
	An impressively eclectic bibliography at the end of the book  
testifies to Doyle's efforts to reconstruct a period and place that 
has been largely wiped from the face of modern, economically 
booming Dublin. 
</P>
<P>
	One conclusion Doyle hits hard, in keeping with his  
working-class and socialist sympathies, is that the IRA's fight for 
independence was led by power-hungry opportunists who replaced the 
injustices of British rule with their own corrupt, conservative 
regime. 
</P>
<P>
	``I must admit, though, I'm very happy living in the Republic of  
Ireland,'' Doyle said. ``I live with the consequences of all that 
violence, and I wouldn't want to live anywhere else. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I wanted to face the reality of that violence. I didn't  
want to glamorize it. I wanted to do away with the innocent picture 
that I was given when I was a kid about the battle between the 
goodies and the baddies. In `Henry,' there's good in the bad, and 
bad in the good -- human beings, really.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle is unconcerned that foreign readers may not know enough  
about his country's past to get it all. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, people who aren't familiar with Irish history are  
going to come up against the fence in this book and wonder what 
it's all about,'' he said. ``But I tried to keep the history 
lessons to a minimum. And fiction makes bad history anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no real place for footnotes in fiction. I just write  
as clearly as I possibly can do. I tend not to think about 
potential audiences abroad. ... When I read `War and Peace' as a 
kid, I didn't know who all these generals were, but I still had a 
ball reading it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle has just finished a screenplay, a romantic comedy called  
``When Brendan Met Trudy.'' The movie is set in Dublin and filming 
is about to start. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also well into his second volume of the trilogy, in which  
Henry Smart sets sail first for England, then the United States, 
presumably to cast an iconoclastic eye on the immigrant experience 
-- and to stretch his creator's literary skills even farther. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle said he's considering moving his wife and three children  
temporarily to America to do research and to discover, he joked, 
``what it's like to live someplace where summer's not exactly the 
same as winter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	An excerpt from Roddy Doyle's historical novel ``A Star Called  
Henry.'' Here, the fictional protagonist describes how his IRA 
boss, the real-life Michael Collins, outwits Dublin's police 
(``rozzers'') by hiding in plain sight: 

</P>
<P>
	``Collins was full of plans and skits that dropped us there with  
admiration, obvious notions that no one ever worded but him. He 
slept in the beds of men who'd just been arrested -- the rozzers 
would never search the same house twice in a night, especially when 
they'd found their man the first time. The safest bed in town, he 
said. He was a plastic man. Everyone knew him but no one could 
describe him. His hair was brown, fair and black. He was broad but 
not particularly tall; he was the tallest man in the room. He grew 
a moustache and the years grew with it; he filled out, became 
middle-aged. He shaved it and became a lad again, much too young to 
be Michael Collins. He smiled at the rozzers when he met them at 
the roadblocks; he helped them in every detail; he joined them. He 
never hid in a coat, behind a collar. 
</P>
<P>
	``---- Michael Collins, he said once in answer to a young, fresh  
rozzer's inquiry. I was with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He laughed. We laughed. They laughed.  
</P>
<P>
	``---- I'm just having you on, he said. In a cap or muffler or  
less impressive in the overcoat, he'd have got a butt of a rifle in 
the chops. Not Mick, though. He was a company director, a man about 
town, a class above them and one of their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``---- Michael Collins, I said to the same question.  
</P>
<P>
	``They laughed again. They let me get away with it because I was  
with Michael Collins. 
</P>
<P>
	``---- Keep it up, lads, said Collins as we passed through the  
block. ---- You'll soon catch the bastard. And you can give him a 
root in the hole for me. 
</P>
<P>
	``---- Good-night, sir.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
