<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aguiar Knows Bidwell's Plight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Louie Aguiar keeps getting second  
chances. He hopes Josh Bidwell gets one too. 
</P>
<P>
	The Green Bay Packers on Monday signed Aguiar, a nine-year  
veteran punter, to replace Bidwell, who is out for the season while 
undergoing treatment for testicular cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a battle Aguiar knows all too well. He beat his own  
testicular cancer last year with surgery and radiation treatments, 
and he returned to play with the Kansas City Chiefs last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``With cancer, you don't know how long it will be there,'' he  
said. ``You don't know how far it has spread. You can never rest 
easy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguiar was cut by the Chiefs on Sept. 5 in favor of rookie  
Daniel Pope. In Green Bay, he takes the place of Bidwell, another 
rookie expected to be his team's punter of the future. 
</P>
<P>
	Aguiar worked out with the Packers for the first time on  
Wednesday. He'll make his debut at Detroit on Sunday, and he'll 
kick at Lambeau Field for the first time in his career next Sunday 
against Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Even after the Chiefs released him, the perpetually cheerful  
punter never doubted he would get another opportunity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew there would be a shot because I knew I could still play  
in this league,'' Aguiar said. ``I've been through a lot. I wasn't 
ready to walk away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bidwell never got a chance to kick in a regular season game for  
the Packers. A fourth-round draft pick from Oregon, he discovered 
the cancer shortly before Green Bay's final preseason game against 
Miami and returned to Oregon for treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers have said they expect Bidwell to return to the team  
next season, but everything depends on how well he recovers. 
</P>
<P>
	Aguiar heard about Bidwell's cancer while in Kansas City and has  
been trying to reach him by phone for about a week. The two haven't 
spoken yet, but Aguiar said he soon hoped to speak to Bidwell, who 
had additional surgery earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just tell him to never give up and never back down from  
it,'' Aguiar said. ``I know how hard this is, and I know how hard 
you have to work to overcome it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers originally signed rookie Chris Hanson to replace  
Bidwell, but coach Ray Rhodes feels more comfortable with a veteran 
at the position. He also said the colorful Aguiar would be a good 
addition to the Packers locker room atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a guy that I've known a lot about for a lot of years,''  
Rhodes said. ``He's one of those guys that grows on you when you're 
around him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like many cancer survivors, Aguiar, 33, took great pride in  
cyclist Lance Armstrong's victory at the Tour de France this 
summer. Armstrong was out of action for two years while battling 
his testicular cancer, while Aguiar needed only three months. 
</P>
<P>
	``His was 10 times worse than mine,'' Aguiar said. ``I only had  
very minimal radiation treatments, so I was grateful for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguiar must undergo CAT scans every six months to determine  
whether the cancer has returned. He also conducts self-examinations 
every three weeks, something he urges more men to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know how guys are. Nobody wants to go to the doctor,'' he  
said. ``But the examinations are something you can do to help 
yourself, and they're easy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguiar's quick punting motion -- he had just one kick blocked in  
631 career attempts -- will be beneficial in poor weather conditions 
at Lambeau Field. Aguiar said Eagles punter Sean Landeta, who 
kicked for the Packers last season, recommended Green Bay highly. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said it was a great team to join and a great city to play  
in,'' Aguiar said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
