<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Wants To Cut Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It's tricky business, AT&AMP;T has found, to shrink  
and expand at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	Confronted with a revenue-draining price war in long distance,  
yet determined to press ahead with its expensive bet on using cable 
TV wires for Internet and telephone service, AT&AMP;T is looking to cut 
more jobs on top of the 20,000 eliminated last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's largest long-distance telephone and cable company  
said Wednesday it froze hiring about a month ago to help meet those 
challenges, which come on top of a pledge made in April to cut $2 
billion in expenses by the end of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials said certain units, especially long-distance  
and administrative, will have to shrink so that rapid-growers such 
as the wireless and Internet divisions can flourish. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T wouldn't rule out layoffs, but officials on Wednesday  
expressed hope that staff reductions can be achieved through 
attrition and redeployment. 
</P>
<P>
	Notably, AT&AMP;T did add 3,000 jobs in the second quarter to its  
Broadband and Internet Services division, which encompasses the new 
consumer offerings in cable TV, local telephone service and 
high-speed Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	And this week, AT&AMP;T revealed plans to open 400 to 500 stores for  
wireless products and as many as 26 more of its Internet Data 
Centers. The centers enable businesses to put the computers that 
operate their Web sites in a facility that's directly connected to 
a major ``backbone'' in AT&AMP;T's fiber-optic network. 
</P>
<P>
	``While we must reduce our costs, we are not taking a  
cookie-cutter approach,'' Mirian Graddick, AT&AMP;T executive vice 
president for human resources, wrote in a message to employees to 
ease worries sparked by news reports that there might be widespread 
job cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	It's really no mystery why AT&AMP;T finds itself battling on so many  
fronts considering the radical makeover the former telephone 
monopoly has undergone to lessen its overwhelming dependence on a 
long-distance market where profits are getting harder to come by. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the obvious exception of a costly price war in long  
distance, sparked by the nickel-a-minute rates introduced by Sprint 
and MCI WorldCom last month, AT&AMP;T has actually invited most of its 
many perils. 
</P>
<P>
	That's been the feisty management style of Chief Executive C.  
Michael Armstrong, who's already slashed 20,000 jobs and $1.6 
billion in expenses since he came aboard less than two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong has also moved to spend more than $100 billion on  
acquisitions in that short span, snaring Tele-Communications Inc. 
and MediaOne Group, two of the nation's four biggest cable TV 
companies, in a bid to create a new-age communications company. 
</P>
<P>
	It will require billions of dollars more to upgrade those cable  
systems to handle the floods of two-way, high-speed communications 
involved with co-mingling voice, video, and Internet services. 
</P>
<P>
	At last count, the company had about 149,000 workers, up from  
108,000 at the start of the year, although most of the increase 
came from the addition of more than 30,000 TCI employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Slightly more than a third of AT&AMP;T's staff are employed in its  
consumer and business long-distance division, which still accounts 
for 80 percent of the company's revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	That business is stagnant thanks to the growth of smaller rivals  
through aggressive price cuts. By contrast, AT&AMP;T's wireless 
telephone unit employs 16,000 people and is expected to post 43 
percent revenue growth this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Another third of the workforce is employed in general  
administrative work and other areas such as research and 
development. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's attrition rate -- employees who retire or quit --  
averages 8 percent a year, said company spokesman Burke Stinson. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
