<DOCNO> APW19990915.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 07:41:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson, Jones Benefit From Sked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Michael Johnson and Marion Jones have been given  
the chance to win multiple gold medals at next year's Sydney 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the long-delayed competition schedule approved for track  
and field events in Sydney, Johnson will be able to attempt a 
repeat of his historic Olympic double in the 200 and 400 meters and 
Jones can bid for an unprecedented five golds. 
</P>
<P>
	The schedule released today also allows for tries at doubles by  
sprinter Maurice Greene, the world champion in the 100 and 200; 
Ethiopia's Haile Gebrselassie, world and Olympic champion at 10,000 
and world record-holder at 5,000; and Russia's Svetlana Masterkova, 
the 1996 Olympic champion in the 800 and 1,500. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Amateur Athletic Federation, the sport's  
governing body, arranged the schedule specifically so top stars 
could compete in more than one event. 
</P>
<P>
	IAAF spokesman Giorgio Reineri said particular attention was  
given to accommodating Johnson and Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	In Atlanta, Johnson became the first man in history to complete  
a 200-400 Olympic double, setting a world record in the 200 in the 
process. After two relatively modest seasons, Johnson reasserted 
his greatness at last month's World Championships in Seville, 
Spain, breaking the 11-year-old world record in the 400. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said his next goal is to defend both titles in Sydney,  
where he could face Greene in a highly anticipated 200-meter 
showdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, meanwhile, has said she intends to win a record five gold  
medals: in the 100, 200, long jump and both relays. She won the 100 
in Seville, but her bid for four golds was dashed when she settled 
for bronze in the long jump, her weakest event. Jones' season came 
to an end when she collapsed with back spasms in the 200 
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Track and field events in Sydney will be held from Sept. 22 to  
Oct. 1, with a day off on Sept. 26. 
</P>
<P>
	The timetable allows at least one rest day between semifinals  
and finals of races of 800 meters and more, and the 400 meter 
hurdles. A rest day was also incorporated between the qualification 
rounds and finals of jumping events. 
</P>
<P>
	``This schedule protects the rights of the athletes to compete  
at the highest level without incurring any risks to their health, 
while offering spectators a balanced distribution of finals 
throughout the nine days of competition,'' IAAF president Primo 
Nebiolo said in a statement Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The schedule was approved Tuesday in Monte Carlo, Monaco, by the  
IAAF's technical delegates and representatives of the Sydney 
organizing committee (SOCOG), ending a protracted dispute between 
the two sides. 
</P>
<P>
	Sydney officials, accusing the IAAF of dragging its feet on the  
schedule, put tickets on sale earlier this summer based on a 
timetable that had not been authorized by the world body. The IAAF 
criticized SOCOG and said it wanted to make several changes, mainly 
to allow for a rest day between the semifinals and finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the final schedule, 11 finals were moved to different days  
than those on the ticket order form. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sydney won its main battle: the date of the women's 400  
final (Monday, Sept. 25) remains unchanged. The women's 400 is the 
highest demand event in Australia because Cathy Freeman, 
Australia's two-time world champion, is expected to be a favorite 
for the gold. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made an exception for the 400 meters out of respect for the  
Australian public,'' Reineri said. ``But the principle of having a 
day of rest was respected in all other events.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reineri said the negotiations over the schedule had nothing to  
do with the IAAF's long-running demands for free tickets and a 
greater share of Olympic television revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	Those matters will be addressed later this month at a meeting  
between Nebiolo and International Olympic Committee president Juan 
Antonio Samaranch. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 07:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Curbing Campaign Finance Passed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bipartisan legislation to curb the influence  
of money in political campaigns won House passage late Tuesday 
night despite vociferous complaints from conservative Republicans 
that it violates freedom of speech. 
</P>
<P>
	The 252-177 vote sent the bill to an uncertain fate in the  
Senate, where GOP opponents are threatening to renew a filibuster 
that killed similar campaign finance legislation a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reach and influence of special interests have grown out of  
control,'' argued Rep. Marge Roukema of New Jersey, one of dozens 
of Republicans to join with Democrats in support of the measure, 
which also enjoys President Clinton's backing. ``As a consequence, 
people believe their elected officials are bought and paid for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. John Doolittle, R-Calif., said the measure, with its  
ban on unregulated ``soft money'' contributions and restrictions on 
certain campaign ads, would ``abridge our precious God-given right 
to speak.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House Republican leadership backed efforts to derail the  
measure or rework it after concluding it could disadvantage GOP 
candidates and leave them vulnerable to attacks by organized labor. 
</P>
<P>
	But in long day of debate on the House floor, a coalition led by  
Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Martin Meehan, D-Mass., 
easily fended off what were characterized as several ``poison 
pill'' amendments. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them were proposals to triple the 25-year-old limits on  
contributions, allowing donors to give up to $3,000 to individual 
candidates and $75,000 overall for any campaign cycle. Both were 
rejected by margins of more than 2-1, indicating that supporters of 
the legislation had the votes to prevail on the final roll call, as 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	One amendment that cleared would require non-office holders who  
campaign for office to reimburse the government for the costs of 
transportation. Democrats complained the provision was aimed solely 
at First lady Hillary Clinton, who is making the rounds in her 
unannounced New York Senate campaign with a complement of Secret 
Service agents. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, 197 Democrats, 54 Republicans and one independent voted  
for the bill's passage, while 164 Republicans and 13 Democrats were 
opposed. The tally was nearly identical to last year's vote of 
252-179. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, as in 1998, GOP opponents in the Senate are ready  
with a filibuster, and prospects for final passage are uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	As drafted in the House, the bill would ban the use of soft  
money in federal campaigns. Unlike hard money donations, which are 
restricted in size, soft money donations are unlimited and 
unregulated by the federal government. Increasingly, they are 
prized by political parties and certain politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the bill would impose limits on certain types of  
political advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcast commercials within 60 days of an election that made  
use of the name or likeness of a candidate would have to be paid 
for with hard money contributions, which are limited in size. So, 
too, would any print or broadcast commercial that contained an 
``unmistakable or unambiguous'' appeal for the election or defeat 
of a federal candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Those provisions are designed to crack down on thinly veiled  
attacks ads that are now paid for with soft money. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation produced a spirited debate on the House floor  
that ranged from bedrock constitutional issues to matters of overt 
partisan politics. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Whip Tom DeLay argued that the measure  
represented ``the mother of all government regulation'' and would 
erode the First Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Roger Wicker of Mississippi agreed, and added that for  
``liberal advocates this bill is really about party politics. The 
big labor bosses use the forced dues of their union members to 
further their political goals,'' he added, and the legislation 
would do nothing to change that. 
</P>
<P>
	Meehan dismissed the complaints about the First Amendment as  
ungrounded. ``When they say free speech, they mean big money,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shays said the measure was designed to enforce a ban on  
corporate campaign donations that has been on the books since 1907, 
and a similar ban on the use of union dues dating to 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Mike Castle, R-Del., said, ``It should concern every one of  
us that there are corporations, there are labor unions, there are 
organizations out there'' whose members make six-figure 
contributions. ``If anyone thinks they're doing it because they 
believe in good government, then they need to look at the 
underlying legislation they're supporting,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shays and Meehan had wanted to have the debate last spring, to  
give their Senate allies more time to battle the threatened 
filibuster there. 
</P>
<P>
	But House GOP leaders successfully delayed the measure, and  
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., stared down rebels in his own 
rank-and-file who had pressured him to step up the timetable. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind the scenes, the GOP hierarchy also emphasized the  
political threat to Republican candidates. The party chairman, Jim 
Nicholson, and Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, who heads the Republican 
campaign committee, met privately with GOP lawmakers last month and 
told them the party enjoyed a $40 million soft money advantage over 
Democrats in the 1997-1998 election cycle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
