<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Move Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures tumbled Wednesday on the Chicago  
Board of Trade as rains improved crop prospects. Soybean and other 
grain futures also retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Overnight rains in the southwestern plains combined with weak  
export demand drove wheat prices sharply lower. The rains doused 
fields in Texas and Kansas with farmers are poised to sow winter 
wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	Weather beneficial to the harvest also led soybean futures  
lower, while corn joined the trend on general market pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 12 1/2 cents to $2.61 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn fell 2 1/2 cents to $2.12 1/4 a bushel; December oats fell 
2 cents to $1.12 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans fell 12 3/4 cents to 
$4.89 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork futures declined on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle fell .20 cent to 67.67 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .40 cent to 79.97 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs fell .33 cent to 42.77 cents a pound; February frozen 
pork bellies fell .05 cent to 54.02 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
