<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Protection of Treasures Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- From Pennsylvania's Amish farmland to an  
Indonesian temple, the world's treasures are under fire from war, 
government policies and the elements, a preservation group said 
Tuesday in announcing its list of the 100 most endangered sites. 
</P>
<P>
	The annual list from the World Monuments Fund seeks to preserve  
historic and modern treasures, as well as man-made landscapes. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based nonprofit group is raising millions of  
dollars a year ``to save these irreplaceable sites that define the 
history and the humanity of the peoples of the world,'' said fund 
president Bonnie Burnham. 
</P>
<P>
	In Bosnia, military attacks have ravaged the city of Mostar,  
whose 16th-century urban landscape is now vulnerable to the 
elements, vandalism and collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	In Peru, tourism is threatening the 15th-century Inca City of  
Machu Picchu, where a government-endorsed plan to build a cable car 
could destroy the site's serene, isolated quality, the group said. 
Another ancient treasure -- the Valley of the Kings in Luxor, Egypt 
-- is swamped by tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	The sea is endangering the Tanah Lot Temple on the island of  
Bali. The beauty of the temple, which honors sea gods, has been 
compromised by 100 concrete supports installed along the shoreline 
to protect it. 
</P>
<P>
	In Pennsylvania's Lancaster County, a proposed superhighway  
would cut through the farmland home of the Amish and Mennonite 
communities, altering one of America's most scenic landscapes. 
</P>
<P>
	The list, begun in 1996, is selected by an expert nine-member  
panel from nominations submitted by governments, U.S. embassies, 
cultural and preservation groups and professionals. There are sites 
in Africa, Asia, the Middle East, Europe, North and South America, 
and the Caribbean. 
</P>
<P>
	A founding sponsor, American Express, has put up $10 million. Up  
to $6 million a year comes from governments, businesses, and 
individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund was created in 1965 by a retired U.S. Army officer,  
Col. James Gray, who helped stabilize the tower in Pisa. The fund 
now supports 62 conservation projects worldwide. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
