<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Raymond Carver Stories Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT ANGELES, Wash. (AP) -- It took more than a decade after  
writer Raymond Carver's death for his widow, poet Tess Gallagher, 
to sit down and sort through the old papers in his desk. 
</P>
<P>
	But when she finally felt the time was right, Gallagher  
unearthed a treasure -- three unpublished stories Carver revised 
several times but never polished. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the stories have been published in Esquire, and the third  
will appear next year in the magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	``These will be the last writings of Ray's to offer of this  
nature. It's been lovely to have his stories in the house again, of 
course. A great excitement and a pleasure,'' Gallagher said this 
week in an e-mail interview from Italy, where she is attending a 
literary festival. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Carver's death from lung cancer at age 50, his fans have  
wondered whether more of his work existed. Many literary critics 
say the blue-collar author of such award-winning works as 
``Cathedral,'' ``Where I'm Calling From'' and ``Short Cuts'' died 
at the height of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher suspected Carver's desk might contain something  
special, but she had some misgivings about searching through it. As 
executor of his estate, she feared new unpublished tales would lead 
to a protracted bidding war. An award-winning writer herself, she 
suspected the resulting hubbub would leave her no time to work. 
</P>
<P>
	So she put off the task until she could find an editor she  
trusted. That person was Jay Woodruff, a friend and senior editor 
at Esquire. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, Woodruff flew from New York to Gallagher's rustic Port  
Angeles home at the foot of the Olympic Mountains to spend a day 
rummaging through Carver's desk. It wasn't until evening, and the 
last drawer, when Gallagher found the three stories dating back to 
the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	``As someone who has read almost everything that Carver had ever  
published, everything was fascinating to me,'' Woodruff said. ``The 
notes, the scraps, the fragments and pieces of a working writer's 
life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woodruff didn't need to do much editing -- just ``light  
housekeeping,'' as Gallagher put it. 
</P>
<P>
	``These aren't stories he wrote when he was 20 and put aside,''  
Woodruff said. ``These are stories he was writing in the mid-80s 
when he was at the absolute peak of his power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first tale, ``Kindling,'' was published in Esquire's July  
summer fiction issue. In the story, a recovering alcoholic purges 
himself of his past through the metaphor of chopping wood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vandals,'' which appears in Esquire's October issue, examines  
the definition of vandalism as the story twists and turns through a 
love triangle. A third piece, ``Dreams,'' will be published 
sometime next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The three stories and two other unpublished Carver works will be  
published by Knopf in a soon-to-be expanded edition of ``No Heroics 
Please,'' a collection of Carver's stories. 
</P>
<P>
	The two other stories were found this summer in the Charvat  
Fiction Collection at Ohio State University, where Carver used to 
sell some of his papers when he was low on money. William Stull, 
who edited Carver collections and wrote his biography, made the 
discovery along with his wife, Maureen P. Carroll. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's fair to say that none of them would rank with his  
greatest stories,'' said Gary Fisketjon, editor at large at Knopf 
publishing, ``but collectively, the five were very strong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Port Angeles library, where a meeting room is dedicated  
to Carver, librarians say Gallagher was wise to wait. In light of 
recently published ``lost'' works by Ernest Hemingway and Louisa 
May Alcott, they say a good editor is essential. 
</P>
<P>
	``With some authors, their books became formulaic and maybe they  
shouldn't be published unless it's different from what they 
normally do,'' said Genie Devine, a reference librarian who was 
pleased with the newly discovered Carver works. 
</P>
<P>
	Devine said fans from as far away as Japan and Australia come in  
to ask where Carver is buried. Some borrow first editions and end 
up keeping them as souvenirs. 
</P>
<P>
	At Carver's grave, which overlooks the Strait of Juan de Fuca  
from a wind-swept bluff, visitors from around the world leave their 
thoughts in a notebook inside a small metal box. Gallagher, whose 
black granite headstone already rests next to Carver's, writes back 
to them all. 
</P>
<P>
	``I also promised him on his death bed that I would look after  
things,'' she said. ``I keep that promise every day.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
