<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disney Not Close to Angels Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- While the Walt Disney Co. is open to an  
offer, it doesn't appear close to a deal to sell either the Anaheim 
Angels or the NHL's Mighty Ducks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's been highly exaggerated,'' Tony Tavares,  
president of Disney subsidiary Anaheim Sports Inc. said Wednesday 
at the baseball owners' meetings. ``It's not actively being 
shopped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tavares said Disney was approached by people interested in the  
teams about four months ago and was ``in a listening mode.'' But he 
said talks hadn't even progressed to the point where the team would 
seek permission from the commissioner's office to show its books to 
prospective suitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Bud Selig also said no deal is imminent but made it  
sound as if Disney definitely wants out of baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that they're selling is a matter of concern,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney took control of the Angels from Gene Autry in March 1996  
and bought a 100 percent interest following his death last year. 
Tavares said the Angels' poor performance -- they are 61-85, 26 1/2 
games behind first-place Texas in the AL West -- was not a factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question is not whether they're satisfied with how the  
teams have gone,'' Tavares said. ``It would be whether or not this 
is on point for their strategic goals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tavares likened people who express interest in becoming sports  
team owners to ``people who come into an auto dealership and kick 
the tires.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, columnist Peter Gammons wrote for ESPN.com  
that Disney has ``completed the parameters of a deal'' to sell the 
baseball and hockey clubs to billionaire Henry Nicholas III for 
$650 million. ESPN.com is a Web site for Disney-owned cable 
broadcaster ESPN. 
</P>
<P>
	While some analysts valued an Angels-Mighty Ducks package at  
$375 million to $425 million, Nicholas ``stepped up and closed the 
deal,'' the ESPN.com said. Nicholas is president and chief 
executive of Broadcom Corp. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
