<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft To Acquire Visio Corp. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. is buying Visio Corp., a leading  
maker of diagramming and technical drawing software, in a $1.3 
billion stock deal that helps Microsoft fill a gap in its line of 
business products. 
</P>
<P>
	Visio software lets professionals such as corporate  
administrators and designers make flow and organizational charts 
and more technical drawings such as engineering schematics. The 
purchase will help Microsoft strengthen its grip on the market for 
business productivity software, already dominated by its Office 
suite of word processing, spreadsheet and presentation products. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are very few areas Microsoft is not a player in. This is  
one of them,'' said Frank Catalano, an industry analyst in Renton, 
Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	Visio, founded in 1990, says its technical drawing software is  
used by 3 million customers and posted $166 million in sales last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft said it has no plans to integrate Visio's software  
into its existing business software and would continue to sell it 
as a separate product. Microsoft, which also dominates the market 
for operating programs that control a computer's basic functions, 
is battling an antitrust lawsuit that alleges it unfairly blends in 
new software features to squeeze out other technology companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft chose to acquire Visio rather than develop similar  
software in-house because Visio has a well-known product with loyal 
customers, said Microsoft senior vice president Bob Muglia. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot more attractive for us to use our sales force (to  
distribute Visio's established products) than to use an unknown 
product,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies said it was too early to say if any of Visio's 700  
workers would be cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Each share of Visio common stock will be exchanged for .45  
shares of Microsoft common stock. The transaction, subject to 
regulatory review and approval by Visio shareholders, is expected 
to close by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Visio's stock price shot up 19 percent, or $6.37 1/2 a share to  
$39.87 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. Microsoft, also traded on 
Nasdaq, was down $2.50 to $92.56 1/4 a share. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
