<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sponsor Fires Golfer John Daly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	John Daly, a recovering alcoholic and winner of two major  
championships, was fired by his main sponsor today because Callaway 
Golf said he violated a contract clause to not drink or gamble, 
then refused to get help. 
</P>
<P>
	``We care a great deal about John as a person, a golfer and a  
friend and we're grateful for the period of time he successfully 
supported the company and its products,'' said Ely Callaway, the 
80-year-old chairman who hired Daly two years ago when other 
sponsors dropped him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Regrettably, we cannot continue to have John as a company  
representative when he is not prepared to take the future steps 
that we feel are necessary to deal with the alcohol and gambling 
problems facing him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daly was returning home to Arkansas from Callaway headquarters  
in Carlsbad, Calif., and could not immediately be reached for 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Callaway did not say when or where Daly violated the drinking  
and gambling clauses, only that it was confirmed by one of its 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The 33-year-old Daly returned to tournament play three weeks ago  
in the Reno-Tahoe Open, where he missed the cut. He had taken time 
off after the U.S. Open, where he was so frustrated that he hit a 
moving ball with his putter, took an 11 on the hole and later said 
he would never play the U.S. Open again. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly became one of the most exciting and volatile personalities  
in golf since he came out of nowhere to win the 1991 PGA 
Championship, thrilling galleries with his ``Grip It and Rip It'' 
style that made him the game's longest hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	But he was just as wild off the course as he was off the tee.  
</P>
<P>
	He went through alcohol rehab at the end of 1992 and won the  
British Open at St. Andrews in 1995. Two years later, he went on a 
drinking binge during The Players Championship that landed him in 
rehab again. 
</P>
<P>
	That cost him his second wife and his contract with Wilson, the  
Callaway gave him another chance, putting its Big Bertha products 
into the hands of a player who has led the PGA Tour in driving 
distance every season but one since 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly has said he has not had a drink since, and the recovery was  
clearly taking a toll. He walked off the course midway through the 
second round of the U.S. Open in 1997, and last year in Vancouver 
got a severe case of the shakes on the 15th green. 
</P>
<P>
	Callaway recently described Daly's ongoing battle as the most  
difficult recovery of any alcoholic. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's trying to recover on the stage of one the more stressful,  
difficult games on earth, and be a champion in front of millions,'' 
Callaway said in late July. ``I don't know of anybody who has ever 
tried to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company begged Daly to seek help and offered to pay for him  
to see a leading expert in alcohol and gambling addictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We urged him with all of our abilities,'' Callaway said. ``He  
just doesn't feel that's necessary.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
