<HEADLINE> Former Avon Executive Leading Excel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Excel Communications Inc., vying with Frontier  
Corp. to be the nation's No. 5 long distance company, has hired a 
former Avon North America executive as its chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Christina Gold replaces Excel founder Kenny Troutt, who will  
remain chairman of the $1.3 billion direct selling unit of 
Canada-based Teleglobe Inc., Excel announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Gold spent 28 years at Avon, rising to become president of  
the North American unit and executive vice president for global 
sales. She left in early 1998 after being passed over for chief 
executive and founded a direct-selling consulting firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointment makes Ms. Gold one of a handful of women running  
U.S. companies with annual sales of more than $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas-based Excel is a direct seller of telecommunications  
products and services. It merged with Teleglobe in November. 
</P>
<P>
	Excel's revenue for the first half of this year was $723  
million, 23 percent below the first half of 1998. Troutt has blamed 
the poor earnings on software that contained programming bugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Gold said she wants to rebuild the company's independent  
sales force, which is less than half the size it was in 1996, when 
it peaked at about 750,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also hopes to expand globally, taking aim at the  
European market. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
