<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Futures Push Forward  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures surged Wednesday, resuming a year-long rally  
and reaching a 2 1/2-year high after Venezuela pledged to follow 
through on production cutbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, orange juice futures plunged after Hurricane  
Floyd missed groves along the Florida coast, and wheat futures fell 
sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil continued its steady march upward after a one-day  
respite. Crude for delivery in October rose 27 cents to $24.13 on 
the New York Mercantile Exchange after zooming as high as $24.49 -- 
its highest level since Feb. 1, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	That's well over twice what crude sold for last December amid a  
world oil glut. 
</P>
<P>
	Buoyed by continued unity among the Organization of Petroleum  
Export Countries on production cuts, as well as declining U.S. 
inventories, oil prices could continue their rise for the 
foreseeable future, industry analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as we've got very strong OPEC compliance and  
inventories continue to drop, prices could go even higher,'' said 
Bob Morris, an analyst for Paine Webber. 
</P>
<P>
	Comments out of Venezuela fueled Wednesday's market movement as  
President Hugo Chavez insisted his country will stand by the OPEC 
production cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, prices edged downward after he said that if prices  
continue flowing upward, Venezuela will pursue its proposal to 
establish an oil price band system to help stabilize world crude 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``If OPEC wants prices to stabilize, the best thing is for them  
not to say anything,'' said Morris. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether prices push to even higher levels may hinge on next  
week's OPEC meeting in Vienna, Austria. Experts say prices could 
settle if the world's top producers give some indication about 
readjusting quotas or clarify what they think is a good oil price. 
</P>
<P>
	Heating oil prices, which have mirrored crude's climb, were  
unchanged Wednesday at 61.06 cents per gallon for October delivery. 
</P>
<P>
	October unleaded regular gasoline rose .63 cent to 69.05 cents a  
gallon; October natural gas fell .8 cent to $2.628 per million 
British thermal units. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent crude for delivery in October fell 12  
cents to $23.59 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The tension went out of the orange juice futures market after  
Floyd skirted the central Florida coast, pounding the region with 
125 mph winds and heavy rains but apparently leaving groves intact 
in the heart of the nation's top juice-producing region. 
</P>
<P>
	``The orange juice crop is not going to be a problem,'' said  
Elizabeth Steger, president of Citrus Consulting International in 
Orlando. ``I didn't hear anything about damage to the groves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fears that the storm could wreck thousands of trees had driven  
prices to nearly the $1-a-pound level this week. But word that the 
key growing areas were relatively unscathed sent the market down 5 
cents on Wednesday to close at 91.55 cents on the New York 
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures plummeted on the Chicago Board of Trade after  
rains soaked fields in Kansas and Texas overnight, improving crop 
prospects with farmers poised to sow winter wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also was pressured by continued weak export demand.  
Sluggish export demand for U.S. wheat puts more emphasis on the 
winter wheat crop, resulting in exaggerated reactions to weather 
developments. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 12 1/2 cents to $2.61 1/2 a bushel.  
Other grains and soybean futures also retreated -- December corn 
fell 2 1/2 cents to $2.12 1/4 a bushel, December oats fell 2 cents to 
$1.12 3/4 a bushel and November soybeans fell 12 3/4 cents to $4.89 a 
bushel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
