<HEADLINE> Heinz Stock Moves on Merger Rumors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of H.J. Heinz Co. and Bestfoods shot  
higher today even as Bestfoods denied a report the companies were 
discussing a merger that would create the nation's second-biggest 
food company. 
</P>
<P>
	Heinz is the maker of Heinz Ketchup and has a product lineup  
that includes StarKist tuna and Ore-Ida french fries. Bestfoods is 
the maker of Hellman's mayonnaise, Entenmann's baked goods, Skippy 
peanut butter and Knorr soups and sauces. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal reported today that the companies are  
discussing a merger, citing people familiar with the talks. It said 
that because Heinz and Bestfoods are similar in size, it is not 
clear which would lead the combined company. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh-based Heinz has annual sales of $9.3 billion, while  
Bestfoods, of Englewood, N.J., has about $8.4 billion for a 
combined total of $17.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	That would be the third largest food company in the world behind  
Europe's Nestle SA, with $52 billion in sales, and U.S.-based Kraft 
Foods, with $27 billion, the newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The Journal said the deal under discussion would be in the form  
of a merger rather than an acquisition. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bestfoods issued a statement today in which it said ``no  
significant acquisition or combination discussions are in 
progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it was responding to press reports and noted it  
was ``departing on this occasion from its continuing policy of not 
commenting on rumors or market activity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials for Heinz declined to comment. ``Our policy is that we  
don't comment on market rumors,'' said Ted Smyth, senior vice 
president of H.J. Heinz. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading this morning on the New York Stock Exchange, Heinz  
was up 3.6 percent, or by $1.56 1/4, at $44.75 a share, while 
Bestfoods jumped 7.3 percent, or by $3.56 1/4, at $52.50. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
