<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Floyd Batters Boats in Bahamas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Captain Emmanuel Forbes tried to stay  
with his 114-foot freighter, the Forget-Me-Not, as Hurricane 
Floyd's waves battered it at its pier along the Nassau shore. 
</P>
<P>
	When police ordered him to abandon ship, Forbes ignored them.  
Then the ropes holding the 210-ton ship to the pier began breaking. 
Forbes' engineer and second mate left him alone on board and he 
bade them farewell. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then the weather really came,'' he said Wednesday. For several  
agonizing hours, he struggled to keep his ship afloat. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, he said, ``I could do nothing else, nothing else. When  
she broke the last rope, I got off and she was carried away.'' 
Forbes leapt from the deck to safety on the pier. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Forget-Me-Not listed in shallow water several  
hundred feet from shore. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's got a heavy draft,'' Forbes said, ``but I hope we'll be  
able to get her out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of boats, large and small, were tossed about like bath  
toys, smashed or sunk when Floyd hit the Bahamas Tuesday. On 
Nassau's Long Wharf, a 100-foot freighter was dumped onto the beach 
next to the Cocktails and Dreams nightclub. 
</P>
<P>
	Littering the beach were a mattress, a satin high-heeled shoe, a  
kid's toy, kitchen dishes, twisted silverware and mounds of ragged 
clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearby, Michel Ashnel stared in despair at the ruins of his  
livelihood: a smashed-off bow -- all that Hurricane Floyd left of 
his cargo boat. The rest was lumber strewn along Nassau's Long 
Wharf. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what to do now. It was all I had,'' Ashnel said  
of the 25-foot vessel he used to ferry supplies among the islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
