<DOCNO> APW19990915.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 08:06:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Leaves Bell Equipment Alone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bell telephone companies won't be forced to  
lease to their rivals equipment used for high-speed Internet 
services but still will have to provide them access to parts of 
their local phone networks under action taken today by federal 
regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Long-distance companies and other upstart competitors had sought  
access to the local phone companies' equipment that delivers 
advanced telecommunications services. They had argued that such 
equipment is need so they can roll out high-speed Internet and data 
services more quickly to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Federal Communications Commission voted 5-0 today not to  
require major local carriers -- like the regional Bell companies or 
GTE -- to give competitors such access in its latest set of rules 
that attempt to wedge open the local phone market. Two 
commissioners dissented in part. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission rules still will enable competitors to lease  
certain components from major local phone carriers so they can 
provide local service without having to build their own facilities. 
A 1996 telecommunications law envisioned this as one way to spur 
more entrants into the local phone marketplace. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are telling companies that the elements you came to rely  
on, you are still going to have those to rely on,'' FCC Chairman 
Bill Kennard said in an interview Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	One piece consists of the wires that run from local phone  
company offices to homes and businesses. These are the most crucial 
network elements because they would be very expensive to duplicate. 
</P>
<P>
	But in an effort to get high-speed Internet services out to  
consumers more quickly, Kennard said the commission doesn't intend 
to force the Bells and others to lease equipment used for such 
advanced services. 
</P>
<P>
	This will give incumbent phone companies an incentive to invest  
in high-speed Internet services in the face of competition from 
others like cable companies who are offering such access over their 
lines, Kennard said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Kennard said, new competitors will have to  
invest in their own equipment for providing these Internet 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are creating the conditions for lots of companies to get  
out there,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC originally developed a list of items -- which did not  
include advanced services -- that local companies had to make 
available in 1996. The Supreme Court eventually sent the rules back 
to the commission, saying the FCC did not adequately consider 
whether competitors could obtain the pieces from another source. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard said the commission has gone back to provide  
justification for its rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those rules have worked. They are going to stay in place,''  
Kennard said. 
</P>
<P>
	The major local phone companies also have urged the FCC to  
provide more limited access to some of the network elements -- such 
as the switches that connect calls to their destination -- in areas 
where there is already enough competition. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 15:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines Aim To Improve Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's major airlines tried to quell a  
storm of congressional and passenger dissatisfaction Wednesday by 
announcing detailed plans aimed at improving customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	United Airlines, the largest U.S. carrier, said its steps will  
include deploying mobile computers that can be wheeled to gates 
that have flight problems, so passengers can get extra help with 
rebooking. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta Air Lines -- the No. 3 carrier, behind American Airlines --  
said its reservation agents will offer callers money-saving travel 
alternatives if a passenger has flexibility, and it will begin 
calling passengers if there are more than two hours notice that of 
a flight cancellation. 
</P>
<P>
	US Airways, an East Coast mainstay, said it would create a  
12-member consumer advisory board that will meet regularly with 
senior managers to discuss how the airline's customer-service plan 
is operating and make suggestions for improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to the Wings Club in New York -- an organization of  
aviation professionals -- Delta Chief Executive Officer Leo Mullin 
said airlines ``must regain public confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His company's plan doesn't create ``new customer service  
concepts for Delta, but what is new is that this is our chance to 
re-establish the covenant of trust that customers believe our 
industry broke,'' Mullin said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plans will take effect by Dec. 15, but critics said they  
remain vague and riddled with loopholes. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Delta pledged to let customers hold a reservation  
until midnight the following day -- which in some cases can be more 
than 24 hours away. However, many reservation agents already let 
travelers do that. Delta also has not changed its policy in which a 
passenger has to pay any fare increase that occurs during that 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Society of Travel Agents complained that airlines  
will continue to outlaw such cost-saving tactics such as 
``hidden-city'' tickets. With hidden cities, a traveler might book 
a flight from Point A to Point C, but get off during a stop at 
Point B because it is less expensive to buy the lengthier ticket 
than one to the interim stop. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically the airlines have not addressed that consumers  
should have the right to use all, part or none of an airline 
ticket,'' said society spokesman James Ashurst. ``They are going to 
be able to continue to penalize travelers for trying to get the 
lowest fare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The airline action came after a New Year's storm in the Midwest  
left thousands of travelers stranded. Some passengers got stuck on 
planes for hours and others had trouble learning when they might 
get home. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress drafted legislation to force the industry into treating  
passengers better, but the airlines said in June that they would 
develop plans by Wednesday for improving service. 
</P>
<P>
	The airlines said the government also must do its part. The  
Federal Aviation Administration ``must restructure and renew the 
air traffic control system to meet the needs of a growing air 
traffic system,'' Mullin told the Wings Club. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who had filed mandatory ``passenger  
rights'' legislation before the airlines made their voluntary 
proposals, offered two measures Wednesday on the Senate floor as 
the chamber considered the Transportation Department appropriations 
bill. One would require airlines to reveal when they overbook a 
flight, while the other would ensure that passengers receive the 
lowest fare. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., argued against the Wyden  
proposals, saying the voluntary plans were achieved after lengthy 
negotiations with the airlines and ``I think we ought to give them 
the chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a voice vote, senators agreed to ask the Transportation  
Department to investigate lowest-fare and overbooking practices. 
They also passed a watered-down ``sense of the Senate'' resolution 
saying it should be a deceptive trade practice to place passengers 
on overbooked flights or not give them the cheapest fare.	   American Airlines has not announced its plans. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
