<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 21:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Mrs. Clinton at Hispanic Gala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore and Hillary Rodham  
Clinton shared top billing at Wednesday's Congressional Hispanic 
Caucus gala -- an occasion crystallizing their shared dilemmas in 
running from the same White House. 
</P>
<P>
	He, in his presidential bid, and she, in her Senate race, have  
both courted the burgeoning Hispanic community. Both also have 
strained to establish political identities separate from President 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Both tried Wednesday to put the collision of those twin aims --  
over the president's grant of clemency to imprisoned Puerto Rican 
nationalists -- behind them by emphasizing kinship with Latinos. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore saluted the community's voting power: ``If a candidate  
speaks the rhetoric of inclusion but pursues the policies of 
exclusion, that candidate is going to pay at the ballot box. You 
will make sure of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton recounted in her warmly received 16-minute address  
that, as a law student, she traveled to the Rio Grande Valley in 
1972 to register Hispanic voters. 
</P>
<P>
	She said that in her more recent campaign travels, ``I have met  
Hispanic leaders and citizens who have been and now are attaining 
what they have demanded -- a seat at the table and an opportunity to 
chart their own destiny.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two took turns boosting each other's candidacy (she said she  
hoped for ``a president named Al Gore''; he said, ``Let's make sure 
that she is elected'') and saying that Clinton has done good for 
Latinos, but not good enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore noted this his shared tenure with Clinton had produced low  
unemployment and poverty rates, and high homeownership among 
Hispanics. But, Gore added, ``That's not to say we don't still have 
a great deal of work to do. We do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady said, ``I am not satisfied because we are still  
leaving too many men, women and children behind. ... I am not proud 
that we leave too many Americans out'' of the nation's world-class 
health care system. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore reveled in his reception from the friendly crowd. He  
bragged that his first grandson was born on the Fourth of July and 
said he hoped his next would claim a Cinco de Mayo birthday, a 
reference to Mexico's May 5 national holiday. After two jokes about 
managed care, Gore licked his finger and made a jaunty check mark 
in the air as if to say, ``Score another one for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Mrs. Clinton staged a news conference, where she stood  
at the side of Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton infuriated other leaders of New York's Puerto Rican  
community, most notably Rep. Jose Serrano, with her surprise 
statement last week opposing clemency for convicts associated with 
the FALN, a militant pro-independence group. Her 
allies-turned-critics complained of not being consulted on the 
matter. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Ferrer dismissed it as a lone disagreement. ``The  
Puerto Rican community is not monolithic and doesn't decide 
questions on one issue,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone at the news conference burst into laughter when Mrs.  
Clinton deflected another hot Puerto Rican issue -- getting the 
Navy's bombing range off the inhabited island of Vieques. 
</P>
<P>
	``One thing I want to do is consult with a number of people. I  
am heavy into consultations now,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Serrano, who attended the dinner, did not return several calls  
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has steered clear of the political tangle, saying only that  
he will not ``stand in judgment'' of the president's clemency 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Privately, Gore aides emphasize that the vice president's  
statement is hardly an endorsement of Clinton's action. 
</P>
<P>
	``The vice president hasn't spoken out,'' Rep. Xavier Becerra,  
D-Calif., lamented. 
</P>
<P>
	``While there is an interest in resolving this issue of  
clemency, it doesn't supplant education, health care, crime, all 
the other issues of importance,'' Becerra said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly am willing to give (Gore) a bye if he's here to  
talk about other issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Raul Yzaguirre, president of the National Council of La Raza, a  
Hispanic advocacy group, appreciated that Gore is in a tricky spot 
politically. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no good to be obtained by him coming down on one side  
or another,'' Yzaguirre said. ``It's a lose-lose for him to make a 
comment now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for the first lady, who stayed behind to campaign while her  
daughter and mother accompanied the president to New Zealand, 
Yzaguirre said: ``Her challenge is to show both independence and, 
at the same time reap the goodwill that Bill Clinton has enjoyed in 
our community. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a dance that she's got to do. It's not easy.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
