<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> O'Malley Wins Mayoral Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- City Councilman Martin O'Malley's  
zero-tolerance stand on crime reached across the racial divide to 
help the white Democrat win his party's mayoral primary in this 
predominantly black city. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a victory for diversity,'' O'Malley said after his win  
Tuesday. ``And it is a decisive victory against divisiveness, fear 
and the worn-out politics of the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Democrats outnumbering Republicans 9 to 1, O'Malley is  
expected to easily defeat his GOP challenger -- developer David 
Tufaroin -- in November. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore, which has been led for 12 years by Kurt Schmoke, who  
is black, would join other predominantly black cities such as 
Oakland, Calif., and Gary, Ind., that have elected white mayors in 
recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	At age 36, O'Malley, a boyish former city prosecutor and leader  
of an Irish musical group, would also be the youngest mayor in city 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people are good, the people are smart, the people are  
fair,'' he said. ``If you're honest and you're true and you stick 
to issues, everyone appreciates it: black, white, Asian, 
Hispanic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Race has been a key factor in politics in Baltimore, where 60  
percent of voters are black. But O'Malley still would have won even 
if Former Councilman Carl Stokes and Council President Lawrence 
Bell combined their votes. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Malley received 61,219 votes, or 53 percent. Stokes had 32,069  
votes, or 28 percent. Early front-runner Bell, who raised the most 
money as of the end of August, more than $1 million, had 19,611 
votes, or 17 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Stokes said even though he lost, he was happy to see voters put  
the issues above race. Black voters ``have proven time and time, 
over and over again that they will be fair in their vote,'' Stokes 
said. ``They will vote across lines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lenneal Henderson, a professor in the School of Public Affairs  
at the University of Baltimore, agreed: ``I think the voters are 
taller than race and taller than parochialism. That's what this 
demonstrates,'' Henderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Malley argued that making streets safe will stop the exodus  
from Baltimore, which suffered the second-biggest drop nationwide 
in population between 1990 and 1998. Baltimore's population dropped 
12.3 percent to about 645,000. According to new census figures, 
nearly one out of three whites left Baltimore during that time. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell, a 12-year city council member, also supported  
zero-tolerance and had the backing of the city police union. But he 
slipped badly in the wake of revelations about personal financial 
troubles and an incident in which his campaign workers disrupted an 
O'Malley event. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the lack of an incumbent and a full schedule of  
community forums and debates, turnout was about 40 percent compared 
with 47 percent four years ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
