<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Previews 2000 Olympic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Australians enjoyed a preview of things  
to come today, one year before the start of the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Crowds at Darling Harbour watched 16 hours of demonstrations of  
volleyball, weightlifting, boxing fencing and judo and met athletes 
from many of the 28 sports to be contested at the games. Darling 
Harbour will be the venue for some of those sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will help make people more aware that this is approaching  
and to get ready,'' Helen Russell, a Sydney resident, said as she 
collected commemorative pins and watched the live entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Australians like a party. ``I think Sydney is about the  
greatest place on earth to live and I think the rest of the world 
can come and see what a great place this is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sydney organizing chief Michael Knight was in Lausanne,  
Switzerland, celebrating the start of the one-year countdown at an 
International Olympic Committee party that featured a fanfare of 
aboriginal music. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight and IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch were among the  
guests at a ceremony which was broadcast live to Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Olympic movement is full of confidence in the capacity of  
the organizing committee to hold a successful games next year,'' 
Samaranch said. ``I am convinced the games of the 27th Olympiad 
will be a great success for the athletes, for Australia and for the 
Olympic Movement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Canberra, a meeting of 60 indigenous leaders convened by the  
Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission decided not to 
jeopardize the success of the Games next year through protest 
action. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, because we're a sport-loving people ourselves, we  
want to be at the Games, we want a successful Games, we want to see 
Cathy Freeman reach her full potential and get gold,'' former ATSIC 
chairwoman Lowitja O'Donoghue said. 
</P>
<P>
	Council for Aboriginal Reconciliation chairwoman Evelyn Scott  
said the success of Australian athletes was paramount. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not about to jeopardize the livelihood of our Australian  
athletes be they indigenous or non-indigenous,'' she said. 
``They've worked all their lives for this, to win gold in their own 
country.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
