<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Claim Killings in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VAVUNIYA, Sri Lanka (AP) -- A clandestine guerrilla radio  
broadcast said that Sri Lankan air force jets killed 18 civilians 
and injured 30 while bombing Tamil rebel positions Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Voice of Tiger radio said that Sri Lankan Kfir jets bombed the  
Pudikudiruppu area, near the eastern Mullaithivu coast. Mullaithivu 
is 170 miles east of the capital, Colombo. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten civilians' houses were damaged, and there were children  
among the dead, the rebel radio broadcast said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Colombo-based army official later confirmed there had been an  
air attack on rebel territory, and said there was no way to 
determine how many people were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	But the officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that  
the air force attacks only when it receives confirmation of rebel 
targets, and bombing does not occur in civilian areas. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no independent confirmation of either the rebels'  
claim or the military's statement, as journalists are discouraged 
from visiting the war zone. 
</P>
<P>
	The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam are fighting for an  
independent homeland for minority Tamils in the north and east of 
the island country, located off India's southern coast. Over 58,000 
people have died since the war began in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, an investigation into a soldier's claim that hundreds  
of Tamils were buried in mass graves in northern Sri Lanka has 
turned up just 11 skeletons. 
</P>
<P>
	The excavation began outside northern Jaffna City on Sept. 6 at  
sites identified by Lance Cpl. Somaratne Rajapakse, who told of the 
graves during his murder trial last year. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had helped prepare graves for some 300 Tamils after  
the army recaptured the Jaffna Peninsula from Tamil Tiger rebels in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	But at some of the sites, no human remains were found, sources  
close to the proceedings said on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators have called for Rajapakse to testify again.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
