<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 00:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Sanders Mulling NFL Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Whether Barry Sanders plans to return to the NFL  
is still anyone's guess. If he does, it won't be with the Detroit 
Lions. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders' agent, David Ware, said Tuesday that the star running  
back hasn't indicated whether he would return. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's ready to consider it, in the right situation,''  
Ware told the Detroit Free Press for a report today. ``But the 
right situation is not the Detroit Lions. His career is finished 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That means his career is finished -- period, Lions chief  
operating officer Chuck Schmidt said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't consider this an issue,'' Schmidt told the newspaper.  
``We've said all along that when Barry signed the contract, it was 
understood that he would retire a Detroit Lion, he'd finish his 
career in Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``And unfortunately that's what he's decided. If he decides to  
come back, we'll welcome him back. And if he retires again, he will 
retire a Detroit Lion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, who announced his retirement in July, has offered to  
repay $5.4 million of his signing bonus if the Lions release or 
trade him this season, Ware said. He said he made the offer to 
Detroit on Monday, but the team rejected it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were little nonplused ... because they know that he won't  
play for them,'' Ware said. ``They've told us that if he plays 
again, he'll play for them or he won't play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 31-year-old Sanders ``definitely would return,'' if the  
Lions would accommodate him, a source close to the running back 
told ESPN for a story appearing Tuesday on its Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders has not filed official retirement papers with the NFL.  
</P>
<P>
	His father, William Sanders, said his son hasn't indicated  
whether he'll come back to football. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was hoping he'd never quit,'' he said. ``I don't know what  
he's going to do. ... I keep my fingers crossed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lions would not confirm whether Ware contacted them on this  
matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our position remains the same -- that we honored his retirement  
wishes and we expected the repayment of the prorated portion,'' 
Lions spokesman Bill Keenist said. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit filed a grievance last week to recover $5.4 million of  
the $11 million signing bonus Sanders got when he signed a 
six-year, $36 million contract signed in 1997. Sanders, who needs 
only 1,458 yards to break Walter Payton's career rushing record, 
disagrees with Detroit's claim that he is required to repay a 
portion of the bonus if he doesn't play. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders did not collect a $1.7 million deferred payment due this  
fall on the original bonus. He also forfeited his 1999 base salary 
of $3.125 million and a reporting bonus of $250,000 by retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Ware said the issue could go either way with an arbitrator. He  
said he has spoken to Lions officials frequently since Sanders 
announced his retirement, asking Sanders to be released or traded 
if he repays the portion of the bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL rules governing the salary cap make it impossible for the  
Lions to trade Sanders this year. They would take an accelerated 
hit of $7.3 million. If Sanders returns the signing bonus, they can 
trade him next year without a salary-cap penalty, The Detroit News 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	William Sanders said he doesn't blame the Lions for taking the  
stand they have. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't release him either if I had a Barry Sanders on a  
contract,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
