<DOCNO> APW19990915.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 00:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Councilman Believes in L.A. Football </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Is the competition over between Los Angeles  
and Houston for the NFL's 32nd team? 
</P>
<P>
	Houston is the favorite again for the league's next expansion  
franchise, although the NFL wasn't expected to take any action 
today, when its initial six-month deadline for Los Angeles expired. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sept. 15 cutoff date for receiving an acceptable stadium and  
financing plan from Los Angeles turned out to be flexible. The 
league now is expected to entertain offers until the owners' 
meetings in Atlanta the week of Oct. 5 -- and possibly beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	City Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas, whose district includes the  
Coliseum, remains optimistic about LA's chances. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the market where the league really wants to be,'' he  
said Tuesday. ``Cut through all the bull and somewhere in there, 
there's a deal to be made. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to do a deal with the league and the league wants to  
do a deal with us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the expansion franchise goes to Houston, the NFL still  
hopes to have a team in Los Angeles at some point, perhaps an 
existing team. 
</P>
<P>
	``All that may be in the realm of possibility, but now we're  
intensively focused on the 32nd franchise,'' Ridley-Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coliseum, which would be completely remodeled, was chosen  
last April as the NFL's preferred site for a team. But negotiations 
stalled in July when the league asked for more public funding for 
the project. 
</P>
<P>
	When talks with the Coliseum bogged down, the league opened the  
door for other possible sites in the Los Angeles area. Carson, 
which had been snubbed when the NFL decided to focus on the 
Coliseum, reentered the picture. 
</P>
<P>
	Marvin Davis, a billionaire oilman, came forward with a proposal  
to build a stadium at Hollywood Park, reviving an old idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Public funds aside, the league might eventually do its first  
billion-dollar deal in LA since three billionaires seem eager to 
bring a team to town. 
</P>
<P>
	Grocery magnate Ron Burkle is a member of the team headed by  
Michael Ovitz, who at one time seemed favored by the league as a 
potential team owner. 
</P>
<P>
	Backing the idea of renovating the Coliseum was Eli Broad, who  
made his money in housing construction. 
</P>
<P>
	After representatives from Los Angeles and Houston met  
separately with NFL officials in New York this week, league 
spokesman Greg Aiello said it was still a ``four-horse race'' for 
the new franchise. He noted that because of the land and parking 
around Hollywood Park, it was the ``most doable'' of the three LA 
sites. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox Think Indians Are Cheating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The Boston Red Sox are convinced the Indians  
are doing much more than videotaping game's for instructional 
purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston manager Jimy Williams asked that a camera atop the  
center-field wall at Jacobs Field be covered after he became 
suspicious that Cleveland was stealing signs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've got something,'' Williams said.  
</P>
<P>
	Williams approached umpire crew chief Tim Welke before Tuesday  
night's game -- a 12-3 Boston victory -- with some kind of evidence 
that the Indians were up to no good. 
</P>
<P>
	And apparently whatever Williams showed Welke was enough to have  
the Indians cover the camera, which Cleveland says is used to 
evaluate its own players' performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Welke said he has notified the AL of the situation, and that the  
camera would remained covered for Wednesday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's in the hands of the league office and being handled  
internally,'' he told the Associated Press before Wednesday night's 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Welke declined to comment on what Williams showed him, saying,  
``That's up to Jimy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams wasn't much more forthcoming, but said he heard  
whispers the Indians were cheating back in 1995 when he was 
Atlanta's third-base coach. The Braves played the Indians in the 
World Series that year. 
</P>
<P>
	``They (umpires) must have thought enough of what I showed them  
to have it covered up,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not the first time Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove has had  
to defend his team against cheating allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand the Red Sox' concerns,'' Hargrove said. ``There  
have been other clubs that we've had concerns with over the years. 
I don't know what we can do to alleviate their fears. We've covered 
up the camera. We don't cheat. We don't. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish out players did, but we don't. I'm not talking about  
scuffing baseballs or corking bats. I'm not talking about cheating 
in that regard. But I wished we relayed signs and things like that, 
but our players don't want to. ... I understand their concerns on 
the other side. We'll do what we can to allay their fears but I 
don't know what I can do other than to say we're not doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And anyway, Hargrove said, if the Indians are cheating at home,  
how is it that they've won 44 games outside of Jacobs Field? 
</P>
<P>
	``Our record on the road is pretty good too,'' he said. ``I'm  
telling you that we don't do that (cheat). 
</P>
<P>
	Indians catcher Sandy Alomar said he was unaware of Boston's  
charges, and denied the Indians ever do anything underhanded. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't steal signs,'' he said. ``We don't have players who  
cheat.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
