<DOCNO> APW19990915.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Carolinas Declared Disaster Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- President Clinton today declared federal  
disaster areas in South Carolina and North Carolina as Hurricane 
Floyd continued to pound the southeastern seaboard. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, in remarks during a brief refueling stop at Hickam Air  
Force Base, said he told the governors of both states that he and 
other federal officials ``would do everything we can'' to help 
residents deal with the storm and its aftermath. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that every citizen will heed the warnings of the  
officials and recommendations to take every action to protect their 
families and stay out of harm's way,'' the president said as he 
returned to American soil after a weeklong trip to New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore announced the latest disaster  
declarations at Federal Emergency Management Agency headquarters in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The disaster declaration clears the way for equipment and  
federal funds to be used in recovery efforts as quickly as 
possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar declarations were previously issued for Florida and  
Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	The massive storm prompted Clinton to cut short a day of rest  
planned for Hawaii. Air Force One stopped only long enough to 
refuel. As he left New Zealand on Wednesday, the president said the 
United States had done ``everything we know to do'' to prepare for 
the potential devasation from the storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd was forecast to come ashore Thursday near Wilmington, N.C.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
