<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 10:39:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Embraces Hispanic Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore will be able to walk  
into tonight's Congressional Hispanic Caucus gala dinner with the 
endorsements of 521 Latino activists in his pocket. 
</P>
<P>
	But by sharing the stage with Hillary Rodham Clinton, Gore risks  
seeing his limelight stolen by the first lady's unresolved campaign 
contretemps with Puerto Ricans. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore himself has not said much about whether President Clinton  
was right to free 14 Puerto Rican nationalists imprisoned on 
sedition and weapons convictions. 
</P>
<P>
	With an eye on his own growing Hispanic support, Gore has said  
only that he is ``not going to stand in judgment'' of the 
president's clemency decision. Gore aides privately emphasize that 
the vice president's statement is hardly an endorsement of 
clemency. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's surprise announcement of opposition to her  
husband's move infuriated several Puerto Rican political leaders, 
among them Rep. Jose Serrano, D-N.Y., who said he no longer could 
support her campaign for a Senate seat from New York, a state with 
a large Puerto Rican population. 
</P>
<P>
	``The vice president hasn't spoken out,'' Rep. Xavier Becerra,  
D-Calif., lamented after a pep rally Tuesday launching Gore's 
effort to amass support in the Hispanic community. 
</P>
<P>
	In that appearance, where Gore pumped hands in an adoring crowd  
to the hot-salsa sounds of Ricky Martin, the clemency issue did not 
come up. Instead, Puerto Rico's pro-statehood governor, Pedro 
Rossello, saluted Gore's ``sensitivity'' to Hispanic concerns, and 
his campaign released the 15-page list of endorsements for Gore's 
presidential bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``While there is an interest in resolving this issue of  
clemency, it doesn't supplant education, health care, crime, all 
the other issues of importance,'' Becerra said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly am willing to give (Gore) a bye if he's here to  
talk about other issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady was not escaping so easily.  
</P>
<P>
	Becerra told reporters that some attending the Congressional  
Hispanic Caucus Institute's annual convention, in the same hotel 
where Gore staged his rally, were abuzz with ``real 
disappointment'' in Mrs. Clinton for her failure to consult them on 
the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it shows that the first lady probably has to continue  
her -- what is it? -- her listening campaign,'' Becerra said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore aides said they paid no attention to Gore's double billing  
with the first lady and were unconcerned by it. 
</P>
<P>
	For her part, Mrs. Clinton tried over the weekend to put the  
matter to rest. She acknowledged that she could have done more to 
consult with Hispanic leaders and said that mistake ``will never 
happen again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The year 2000 crop of political candidates, including Republican  
presidential hopeful George W. Bush, is fiercely courting Latino 
voters. 
</P>
<P>
	New census data released Tuesday showed the U.S. Hispanic  
population grew by more than 35 percent to about 30.3 million 
between 1990 and 1998, increasing their share of the total 
population from 9 percent to 11 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	With a riff on pop star Martin's hit single, Gore supporters on  
Tuesday ridiculed any inroads Bush, the Texas governor, has made 
with the Hispanic community. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's all this talk about George W. Bush and the Latino  
community? I mean they talk about this guy like he's Ricky Martin 
or something,'' said California Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anybody thinks that George W. Bush is good for Latinos,  
they ARE living 'La Vida Loca.' (The Crazy Life.)'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Bustamante's endorsement of Gore sounded a bit  
backhanded: ``Many months ago I decided -- maybe it wasn't the smart 
political thing to do, but I think it was the right thing to do -- 
to support Al Gore for president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As part of his ``Ganamos con Gore'' (We win with Gore) theme  
week, Gore joined former ``NYPD Blue'' actor Jimmy Smits and the 
National Hispanic Foundation for the Arts on Monday night to 
deplore the lack of diversity in mainstream movie and TV roles. On 
Thursday, he speaks to the Latino Chamber of Commerce in Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's lone rival for the  
Democratic presidential nomination, is also competing for minority 
voters in next year's primaries. And on Monday, the Bradley camp 
announced endorsements from a host of Brooklyn political leaders, 
including several influential members of the New York City 
borough's black community. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
