<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Party Threatens Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) -- An ethnic-based party in Pakistan  
warned Wednesday that its activists could use violence to protest 
police attacks on its workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Muttahida Qami Movement, which represents the Indian  
immigrant population, accused Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif of 
ordering the police to arrest, torture and kill its workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this situation the government is pushing us toward  
violence,'' said Farooq Sattar, a spokesman for the MQM. ``We have 
tried the peaceful approach, but the government has responded with 
brute force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sattar did not explain what form the violence could take.  
</P>
<P>
	Since November 1998 when Sharif dismissed the Sindh provincial  
government and imposed federal rule, 28 MQM workers have died while 
in police custody, Sattar said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sattar said police explain that MQM workers die of heart attack  
or while trying to escape. Pakistan's independent human rights 
groups also have complained of unexplained deaths in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	The MQM, along with 18 other opposition parties, including  
former prime minister Benazir Bhutto's party, the Pakistan People's 
Party, have been waging almost daily protests against Sharif's 
government in southern Sindh province, of which Karachi is the 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, the government has imposed a two-month ban on  
demonstrations in the province, saying the daily strikes and 
protests is crippling businesses in Karachi, the country's 
commercial and financial center. 
</P>
<P>
	The opposition has responded with promises of further  
demonstrations and strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	The MQM is the second largest political party in southern Sindh  
province. Ms. Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party is the largest. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
