<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former All-American Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUSKOGEE, Okla. (AP) -- Terry Miller, a two-time All-American  
running back at Oklahoma State, was sentenced to two years in 
prison on Tuesday for defrauding a McAlester bank out of $179,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to apologize to those I hurt in this matter,'' Miller  
said. ``I want to leave the impression I will do anything I can to 
make it up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller's lawyer, Steve Stidham, said he had hoped Miller, 43,  
could avoid a jail term. His client has been a longtime community 
volunteer who has paid back most of his $1 million debt to The 
Bank, N.A. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, who is out on bond, will report to prison in November.  
</P>
<P>
	``He will pay The Bank back every penny,'' Stidham said.  
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors alleged in March that Miller submitted false  
invoices to The Bank beginning around March 1995. Under a business 
manager agreement negotiated with The Bank that same month, he 
would then receive advance funds based on the invoices. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller and his sports-apparel company, Sports Nut Inc., received  
about $1 million in advances, $179,000 of which was gained through 
the false invoices, according to records. The former football star 
has paid back more than $800,000 of the money, Stidham said. 
</P>
<P>
	District Judge Frank H. Seay said Miller's situation didn't meet  
the requirements needed for a lighter sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller also faces three years of probation upon his release from  
prison and must pay the $179,000 in restitution to The Bank, Seay 
ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. attorney Jeff Gallant noted during Tuesday's  
sentencing hearing that Miller had four previous convictions on his 
record. Two of those convictions were for writing bad checks, which 
indicated fraudulent behavior, Gallant said. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller testified that his business situation suffered after  
$900,000 worth of sports jackets were recalled from his company. 
The jackets had been made by a Eufaula sewing company with which 
Miller also was involved, he testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller was one of the most decorated running backs in Oklahoma  
State history. He ran for 1,680 yards in 1977, his senior year, and 
finished second to Earl Campbell of Texas in the Heisman Trophy 
voting. 
</P>
<P>
	He was an NFL first-round draft pick by the Buffalo Bills.  
Replacing O.J. Simpson in the Bills backfield, Miller gained more 
than 1,000 yards in his rookie year. 
</P>
<P>
	Injuries ended Miller's pro career. He started Sports Nut Inc.  
in 1989. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
