<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Xerox Suit Vs. Hewlett-Packard Nixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A federal court has dismissed a lawsuit  
Xerox Corp. filed last year against Hewlett-Packard Co., 
effectively ending one of five technology-related lawsuits between 
the two office equipment companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox had filed the lawsuit in May last year in federal court  
seeking to block H-P from selling inkjet supplies and printers, 
including some DeskJet models, using the disputed technology. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Michael Telesca ruled Tuesday that H-P did  
not infringe on Xerox's patent and dismissed in its entirety 
Xerox's action against H-P. 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox officials said the company would appeal the decision.  
</P>
<P>
	The companies remain locked in a series of other legal  
squabbles, spawned largely by Xerox's introduction in 1997 of H-P 
compatible laser-printer cartridges. 
</P>
<P>
	The competition fostered a series of lawsuits over patents and  
trademarks. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies settled one lawsuit in January, with Xerox  
agreeing to redesign lettering on packages for H-P-compatible 
printer cartridges. 
</P>
<P>
	In another lawsuit, a federal court in Wichita, Kan., handed  
down a mixed ruling in August forcing H-P to complete shipments to 
Xerox of 4,000 computer chips based on H-P's TrueRes technology, 
which Xerox uses to sharpen images produced by its DocuPrint NC60 
color laser printer. 
</P>
<P>
	But that court ruled Xerox would have to fight for any further  
shipments, forcing the company to look elsewhere for equivalent 
technology. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
