<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Site at U. of Tex. Reopened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- From the observation deck of the University  
of Texas Tower, school president Larry Faulkner could see students 
milling about on the mall below -- the same place where gunman 
Charles Whitman found many of his victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The deck was reopened Wednesday, 25 years after officials closed  
it because of the 1966 sniper attack that killed 16 people and a 
series of suicide jumps. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't wipe out the past but you don't stop with the  
past,'' Faulkner said as he surveyed the panoramic view from the 
clock tower's 27th floor. ``I believe it is important that we move 
beyond these painful chapters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tower was forever linked with Whitman on Aug. 1, 1966, when  
he lugged a rifle and a footlocker full of ammunition to the 
observation deck and started shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	The bloody rampage lasted for 92 minutes, until he was shot to  
death by police officers Ramiro Martinez and Houston McCoy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like Whitman was holding the tower hostage,'' said  
Martinez, who favored reopening the observation deck. ``It's time 
we took the tower back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nine other deaths are associated with the tower, including two  
accidental falls and seven suicides, five from the observation 
deck. 
</P>
<P>
	The university closed the deck in 1974 but agreed last year to  
reopen it using a plan generated by students. 
</P>
<P>
	The deck is now covered with a stainless steel lattice to thwart  
jumpers. Visitors must go through a metal detector and cannot bring 
packages onto the observation deck. Security guards will be posted 
at the check-in point and on the deck, Faulkner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulkner said most people have favored reopening the observation  
deck. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad they're doing it,'' said Robert Heard, a former  
Associated Press reporter who was shot by Whitman while covering 
the story. ``It's a magnificent view from up there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month the university dedicated a memorial garden on the  
north side of the tower to honor Whitman's victims. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
