<DOCNO> APW19990915.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 01:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hair Braiders Fight for Their Craft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Gently pulling aside a tiny clump of hair from  
the woman sitting in front of her, JoAnne Cornwell deftly maneuvers 
the tresses into a tightly coiled lock. 
</P>
<P>
	There was a time when such a simple action could have resulted  
in a hefty fine because Cornwell, like thousands of other braiders 
of African-styled hair designs, doesn't hold a state cosmetology 
license. 
</P>
<P>
	So before the state could come knocking on her door, she took  
them to court. 
</P>
<P>
	The result: Cornwell is celebrating a federal court victory that  
she and her fellow hair braiders nationwide hope will pave the way 
for them to keep practicing their craft without a license they feel 
is unnecessary. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't shampoo. We don't use chemicals. And we don't cut  
hair,'' said Cornwell, a university professor who developed her own 
trademarked styling technique called Sisterlocks. ``Yet they want 
us to take 1,600 hours of cosmetology training that never addresses 
what we do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court Judge Rudi Brewster agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``The court concludes that requiring a would-be African hair  
braider to attend a school of cosmetology is irrational and 
certainly unreasonable,'' the judge said in a 26-page ruling issued 
last month. 
</P>
<P>
	But he declined to issue a summary judgment extending that kind  
of blanket protection to the American Hairbraiders and Natural Hair 
Care Association in general, partly because their stylists' 
practices vary widely. 
</P>
<P>
	While the association argues its case, the Department of  
Consumer Affairs, which oversees the state's Barbering and 
Cosmetology Program, is waiting for a final ruling before deciding 
whether to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	State and cosmetology officials have argued that hair braiders  
need to be licensed to ensure consumers are protected. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're working in an environment where diseases and where  
head lice can be transmitted from person to person,'' said Gordon 
Miller, executive director of the 30,000-member National 
Cosmetology Association. ``Sanitary procedures are things that need 
to be learned and understood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are believed to be thousands of people operating small,  
home-based businesses around the country offering such 
African-styled braiding as corn rows and dreadlocks. 
</P>
<P>
	But many have been pushed underground by state cosmetology  
boards that want them to undergo training, said attorney Clint 
Bolick of the Washington, D.C.-based Institute for Justice, which 
filed the lawsuit on behalf of Cornwell and the hairbraiders 
assocation. 
</P>
<P>
	A few states have addressed the issue either by creating a  
separate license for braiders or exempting them from the 
cosmetology requirements. Two bills that would do the same in 
California are pending in the state Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, Bolick said he hopes to use the Sisterlock  
ruling to induce nationwide deregulation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Throughout this litigation, the state was unable to identify  
virtually any unlicensed hairstylists who had harmed consumers,'' 
he said. ``They know they can snuff out competition if they force 
African hairstylists to submit to massive irrelevant training in 
cosmetology schools that derive an enormous profit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cornwell, a San Diego State University professor, developed the  
Sisterlock, which is like a tiny dreadlock about the width of a 
pipe cleaner, while experimenting with new hairstyles for herself. 
</P>
<P>
	She said Tuesday she received so many compliments from other  
black women that she decided to turn the style into a business in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Sisterlocks now has some 200 stylists working in several states.  
Each receives 16 hours of training and is kept up on procedures 
through newsletters, manuals and videos. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issues that we're presenting are issues that everyone can  
relate to,'' she said. ``They have to do with the right to earn an 
honest living, individuals and self-empowerment, 
community-building, with all kinds of things that have to do with 
the American way.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 06:50:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Upholds Racketeering Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A judge today refused to throw out a racketeering  
indictment against a reputed mobster-turned-informant, saying the 
deal he had with the FBI did not grant him immunity. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Mark L. Wolf said the case of Stephen ``The  
Rifleman'' Flemmi, which led the FBI to admit it mishandled 
informants and threatened to undo earlier mob prosecutions, had 
merit but did not deserve to be dismissed entirely. 
</P>
<P>
	``Flemmi did not understand that the government, or any of its  
agents, had agreed that he would not be investigated, by the FBI or 
any other law enforcement agency, or prosecutor,'' the judge wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rather, he expected that the FBI would overlook some of his  
criminal activity, provide him information concerning any 
investigations that were conducted, and warn him of any imminent 
charges against him of which it learned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf acknowledged the case could be thrown out later.  
</P>
<P>
	Testimony during months of hearings revealed that Flemmi and  
James ``Whitey'' Bulger were longtime informants who dined with FBI 
agents, swapped gifts, and gave money and loans to the agents. 
Flemmi said he and Bulger, now a fugitive, were even tipped off to 
the pending indictments so they could flee. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers sought to dismiss the 1995 racketeering  
indictments based on a relationship that was so cozy that Bulger 
and Flemmi were free to commit crimes -- short of murder -- as long 
as they kept informing on their associates. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear how Wolf's decision would affect  
other co-defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	For Bulger and Flemmi, the ruling is largely irrelevant because  
they now face more serious racketeering allegations that include 
gangland murders. 
</P>
<P>
	The intensified prosecution was at least partially related to  
the disclosures about their past as informants. John Martorano, an 
admitted killer and racketeering co-defendant, became angry about 
Bulger's and Flemmi's cooperation with authorities and agreed to 
testify against them. 
</P>
<P>
	Disclosures about the Bulger-Flemmi relationship with the FBI  
led agency Director Louis Freeh to concede it made significant 
mistakes handling informants and had changed its policies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 16:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Upholds Racketeering Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A federal judge on Wednesday refused to throw out  
a racketeering indictment against a mobster-turned-informant, but 
said the case can only go forward if the government can prove it 
was as faithful to their deal as he was. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi's agreement with the FBI did not  
grant him all-encompassing immunity, U.S. District Judge Mark L. 
Wolf ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	But he ordered hearings to determine whether the indictments  
against Flemmi resulted from the very wiretaps that he helped the 
government obtain by providing information about the room where a 
1989 mob induction ceremony was held. If that's the case, the 
charges against him could be dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf said Flemmi relied on FBI assurances that any evidence  
intercepted through wiretaps would not be used against him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Flemmi performed his part of the bargain,'' Wolf wrote. ``The  
government claims that it should not be required to provide Flemmi 
the benefit of that bargain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The government contends that any agreement that Flemmi had with  
the FBI was invalid because he committed many serious crimes -- 
including murder -- but did not tell the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys had filed a motion to dismiss the racketeering  
indictments based on the cozy relationship between Flemmi, 
defendant James ``Whitey'' Bulger, also an informant, and FBI 
officials who turned a blind eye to criminal behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	Flemmi's 30-year relationship with the FBI was tight enough that  
they exchanged holiday gifts and the feds looked the other way when 
crimes were committed -- as long as Flemmi kept informing on his 
pals. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, Wolf's decision could be irrelevant for Bulger and  
Flemmi because they now face more serious racketeering allegations 
that include gangland murders. 
</P>
<P>
	Flemmi's lawyer, Kenneth Fishman, called Wolf's decision a  
``stunning victory. ... The court has clearly rejected the notion 
that the government can walk away from deals made with top echelon 
informants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Attorney Donald K. Stern said he was pleased the judge did  
not dismiss the indictment but disappointed further hearings were 
deemed necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Mawn, the FBI's special agent in charge, said the judge's  
ruling will be reviewed to identify and correct ``potential problem 
areas.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
