<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Future Safety Systems See Accidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Right now, a car's safety systems,  
such as air bags and seat belts, don't do anything until the 
vehicle slams into another object. 
</P>
<P>
	In the future, cars will do a bit more thinking ahead -- using  
radar sensors and cameras to predict a crash and help lessen the 
impact and injury, or possibly even avoid an accident altogether. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you can predict a crash, you can do a better job of  
managing that energy,'' said Ralph Hoar, an auto safety consultant 
based in Arlington, Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea has been in the works for years, and several automakers  
are working on the concept, including Mercedes-Benz, which used the 
Frankfurt International Motor Show to show off a system that could 
be in production in as little as two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think this is the next great step in passive safety,'' said  
Rainer Justen, an engineer at Mercedes, a division of the merged 
DaimlerChrysler. He said 59 percent of accidents are caused in such 
a way that predictive sensors could help. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Mercedes system, radar sensors are located in the front  
bumper and a camera is mounted on the back of the rear-view mirror, 
facing through the front windshield. 
</P>
<P>
	The devices help determine the speed and size of the object that  
the car is about to hit. The car automatically tightens seat belts 
and inflates air bags ahead of the actual collision -- as much as 
16.5 to 33 feet before the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	The pre-crash system could be especially beneficial for  
passengers, Justen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the driver usually sees the accident coming and slams on  
the brake, they maintain a position that allows for the maximum 
benefit from air bags and seat belts. 
</P>
<P>
	A passenger, however, usually doesn't see the accident coming  
and is jerked forward when the brakes are applied. That means the 
seat belt has too much slack and the air bag is too close. 
</P>
<P>
	More advanced systems also could eventually adjust the stiffness  
of the bumper -- making it softer when a pedestrian is in the way of 
the car or harder when the car is about to collide with a solid 
object, for example a wall or another vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Other innovations could include a hood that rises to cushion the  
impact of a pedestrian who is thrown onto the front of a car after 
being struck. 
</P>
<P>
	If the car can predict the accident, then why not just prevent  
it altogether? Future innovations will also help apply the brakes 
to reduce stopping distance, or even bring the car to an emergency 
stop. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoar cautioned that such systems would not eliminate human error  
-- or the necessity to develop safety features. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neither manufacturers nor the public should think this will  
mean there will be no more crashes, or that less thought has to be 
given to protecting people when crashes occur.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
