<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US West Plans Cheaper Web Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hoping to capture a wider audience, U S West  
Corp. is offering more for less with a new dial-up version of a 
digital subscriber line, or DSL. 
</P>
<P>
	The Baby Bell phone company which serves 14 Western states,  
announced Wednesday that its MegaBit Select is being introduced 
throughout its service area after a trial run in four cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The service costs $19.95 a month, $10 less than what U S West  
charges for a continuous Internet connection via DSL. 
</P>
<P>
	DSL allows people to access the Internet at speeds five times  
faster than the fastest dial-up modem installed on most desktop and 
laptop computers. Continuous DSL service typically costs $50 or 
more per month. 
</P>
<P>
	The dial-up service is targeted at residential customers who  
typically spend a few hours online at a time, although there is no 
limit on access time, said spokesman Garth Neuffer. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the economy of scale. We'd rather have everyone sign up  
for a low price than just a few sign up at a higher price,'' 
Neuffer said. 
</P>
<P>
	DSL users still need to pay a separate monthly fee, generally  
ranging from $10 to $22, to an Internet service provider such as 
America Online. 
</P>
<P>
	``MegaBit Select will dramatically accelerate the use of  
high-speed Internet services by mass market consumers,'' said Joe 
Zell, president of U S West's !nterprise Networking unit. 
``Recreational and weekend Internet surfers will enjoy dedicated, 
high-speed Internet access at a price that makes sense for their 
lifestyle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The service is available immediately in more than 40 Western  
cities, including Denver, Minneapolis/St. Paul and Salt Lake City. 
It will be available in other parts of U S West's 14-state 
territory next month, the company said. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
