<DOCNO> APW19990915.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 19:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Keeping Lower Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Hugo Chavez on Wednesday  
ruled out increasing Venezuela's oil output to capitalize on higher 
prices, saying an earlier decision to cut production would be 
maintained. 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuela, the world's third largest oil exporter and founding  
member of OPEC, had long been among the biggest quota busters. But 
since taking office in February, Chavez has reversed that policy 
and reduced output in order to help raise flagging prices. 
</P>
<P>
	That policy has been largely successful, with oil prices  
rebounding from a 12-year low last year. The price of a barrel of 
Venezuelan oil went from $7 last year to more than $20 now. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez said in a speech Wednesday that a March OPEC agreement to  
cut production by two million barrels a day would be respected at 
least until next March. Some have urged a production increase as a 
response to the higher prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The cutbacks in oil production have contributed to an acute  
economic recession in Venezuela. The economy contracted by an 
astounding 10 percent in the first half of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not interested in increasing our production. We have  
said that we are going to maintain the cutback agreement that we 
now have with Mexico, Saudi Arabia and the OPEC countries,'' Chavez 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil accounts for about three quarters of Venezuela's export  
earnings. So far, the rebound in oil prices has not translated into 
economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Hector Ciavaldini, the newly appointed president of the state  
oil monopoly Petroleos de Venezuela, said last week that the 
company would begin spending more money to stimulate the depressed 
oil sector. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
