<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Down on Outlook / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Forecasts for dry weather and favorable crop  
conditions sent grain and soybean futures lower in early trading 
today on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Beneficial harvest weather was forecast through the week in the  
eastern Midwest -- the heart of the soybean belt. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans had already closed Tuesday at their lowest level in  
nearly two weeks, pressured by talk of better-than-expected yields 
along with slowing U.S. export demand because of increasing prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures followed the trend in soybeans, with investors  
also wary because of a report of improved planting prospects for 
hard red winter wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn slipped further amid continued good prospects for the fall  
harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 4 1/2 cents to $2.83 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1 1/4 cents to $2.13 1/2 cents a bushel; December oats 
fell 1 cent to $1.13 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans fell 5 3/4 cents to 
$4.96 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were higher on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while pork futures were lower. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle fell .25 cent to 67.62 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle fell .35 cent to 80.02 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs rose .25 cent to 43.35 cents a pound; February pork 
bellies rose .18 cent to 54.25 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
