<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sorenstam To Defend Safeco Title  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENT, Wash. (AP) -- Annika Sorenstam is back to defend her Safeco  
Classic title this week on the 6,241-yard Meridian Valley Country 
Club course. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's LPGA rookie of the year, Se Ri Pak, will join her at  
the $650,000 event, as will Lorie Kane, No. 4 on this year's money 
list. Pak is No. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Many other top players are skipping the event, which begins  
Thursday, so the big three might turn it into their own private 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Sorenstam, the 1998 Player of the Year, is fifth on this year's  
money list and will be looking for her second victory of the year. 
She won the Michelob Light Classic in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-time Safeco winners Karrie Webb and Juli Inkster, also the  
top two money winners this year, chose to skip Safeco, as did other 
notables: Rosie Jones, Laura Davies, Kelli Kuehne, Sherri 
Steinhauer and Liselotte Neumann. 
</P>
<P>
	The leading rookie on the tour, Mi Hyun Kim, pulled out Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Hall-of-Famer Patty Sheehan, a three-time winner and crowd  
favorite, is also skipping the event as she is taking time off 
following the death of her father. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb, Inkster and Sheehan have seven wins in the 17 years of  
Safeco. 
</P>
<P>
	Safeco has traditionally followed the Safeway Golf Championship  
in Portland, Ore., and often causes scheduling problems for the 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the LPGA schedule makers have the tournament  
following the Samsung World Championship of Women's Golf in 
Minnesota. Many players who took part in that tournament, which 
featured the world's top 20 female golfers, pulled out of this 
year's Safeco event. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Samsung event really hurt us,'' Safeco tournament director  
Rosanna Bellotti said. ``A lot of players play hard before a 
championship, peak, then need a break.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two local golfers joined this year's field with sponsor  
exemptions. Jimin Kang, who played golf with Pak as a youngster in 
South Korea, is a senior at Seattle's King's High School. Kang 
finished second at the recent U.S. Women's Amateur Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining Kang is Oregon's Paula Patterson, who grew up in  
Washington. Patterson won the USGA's U.S. Open Sectional Qualifier 
this year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
