<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  American Designs Hit the Runway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ralph Lauren wore his patriotism on his sleeve  
as he unfurled his new collection cast in red, white and blue. 
</P>
<P>
	Looks culled from Americana have splashed color on the spring  
2000 runways throughout the first half of the New York Fashion Week 
designer previews. The vivid colors of Old Glory blanketed Tommy 
Hilfiger's rock 'n roll-inspired collection, and Michael Kors 
dedicated his line to all-American preppy chic. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauren's show Wednesday saluted ``true American sportswear,'' he  
said, with enough red, white and blue gingham tablecloth patterns 
to supply the Fourth of July. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauren also gave a nod to the emerging trends of the season,  
including midriff-baring tops, pants cropped above the ankle, 
perforated leather and skirts that drop just below the knee with a 
double-ruffled hem. 
</P>
<P>
	Kors on Wednesday revised ``The Official Preppy Handbook'' with  
a sexy spin on shrunken tennis sweaters and golf pro-shop colors. 
He updated the Ivy League rugby shirt into a body-skimming 
minidress, paired tongue-in-cheek with stiletto sandals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sexy nouvelle prep -- the woman of the country club who  
all the other women hate and all the men love,'' said Kors, who 
parodied the poolside set with floral caftans and turban towels. 
</P>
<P>
	Hilfiger went for flash-and-dazzle showmanship Tuesday night  
with a fashion extravaganza at Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	The collection ``combines a rock 'n roll edge with an American  
sensibility,'' said Hilfiger, whose show included a live 
performance by the rock group Bush and giant video monitors 
capturing the outlandish outfits, including crystal-fringed 
bellbottoms, snakeskin biker vests and cowboy boots emblazoned with 
``Tommy Rocks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With equal parts Hollywood and Nashville, the collection  
featured over-the-top leathers appliqued with a flame print, 
microminis with crystal shimmy fringe, and leather jeans 
embroidered with star pockets. 
</P>
<P>
	Cynthia Rowley fit her show into an oldtime, mirrored ballroom  
and breathed new life into vintage handkerchiefs found at an 
upstate New York thrift shop. They showed up Tuesday evening in the 
guise of halter tops held together with delicate string, as well as 
patchwork dresses. 
</P>
<P>
	Rowley, known for her whimsical designs, also lighted up the  
night with lacy, metallic dresses with tiny lights twinkling in the 
dark, the season's best case for battery-operated fashions. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 20:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
