<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alaskan Dividend Survives Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Balancing the state budget is less  
attractive to Alaskans than keeping the annual dividend each man, 
woman and child receives from the state's oil-royalty savings 
account. 
</P>
<P>
	Voters on Tuesday rejected a plan to divide the earnings of the  
$26 billion Alaska Permanent Fund between state spending and the 
fund's wildly popular annual dividend. 
</P>
<P>
	With all precincts reporting, 83 percent of voters rejected the  
plan, confirming a long-held belief in Alaska politics: Politicians 
who try to touch the dividend are courting disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Alaska Legislature got a clear message to go back to the  
drawing board,'' said Eddie Burke, chairman of Save Your 
Dividend-Vote No. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote means Democratic Gov. Tony Knowles and the  
Republican-controlled Legislature -- who put the plan on the ballot 
-- must try again to find a new way to fill the gap between state 
spending and normal revenue. The state gets most of its operating 
money from taxes and royalties on oil production, while Alaskans 
pay no state income tax and no state sales tax. 
</P>
<P>
	A decline in oil revenues has forced sharp cuts in the state  
budget, but the fund -- and the dividend -- have grown in the booming 
stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan before voters would cut the dividend to about $1,340 in  
2001. Last year's payout was $1,540 and this year's is expected to 
exceed $1,700. About $800 million a year would be dedicated to 
bridging the gap between the state's spending and its revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the plan contended it was necessary to avoid  
drastic budget cuts or the loss of Alaska's status as the only 
state without an income tax or a sales tax. The supporters drew 
more than $500,000 in donations from businesses, particularly in 
oil and tourism. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people need to understand that in some way they're going  
to have to pay for state government in the future,'' said 
Republican state Rep. Eldon Mulder, one of the plan's architects. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents, including a loose coalition of conservatives and  
liberal environmentalists, said cutting the dividend would amount 
to a regressive tax that hits the poor while largely exempting rich 
people and corporations, including Alaska's powerful oil industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Some opponents want deep budget cuts, others want an income tax,  
and still others want to increase taxes on the oil industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``This vote is telling the leaders in the Legislature, the  
Republican leaders especially, to look for other sources of 
revenue,'' said Paula Phillips, a spokeswoman for Alaska 
Conservation Voters. ``The business sector, including oil and big 
tourism, are just going to have to contribute to the solution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The move to put the plan on the ballot began last winter, when  
oil prices dropped below $9 a barrel and the projected budget gap 
for the current fiscal year grew to more than $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, oil has climbed to more than $23 a barrel, shrinking  
the budget gap to a projected $632 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
