<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retired News Agency Head Dies at 82 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Elvezio Bianchi, who reported on postwar Italy for  
United Press for two decades and later headed Agenzia Italia, one 
of the country's leading news agencies, died Tuesday night. He was 
82. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement by his family did not give the cause of death.  
</P>
<P>
	Bianchi joined United Press before World War II as a copy boy.  
After the war, he became news editor. In 1966, he was appointed 
director of AGI, originally founded by Italy's state-owned oil 
company ENI. 
</P>
<P>
	AGI expanded into business and financial news and distributed  
major international news agencies, including The Associated Press 
and AP-DowJones, to the country's media. 
</P>
<P>
	He retired in 1981. He is survived by his widow, Luciana, a  
daughter, Nicoletta and a son, Massimo. Funeral arrangements were 
scheduled in Rome at San Lorenzo Outside the Walls on Thursday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
