<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unions Against Pakistan Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The AFL-CIO is joining an international  
campaign to pressure U.S. companies that sell or buy surgical tools 
to make sure the instruments are not made by child laborers in 
Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thousands of children in Pakistan, some as young as eight  
years old, have never been to school. Instead, these kids are 
making surgical instruments commonly used in hospitals, doctor's 
offices, and medical centers every day, all across America,'' 
AFL-CIO President John Sweeney said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Unions within the labor federation representing nurses and other  
health care workers have pledged to bring the issue to the 
bargaining table, if necessary, or use their clout as large 
investors of union pension money. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pakistani government has estimated that at least 7,000  
children under the age of 14 work in the country's surgical 
manufacturing industry, doing dangerous jobs such as metal cutting, 
grinding and sandblasting. Many of the children labor in small 
workshops that contract with larger Pakistani vendors that export 
the tools. 
</P>
<P>
	About half of Pakistan's $125 million in annual exports of  
surgical instruments -- such as scalpels and scissors -- go to the 
United States, according to Public Services International, a 
France-based alliance of government workers' unions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The eyes of the world really are on the U.S. in this matter,''  
said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, an activist against child labor. 
</P>
<P>
	PSI has written to nine U.S. companies that it believes may buy  
surgical tools from Pakistani vendors, in turn selling to American 
health plans, hospitals and doctors' and dentists' offices. 
</P>
<P>
	In responses received so far, including from Johnson &AMP; Johnson  
and Baxter International Inc., the companies have denied 
connections to vendors using child labor in Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Patricia Molino, a Johnson &AMP; Johnson vice president, wrote  
Tuesday that the company has strict rules against doing business 
with such vendors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't accepted those assurances on face value and have  
undertaken additional evaluations of the situation in Pakistan,'' 
wrote Molino, but she added, ``We remain very interested in any 
information you can share with us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The unions said they will urge U.S. companies to submit to  
independent investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody is using child labor, if you believe them,'' said PSI  
General Secretary Hans Engelberts. ``We want a monitoring system so 
that we can check.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations' International Labor Organization launched a  
program this week to monitor surgical tool production sites in 
Pakistan and send child laborers there to school. 
</P>
<P>
	The union campaign will also target U.S. health plans and  
hospital companies that buy large quantities of surgical equipment, 
asking them to hold their suppliers accountable. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
