<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schools Providing Mental Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dr. Mark Weist only gets to visit Southwestern  
High School in central Baltimore one day a week. But even that one 
day has given the therapist a chance to save lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had young people who are suicidal or seriously depressed  
referred to me in a state of crisis,'' said Weist. ``But I was able 
to make a connection with them, involve the family, provide more 
intensive care.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's the value of bringing mental health care into the schools  
where children can get it, said Weist, who also directs the Center 
for School Mental Health Assistance at the University of Maryland 
at Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	The typical school health center deals with scissors accidents,  
routine eye exams and measles shots. But, as recent high-profile 
school shootings highlighted the need to heal children's minds as 
well, many of the nation's 1,200 school health centers are 
including mental health in their mission. Today, school-based 
mental health advocates will begin their fourth annual conference 
in Denver, expecting 500 attendees up from just about 200 at the 
first conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kids who are being abused, contending with neglect, dealing  
with violence, depressed or are acting out cannot learn,'' said 
Weist, who expects a cadre of child psychologists, school health 
professionals, teachers, health educators, youth advocates, family 
members and legislators to come up with ways of improving 
school-based mental health care. 
</P>
<P>
	Weist's Baltimore-based center is one of two national training  
facilities and five state pilot projects for mental health in 
schools established in 1995 by the Health and Human Services 
Department. Advocates estimate 10 million children nationwide ages 
10 to 17 lack proper mental health care. 
</P>
<P>
	In an annual policy speech Wednesday, Education Secretary  
Richard Riley called on Congress to increase funding for mental 
health counseling. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly we need to have many more counselors and mentors in  
our high schools and not just to help young people get ready for 
college,'' Riley said in the speech that focused on an emerging 
high school population boom. 
</P>
<P>
	Children were in need of help long before April's shooting at a  
Littleton, Colo., high school, said Weist. But the tragedy and 
others like it opened many discussions on the subject of child 
mental health. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had lots of kids not coming to school after that,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Policy-makers, too, have reacted by providing more funds. This  
spring, the federal government launched a $1.3 million study of the 
link between abuse and neglected children and later criminal acts. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers are also trained at the Center for Mental Health in  
Schools at the University of California, Los Angeles. Kentucky, 
Maine, Minnesota, New Mexico and South Carolina have statewide 
projects providing school-based mental health. 
</P>
<P>
	But more money is need, particularly for staff, educators argue.  
Nationally, on average, there's one teacher for every 17 students, 
but a single counselor for every 513 students. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many students bring problems to school that principals and  
teachers are simply not equipped to handle,'' argues Gerald N. 
Tirozzi, executive director of the National Association of 
Secondary School Principals. ``They need the help of qualified 
professionals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weist says school mental health advocates must also battle  
problems of public perception: ``If these programs are not in 
schools, then reality is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Workers try to assure parents and children that students are not  
being manipulated or unfairly diagnosed because of language or 
cultural differences. Instead, students who may have had to travel 
across town and wait endlessly for appointments in a crowded 
community clinic, can take time out at school to confidentially 
discuss problems ranging from drug addiction to sexual abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	In the long run, children can focus on their lessons, Weist  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Baltimore school, positive peer pressure has brought many  
more students to Weist's door. 
</P>
<P>
	``The longer we're in school; the less stigmatizing the program  
is,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
