<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cards' Ankiel Moving to Bullpen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- It's certainly not a demotion, but St. Louis  
Cardinals phenom Rick Ankiel will be moving to the bullpen for the 
rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals simply don't want to overwork Ankiel and strain  
the arm of what could be the team's ace for years to come. So 
manager Tony La Russa said Wednesday that Ankiel's days as a 
starter are over until 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The 20-year-old left-hander allowed one run in five innings, and  
did not get the decision, in the Cardinals' 4-1 loss to Milwaukee 
on Tuesday. That gave him 28 innings in five starts, but 165 2-3 
innings overall during a season-long rise from Double-A. And he's 
thrown a lot of pitches, considering his 224 strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we'll do is give him his complete rest so by Sunday,  
which would be his fifth day, we'd have him available in the 
bullpen,'' La Russa said. ``And maybe he'll be in a situation late 
in the game to pitch an inning here or there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ankiel, 0-1 with a 3.86 ERA with the Cardinals, is nearing the  
innings target set for him. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Ankiel was effective with an extra day's rest  
Tuesday. La Russa was cautious with him that game, pulling him from 
a 1-1 game after five innings and 86 pitches. In his previous 
start, Ankiel struggled in the sixth and walked four -- one with the 
bases loaded. 
</P>
<P>
	But if Ankiel is feeling the strain of the innings, he's not  
letting on. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel normal, I guess, for playing a season,'' Ankiel said.  
``I don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ankiel, who's far from the most expansive interview subject,  
didn't seem too disappointed that he got his first career hit 
before his first victory. He has four no-decisions, and the 
Cardinals have lost all five of his starts. 
</P>
<P>
	``You get out there and get a chance to compete at this level  
and kind of see how hitters react,'' he said. ``I think I'm 
learning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Certainly, he doesn't seem in awe of his surroundings even  
though he was pitching in high school a little more than two years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really didn't think about what it would be like,'' Ankiel  
said. ``I try and focus on throwing to the mitt, and not worrying 
about where I'm at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To some opponents, he looks like a seasoned veteran.  
</P>
<P>
	``Ankiel has a lot of poise and know-how for 20 years old,''  
Brewers pitcher Scott Karl said. ``He's got super stuff, so fluid 
on the mound. He looks so nice and easy and throws it 93 or 94 
mph.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To others, he's definitely a work in progress.  
</P>
<P>
	``When things go a little awry and he walks a guy or gives up a  
hit, he's not in a comfort zone,'' said Jeff Cirillo, who doubled 
and scored in the fourth. ``That's to be expected from a young guy 
pitching in the big leagues for the first time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	La Russa can't wait to see the finished product.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's real good, already,'' La Russa said. ``Imagine what he's  
going to be. He's a beautiful young man.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
