<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heinz, Bestfoods Stocks Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Although H.J. Heinz Co. refused comment and  
Bestfoods denied rumors the two were in merger talks, investors bid 
up their shares Wednesday on the prospect of takeovers boosting the 
value of food companies' lagging stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts in the food industry have long advised that big food  
makers may have to merge to boost lagging earnings, firm up their 
global presence and answer the call for cheaper prices from large 
grocery chains. 
</P>
<P>
	``Food companies have lost 10 percent of their value on average,  
while the market is up 10 percent. So there's a 20 percent spread 
there. You've got a group of shareholders who are getting pretty 
darn frustrated,'' said analyst Terry Bivens of Bear Stearns. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumors of merger talks between Bestfoods and Heinz were first  
reported in Wednesday's edition of The Wall Street Journal. Dow 
Jones News later Wednesday reported that talks had broken off 
Tuesday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Heinz, best known for its ketchup, has a product lineup that  
includes StarKist tuna and Ore-Ida french fries. Bestfoods is the 
maker of Hellmann's mayonnaise, Entenmann's baked goods, Skippy 
peanut butter and Knorr soups and sauces. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh-based Heinz refused to confirm or deny that it was  
talking to Bestfoods, while Bestfoods issued a statement saying 
``no significant acquisition or combination discussions are in 
progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it was responding to press reports and noted it  
was ``departing on this occasion from its continuing policy of not 
commenting on rumors or market activity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heinz's no-comment was typical of companies that are the subject  
of Wall Street rumors. That Bestfoods went a step further intrigued 
Bivens, who said an investor might infer something is going on with 
the Englewood, N.J. company. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know Heinz would like to do it. I think the real question is  
what's Bestfood's disposition on this,'' said Bivens. ``As I look 
across the food category, this would be the best combination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Bestfoods jumped up $4.81 1/4, a 8.5 percent gain, to  
$53.12 1/2. Shares of Heinz were up $1.43 3/4, or 3.3 percent, to close 
at $44.62 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Heinz and Bestfoods come together, it would be a merger of  
equals -- not an acquisition, The Journal reported. Heinz has annual 
sales of $9.3 billion, while Bestfoods, of Englewood, N.J., has 
about $8.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, their sales would be $17.7 billion annually, making  
the combined company the third-largest food company in the world 
behind Europe's Nestle SA, with $52 billion in sales, and 
U.S.-based Kraft Foods, with $27 billion, the newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Merrill Lynch and Salomon Smith Barney have issued reports  
suggesting the time is right for food manufacturers to consider 
acquisitions or mergers. 
</P>
<P>
	The firms said most big food companies have reached a point  
where they are having trouble generating profits and will have to 
merge to consolidate costs, increase market share or find new 
distribution channels to combat increasing pressure from a 
consolidating grocery industry that is demanding lower prices as 
its buying power grows. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've all been waiting for this consolidation to start. Maybe  
this will be it,'' said Bill Leach of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. 
</P>
<P>
	``The real problem in the food industry is there's just not any  
sales growth,'' Leach added. ``Heinz seems like it has a 
restructuring every couple of years. Their factories are pretty 
efficient; there's just not a lot you can do to improve the 
margins.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
