<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds To Hear Insurance Complaints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal bank regulators have signed new  
agreements with seven states to share information about customer 
complaints related to insurance sales by banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The move announced Wednesday brings to 16 the number of states  
that have signed such accords, and more are expected in the near 
future. It comes as Congress gets closer to enacting sweeping 
legislation that would lift Depression-era legal barriers and allow 
banks, securities firms and insurance companies to get into each 
other's businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks now sell a small amount of insurance, but sales are  
expected to grow substantially in the near future, regulators say. 
</P>
<P>
	The new information-sharing agreements were announced by the  
Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, the Treasury Department 
division that oversees nationally chartered banks. They were signed 
by the Comptroller's office and insurance regulators in Alabama, 
Arizona, Arkansas, Connecticut, Indiana, Maryland and West 
Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	``These agreements enhance consumer protection and assure  
compliance with appropriate insurance sales standards,'' 
Comptroller John D. Hawke said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators couldn't immediately provide examples of consumer  
complaints about insurance sales by banks. But Consumers Union and 
the Independent Insurance Agents of America, whose members compete 
with banks, have maintained that many consumers are confused about 
whether insurance sold by banks is federally guaranteed -- as bank 
deposits are -- and therefore could be misled by bank salespeople. 
</P>
<P>
	The groups also say consumers are vulnerable to pressure to buy  
insurance, notably credit life insurance, when they apply for loans 
from banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new agreements, the Comptroller's office will forward  
to the state insurance regulators copies of any complaints it 
receives regarding to sales of insurance in that state by a bank. 
The state regulators will do the same. Confidentiality of all 
shared information will be maintained. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar accords previously had been signed with Delaware,  
Kansas, Kentucky, Louisiana, Maine, North Carolina, North Dakota, 
Oklahoma and Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	The Comptroller's office said Wednesday it had completed  
negotiations with three other states, which it did not name, and 
that it expected to sign agreements with them in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial services legislation cleared the House in July  
with a veto-proof vote, 343-86. House and Senate negotiators have 
been trying to blend the package with a substantially different 
version passed by the Senate in May. The Clinton administration 
supports the legislation in principle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
