<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Military Pay Raise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House approved a bill Wednesday that  
boosts spending for the military -- and raises pay -- despite 
reservations from some Democrats about the measure's proposed 
revamping of the nation's nuclear weapons programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The $289 billion military spending bill passed 375-45. It  
already had been approved by House-Senate negotiators and is 
expected to get final approval in the Senate, probably next week. 
</P>
<P>
	But the legislation, which increases military spending by $18  
billion over this year, also directs a reorganization of the Energy 
Department, creating a largely independent nuclear weapons agency 
within the department. 
</P>
<P>
	That had some Democrats concerned and has prompted a possible  
veto by President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The reorganization has wide support in Congress after months of  
controversy over allegations of lax security and Chinese espionage 
involving the nuclear weapons labs and the mishandling of a spy 
investigation at the Los Alamos lab dating back to 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said in an interview that he  
``most likely'' would recommend a veto of the defense bill because 
it puts too much power into the hands of the new agency. 
</P>
<P>
	While supporting creation of a new agency within the department,  
he said the House-passed provision ``endangers health, safety and 
environmental oversight'' of the nuclear weapons program and would 
jeopardize security and counterespionage improvements he already 
has made. 
</P>
<P>
	An attempt to rework the Energy Department portion of the bill  
was rejected by 281-139. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans and many Democrats, particularly those from  
districts with defense sites, said too much was at stake for 
America's military in the bill to open it up again for changes 
because of the Energy Department reorganization. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would provide $8.3 billion more for the military  
in fiscal 2000 than was sought by President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	It includes a widely popular 4.8 percent military pay raise;  
more money for military barracks and family housing, and increased 
spending for readiness, maintenance and military hardware from $176 
million for 17 new Black Hawk helicopters to $3.7 billion for a 
ballistic missile defense system. 
</P>
<P>
	``The military's readiness is in jeopardy,'' said Rep. Duncan  
Hunter, R-Calif., referring to the dispute over DOE reorganization. 
``It would be a tragedy to defeat this bill for some turf fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., said he supported the defense  
provisions, but criticized the creation of a National Nuclear 
Security Administration that would be largely insulated from the 
rest of the Energy Department and even the secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	``It returns us to the dark secretive days ... when the Atomic  
Energy Commission lied to everybody,'' declared Dingell. The AEC 
during much of the Cold War years worked largely in secret and in 
producing America's nuclear arsenal also left major environment 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Mac Thornberry, R-Texas, who was key in crafting the DOE  
reorganization provision, said the new agency will ``establish a 
clear chain of command ... where accountability is no longer a 
question'' when it comes to the nuclear weapons labs and security. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., said the new agency still would be  
subject to environmental and worker safety laws. ``It will not 
result in any reversal of any existing environmental policies,'' 
insisted Spence. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers rushed to put the measure into the defense bill amid  
the outcry in recent months over the handing of a three-year 
espionage investigation at the Los Alamos weapons lab in New 
Mexico. A scientist at the lab was fired in March for security 
violations after being under investigation since 1996 in the 
apparent theft of nuclear secrets in the 1980s. He has not been 
charged with a crime. 
</P>
<P>
	An internal Energy Department review was critical of the  
handling of the investigation. Recently three Los Alamos officials, 
including its former director, were given reprimands and other 
disciplinary action involving the spy investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	A congressional panel this summer produced a report that alleged  
widespread Chinese theft of America's nuclear secrets dating back 
20 years or more because of inattention at the Energy Department 
and weapons labs to security and counterespionage. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently a presidential commission on intelligence called for  
creation of a semiautonomous nuclear weapons agency within the DOE 
saying that the department was not capable of reforming itself. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
