<DOCNO> APW19990915.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 07:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Savannah: What, Me Worry? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) -- As Hurricane Floyd barreled toward him, Dr.  
David Thomas sat on the steps of his 1889 Italianate home on 
Monterey Square, calmly sipping orange juice and staring at the 
moss-draped live oaks and towering magnolias. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before an improved forecast eased the minds of city  
residents today, nailing plywood was the furthest thing from 
Thomas' mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I figure if it's been here over 100 years and it's withstood  
it without any problems, it'll probably withstand this one -- 
hopefully,'' Thomas said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	His three-story home is across from Mercer House, made famous by  
the book and movie ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas' sentiments appeared to be shared by most in historic  
Savannah, where precious few of the graceful antebellum mansions 
were boarded or even had their windows taped. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials had reason to worry Tuesday. The Georgia Emergency  
Management Agency had predicted Floyd would rake Savannah and other 
coastal cities with 125 mph wind late today. But as the storm took 
a more eastward track, that estimate was lowered today to 50-60 
mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Chatham County, of which Savannah is the seat, ordered all  
250,000 residents to evacuate Tuesday. The director of the county's 
emergency operations center, Phillip Weber, said today the 
evacuation order would stay in effect, even with the improved 
forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that we have a bluebird day here in Savannah, but we  
can't afford to plan that way. This storm is not a dot on a track. 
... We can't afford to let our guard down,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But many in the historic district were staying put Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to stay down on the first floor in the hall at the  
peak of the storm and just sit there and play cards and drink 
wine,'' said Barbara Hofer, 67, who lives behind Mercer House. 
``It's four bricks thick all the way around -- brick all the way up, 
three stories.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others weren't willing to gamble. At Bonaventure Cemetery,  
pictured on the ``Midnight'' cover jacket, a few people removed 
statues from the graves of relatives. Bonaventure, where songwriter 
Johnny Mercer and other leading citizens of Savannah are buried, 
sits on the Savannah River and could flood. 
</P>
<P>
	The monument for Revolutionary War hero Casimir Pulaski, which  
had been on display at the Coastal Heritage Museum, was put in 
storage. 
</P>
<P>
	On Lafayette Square, workers rushed to remove 112 feet of  
scaffolding from the twin spires of St. John the Baptist Cathedral, 
one of Savannah's oldest churches at 200-plus years. The 
scaffolding was erected to repair the church's stucco surface. 
</P>
<P>
	Savannah's historic district sits on a bluff above the Savannah  
River, 20 miles inland and high enough to keep most of downtown 
from flooding, city officials said. Their main worry was that wind 
and debris could breach old homes and buildings, letting water seep 
in from heavy rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Savannah residents worried most about damage to the  
towering oaks that give the city some of its distinctive natural 
beauty. But city officials expect many will survive. 
</P>
<P>
	Savannah wasn't the only place in Georgia worried about  
protecting its historic buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers on Jekyll Island shuttered the ``millionaire cottages''  
built by the Rockefellers and Pulitzers. At Fort McAllister, where 
Gen. William T. Sherman ended his March to the Sea after burning 
Atlanta, state workers removed military artifacts, including small 
arms and artillery shells. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in Savannah, Thomas was more worried about his boat docked  
in the harbor than his home. 
</P>
<P>
	That, he said, will ``be here after I'm gone.''  
</P>
<P>
                            	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	Allen G. Breed is the AP's Southeast regional writer, based in  
Raleigh, N.C. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
