<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bombing Prosecutor Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The U.S. attorney who helped prosecute  
Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols in the Oklahoma City bombing case 
has resigned, saying he planned to return to private practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick M. Ryan said that while he was disappointed that Nichols  
did not receive the death penalty for the explosion that killed 168 
people, he believed justice was done. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan, 53, was sworn in as U.S. attorney for the Western District  
of Oklahoma 19 days before the bombing. He devoted the following 
three years to preparing the case for trial in Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will never forget the many thousands of victims of the April  
19, 1995, tragedy that I have worked with and met over the past 
several years,'' Ryan wrote in his letter of resignation to 
Attorney General Janet Reno. ``Their stories and faces are forever 
etched in my memory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He told The Associated Press on Wednesday that he would keep his  
promise to the victims not to write a book about the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the facts are out,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	His resignation is effective Oct. 20.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
