<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pianist Williams Planning Recital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Pianist Roger Williams plans to be at the  
keyboard the moment he turns 75. 
</P>
<P>
	The entertainer, known for hits like ``Autumn Leaves,'' ``Born  
Free,'' ``Lara's Theme'' and ``The Impossible Dream,'' is planning 
a 12-hour recital to celebrate the occasion. 
</P>
<P>
	The marathon will begin Sept. 30 and end Oct. 1 -- his birthday --  
at the grand opening of Steinway Hall of Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	``Recently, my kids and my friends started asking me what I  
wanted to do for my 75th birthday,'' Williams said Monday. ``Well, 
I love to play and I love to play people's requests. So in 12 
hours, I'm going to get to do a lot of what I love to do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 14:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quayle Opposes Troops in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, N.H. (AP) -- The United States should stop being ``an  
international 911 operator'' and keep American troops out of East 
Timor, former Vice President Dan Quayle said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a superpower, our role is not peacekeeping,'' the  
Republican presidential candidate told Dover Rotary Club members. 
``Our role is peacemaking ... I do not believe that even though we 
are the only superpower, we should be the global policemen of the 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration said Wednesday that sending troops to  
East Timor could help Indonesia's transition to democracy and 
protect U.S. military and economic interests. But Quayle said the 
U.S. military already is stretched too thin. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're spread all over the world, and when there is a serious  
crisis in an important region of the world, we may not be able to 
do the job,'' he said. ``Bill Clinton has taken the bar so low in 
foreign policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle said Clinton has ``cut at the heart and soul'' of the  
military by letting it dwindle in size. He proposes building it up 
with the money generated by his proposed tax cut, a freeze on 
non-defense discretionary spending and shrinking the federal 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	The departments of Education and Labor should be folded into the  
Department of Health and Human Services, he said, to save money and 
provide ``one-stop shopping.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle was unfazed by his poor showing in state polls -- 3  
percent of likely New Hampshire primary voters said they'd vote for 
Quayle in a WMUR-CNN poll released this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been behind before,'' he said. ``I just have to take my  
message to the people and let them choose. I think after I do that, 
I'll do exceedingly well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle said he has enough money to get through the New  
Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary and will evaluate his 
support after that. 
</P>
<P>
	Rotary member Dave Azarian, a Democrat, said he was more  
impressed with Quayle than he anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think if he can continues like this, he's going to do a lot  
to restore the impression people have of him,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
