<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disney: No Deal Near on Angels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. isn't close to a  
deal to sell either the Anaheim Angels or the NHL's Mighty Ducks, 
the company's executive in charge of the teams said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's been highly exaggerated,'' said Tony Tavares, the  
president of Anaheim Sports Inc., a Disney subsidiary. ``It's not 
actively being shopped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, columnist Peter Gammons wrote for ESPN.com  
that Disney has ``completed the parameters of a deal'' to sell the 
baseball and hockey clubs to billionair Henry Nicholas III for $650 
million. ESPN.com, which is a Web site for Disney-owned cable 
broadcaster ESPN. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analysts have valued the Angels-Ducks package at $375  
million to $425 million, but Nicholas ``stepped up and closed the 
deal,'' the columnist wrote. Nicholas is president and chief 
executive of Broadcom Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Tavares said Disney was approached by people interested in the  
teams about four months ago and was ``in a listening mode.'' But he 
said talks hadn't even progressed to where the team would seek 
permission from the commissioner's office to show its books to 
prospective suitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney took control of the team from Gene Autry in March 1996  
and bought a 100 percent interest following his death last year. 
Tavares said the Angels' poor performance -- they began the day 
60-85, 26 1/2 games behind first-place Texas in the AL West -- was not 
a factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question is not whether they're satisfied with how the  
teams have gone,'' Tavares said. ``It would be whether or not this 
is on point for their strategic goals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tavares likened people who express interest in become sports  
team owners to ``people who come into an auto dealership and kick 
the tires.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
