<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower Wednesday  
on Wall Street's overnight slide and rising jitters over a possible 
U.S. interest-rate hike. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese financial markets were closed for a public holiday.  
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks plunged as higher-than-expected U.S. retail  
sales data sparked concerns that the U.S. Federal Reserve might 
increase interest rate to dampen inflationary pressure before the 
end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index shed 373.43 points, or 2.7  
percent, closing at 13,430.60. On Tuesday, the index had lost 56.82 
points, or 0.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong interest rates traditionally track U.S. rates to  
maintain the local currency's link to the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	In Singapore, share prices closed mixed as investors were  
sidelined by worries about the drop on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark Straits Times Index fell 21.92 points, or 1.02  
percent, to 2,120.58 points. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped  
120.00 points, or 1.09 percent, to finish at 10,910.33. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian shares also plunged, as investors scrambled to take  
profits amid the growing political fallout from a bank scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index fell 13.447 points,  
or 2.4 percent, to 548.612. 
</P>
<P>
	Alleged financial irregularities at Bank Bali center on a $80  
million transfer from the bank to a company controlled by a senior 
official in the ruling Golkar party. Golkar opponents claim the 
funds were meant to finance President B.J. Habibie's re-election 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	News of protests in various parts of Jakarta in response to the  
upcoming deployment of troops to East Timor also unnerved the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading in Asia, the dollar was quoted at 105.35  
yen, down from 105.92 yen late in New York the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is getting more and more concerned about what the  
yen's strength means for Japanese asset markets,'' said Patrick 
Bennett, foreign exchange analyst at Warburg Dillon Read in 
Singapore. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed lower. The SET Index fell 5.23  
points, or 1.2 percent, to 438.59. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed lower. The Composite  
Index closed down 11.31 points, or 1.6 percent, at 717.74 points. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks fell on U.S. interest rate concerns.  
The PSE index closed down 27.13 points, or 1.3 percent, at 
2,074.08. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: South Korean shares fell 1.6 percent as investors cashed  
in for the second straight day following recent gains. The Kospi 
index fell 15.85 points to 952.69. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares closed lower as negative sentiment  
from Wall Street dampened local industrial share prices. The All 
Ordinaries Index closed at 2,938.1, down 37.8 points, or 1.3 
percent.. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Taiwan shares closed lower as investors cashed in on  
recent gains in heavily weighted, high-priced technology shares. 
The Weighted Price Index finished down 120.98 points, or 1.49 
percent, at 7,971.04. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower, dragged down  
by a sharp drop in Telecom Corp. of New Zealand Ltd. The NZSE-40 
Capital Index ended down 25.26 points, or 1.2 percent, at 2,095.71. 



</P>
</TEXT>
