<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Sept. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 108.91  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors brushed off a government report that  
showed little evidence of rising inflation, driving stocks lower 
today. The dollar's continued weakness against the Japanese yen 
also undercut stocks. At the close of trading on Wall Street, the 
Dow Jones industrial average was down 108.91, or by 1 percent, at 
10,801.42. The index had tumbled from an early gain of 103 points, 
with the selloff gaining momentum in the final hour. Broader stock 
indicators also closed lower, with the technology heavy Nasdaq 
composite index especially hard hit after rising yesterday. The 
Nasdaq was down 54.13 at 2,814.16. today. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,801.42  - 108.91
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1,180  Declines 1,767  Unchgd  548
NYSE Volume:         752,607,520
Most Active NYSE issue:         Boston Scientific27       - 8 5/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1316.65 - 19.64
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          797.48   -  4.00
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,814.16   - 54.13
Gold(final) -    $256.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.
Silver(final) -   $5.060  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Prices Rise 0.3 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Motorists got another shock at the gasoline  
pumps last month but elsewhere consumer prices remained subdued. 
Falling costs for clothing, computers, airline tickets and new cars 
pushed the core inflation rate to the lowest level in 33 years, the 
government reported. The Labor Department said today that its 
Consumer Price Index was up 0.3 percent overall in August, but 
outside of the volatile food and energy areas, prices rose just 0.1 
percent. But even with the good news in the underlying rate of 
inflation, many economists said they still expected the Federal 
Reserve will raise interest rates for a third time this year at its 
meeting Oct. 5. 

</P>
<P>
	Business Inventories Rise 0.3 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department said today that  
inventories held by businesses on shelves and backlots rose by 0.3 
percent in July while business sales rose at an even faster 0.4 
percent clip. That left the ratio of inventories to sales at a 
record low of 1.34 months, meaning it would take that length of 
time to exhaust supplies at the current sales pace. 

</P>
<P>
	European Stocks Fall on Fed Concern  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Stocks fell in Europe today as traders worried  
about a possible U.S. interest rate increase by the Federal Reserve 
next month. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies 
fell 1.07 points, or 0.3 percent, to close at 311.33. A report 
Tuesday showing strong consumer spending in the United Staets 
helped fan fears that the Fed may raise rates when it meets again 
in October. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index fell 9.33 points to 
3,816.53, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed down 9.22 points at 
3,700.92. In European markets, Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 0.3 
percent. The Paris and London bourses were the worst performers, 
with a drop of 0.8 percent in both the CAC-40 and FTSE 100 indexes. 
In London, heavyweight oil stocks came under pressure, with BP 
Amoco and Shell closing down. 

</P>
<P>
	UAW, Auto Makers in Intensive Talks  
</P>
<P>
	AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Bargainers for the major U.S. car  
companies and the United Auto Workers continued intensive 
negotiations today after the union granted an open-ended extension 
to contracts that cover 407,000 workers. The focus of the talks was 
at DaimlerChrysler's U.S. headquarters, where the two sides met 
through the night. They took a short break at midmorning, returning 
to the table this afternoon. Neither side would comment on 
progress, but the marathon session was taken as a sign a deal could 
be imminent. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds To Hear Insurance Complaints  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal bank regulators have signed new  
agreements with seven states to share information about customer 
complaints related to insurance sales by banks. The move announced 
today brings to 16 the number of states that have signed such 
accords. More are expected in the near future. The development 
comes as Congress gets closer to enacting sweeping legislation that 
would lift Depression-era legal barriers and allow banks, 
securities firms and insurance companies to get into each other's 
businesses. 

</P>
<P>
	Patagonia Founder Steps Down As CEO  
</P>
<P>
	VENTURA, Calif. (AP) -- The founder of the company that makes  
Patagonia outdoor clothing, noted alpinist Yvon Chouinard, is 
stepping down as chief executive officer to spend more time 
pursuing his two passions: surfing and mountain climbing. 
Chouinard, 60, will still own Patagonia's parent company, the Lost 
Arrow Corp. based in Ventura, Calif. Michael Crooke, most recently 
CEO at Pearl Izumi, a cycling and sports apparel company in 
Colorado, was named chief executive officer. He will move to 
Ventura in mid-October. 

</P>
<P>
	Oracle Slips After Earnings Report  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Shares in Oracle Corp. tumbled today  
after the database software developer reported first quarter 
profits that met Wall Street estimates, but fell short of more 
ambitious expectations. For the three months ended Aug. 31, Oracle 
reported net income of $236.7 million, or 16 cents a share, up 21 
percent from $195 million, or 13 cents a share, in the comparable 
period a year ago. Revenue rose 13 percent, to $1.98 billion from 
$1.75 billion, Oracle reported late Tuesday. Oracle shares weere 
down 2 3/4 at 42 11/16 today. 

</P>
<P>
	US West Plans Cheaper Web Access  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hoping to capture a wider audience, U S West  
Corp. is offering more for less with a new dial-up version of a 
digital subscriber line, or DSL. The Baby Bell phone company which 
serves 14 Western states, said toda its MegaBit Select is being 
introduced throughout its service area after a trial run in four 
cities. The service costs $19.95 a month, $10 less than what U S 
West charges for a continuous Internet connection via DSL. DSL 
allows people to access the Internet at speeds five times faster 
than the fastest dial-up modem installed on most desktop and laptop 
computers. 

</P>
<P>
	Motorola Buys General Instrument  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Motorola Inc. announced today that it had agreed  
to pay about $11 billion in stock for General Instrument Corp., the 
largest producer of cable TV set-top boxes. General Instrument's 
set-top box operations dominate one of the key technologies that is 
revolutionizing home entertainment. With the new equipment 
available today, the televisions of tomorrow can offer many more 
``broadband'' cable services, including Internet access, 
interactive video games and telephone services. Motorola stock was 
down 6 11/16 at 86 1/2 today; General Instrument Corp.was down 3 1/2 at 
47. 

</P>
<P>
	Dime Bancorp Getting Hudson United  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dime Bancorp Inc. is acquiring Hudson United  
Bancorp for $1.58 billion to create one of the largest regional 
banks in the Northeast with $32 billion in assets, the companies 
announced today. The 330 branches of the combined bank will operate 
under the DimeBank name in New York, New Jersey, Connecticut and 
Pennsylvania. The parent company, Dime United Bancorp Inc., will be 
based in New York. 

</P>
<P>
