<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Pledge Long-Term Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- The two Democratic presidential  
candidates, pressured by the state's large and active elderly 
community, signed pledges to find ``a comprehensive solution'' for 
long-term care. 
</P>
<P>
	Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley headed to a senior center to  
sign the pledge Wednesday, and added that he would push for 
prescription medication coverage as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore signed the same pledge ``without  
hesitation'' earlier in the week after meeting privately with 
leaders of AARP, the nation's largest lobby group for the elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	That group has made long-term care a top priority, arguing that  
it isn't covered by Medicare and most insurance policies. It has 
been pressuring presidential candidates to deal with the issue, and 
both Bradley and Gore signed the same pledge. 
</P>
<P>
	That pledge doesn't commit them to specific actions, but they  
agreed to make ``the long-term care crisis one of my 
administration's top priorities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It calls for a ``comprehensive solution drawing on both private  
and public financing methods.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley and Gore are competing in the state's leadoff precinct  
caucuses next winter and the elderly are a key group being courted. 
Iowa is the nation's third oldest state, and studies have shown 
that the elderly voter in heavier proportions than other 
demographic groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Nursing homes can cost thousands of dollars and month, and more  
for those requiring skilled care. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley held a roundtable with about a dozen seniors, telling  
them he'll offer a detailed health care package within a couple of 
weeks, but said it will have a component dealing with long-term 
care. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are about 25 million adult Americans who are caring for  
their elderly parents,'' said Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley argued for ``some form of Medicare drug benefit'' to  
ease the financial pinch facing the elderly, with the cost to come 
from the projected budged surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first priority in the use of that money should be health  
care and reducing child poverty,'' said Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	For his part Gore said long-term care issues have long been a  
priority, and he noted that the administration is pushing for a 
prescription drug benefit under Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	``Long-term care is a top priority of mine and will continue to  
be if I am elected president,'' Gore said. He signed the pledge 
Sunday night during a private meeting with AARP leaders, and his 
campaign issued a statement Wednesday about the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The focus on health care was shifted briefly during Bradley's  
appearance when he took note of a measure which passed the House 
banning so-called soft money from campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said the administration of which Gore is a part hasn't  
been terribly active on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this administration truly cared about this issue they  
should be up there breaking arms,'' said Bradley. ``This is a real 
test of how serious the administration is toward the elimination of 
soft money.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
