<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Braces for Hurricane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawmakers are fleeing, the president is  
rushing back from overseas and ordinary Washingtonians are 
hunkering down. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Hurricane Floyd is expected to be much weakened by  
the time it reaches Washington on Thursday, the capital's denizens 
aren't taking any chances. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish all my colleagues safe travel home,'' House Majority  
Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said Wednesday, as he and the other 
leaders canceled legislative business for the week so 
representatives could catch flights home in case local airports 
close. 
</P>
<P>
	Members hurried past a dozen or so ornate metal outdoor lounge  
chairs that had been brought inside from the Capitol's many 
balconies to protect them against Floyd's winds. 
</P>
<P>
	Senators, somehow hardier than their House colleagues, remained  
in town to finish their weekly work and ride the storm out. 
</P>
<P>
	And President Clinton nixed plans for a day of golfing in Hawaii  
-- where his plane was stopping to refuel after a five-day official 
trip to New Zealand -- so he could hurry home to face Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	For the people who live in and around Washington, flash flood  
warnings and predictions of winds up to 60 mph prompted a rash of 
school closings and a run on local markets 
</P>
<P>
	``People are shopping as if a blizzard were coming,'' said Mike  
Masoni, manager of the Giant Food Store in Bowie, Md., east of 
Washington. Shoppers stocked up on water, canned goods, ice, 
flashlights and batteries, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	When Floyd comes into range, sometime during the night, 3 to 6  
inches of rain are expected to fall in six hours or less, producing 
flash flooding and heavy winds, forecasters said. District of 
Columbia officials are expected to decide Thursday whether to 
declare a state of emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't like a sightseeing thing,'' said D.C. Mayor Anthony  
Williams. ``When you've got winds of 60 miles per hour, that's 
serious,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some commuter trains heading into Virginia and Maryland were  
canceled, and the Federal Aviation Administration said flights 
would likely be canceled at Ronald Reagan National Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexandria, a Virginian city just across the Potomac from  
Washington, prepared 2,000 sandbags, prompting its mayor, Kerry 
Donley, to declare, ``We're prepared for anything that Floyd's 
going to give us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The D.C. city government and several other local jurisdictions  
have instituted a ``liberal leave'' policy for nonessential 
employees. District businesses are encouraged to adopt similar 
policies. 
</P>
<P>
	But a tape recording at the Office of Personnel Management  
indicated neither hurricane nor floods nor an empty House of 
Representatives would keep government workers from their appointed 
rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``All federal employees are expected to report for work on  
time,'' it said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
