<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kimeses Indicted on Murder Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A mother and son held on murder charges in  
New York in the disappearance of a wealthy widow have been formally 
charged in the Los Angeles slaying of one of their business 
associates. 
</P>
<P>
	A felony complaint and arrest warrant filed Aug. 18 in Los  
Angeles Municipal Court and unsealed Wednesday accuses Sante Kimes, 
64, and her son, Kenneth Kimes, 23, with the murder of David 
Kazdin. The pair remained jailed in New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	The charge carries a possible death sentence, District Attorney  
spokeswoman Sandi Gibbons said Wednesday. Authorities do not expect 
to bring the mother and son to Los Angeles before the New York case 
is completed. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the Kimeses' lawyers said they were unaware of the  
complaint, which alleges that Kenneth Kimes ``personally and 
intentionally'' shot Kazdin to death in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazdin, 63, was found dead March 14, 1998, his body dumped into  
a trash bin. The felony complaint alleges the Kimeses killed Kazdin 
``for financial gain'' but did not give specifics of the motive. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyer Jose Muniz said the Los Angeles Police Department  
says it has one witness who says he helped dump the body. 
</P>
<P>
	``To our knowledge, they don't have any forensics tying Kenneth  
to the murder,'' Muniz said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kimeses were arrested in New York on July 5, 1998, on a Utah  
warrant alleging that they wrote a bad $14,000 check to buy a 
Lincoln Town Car. In the meantime, police learned that the Kimeses' 
landlady had vanished. 
</P>
<P>
	The mother and son became suspects in the disappearance of the  
landlady, wealthy widow Irene Silverman, 82, after police found 
Mrs. Silverman's personal and financial documents in the Kimeses' 
car. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also found a forged deed that purported to transfer Mrs.  
Silverman's Upper East Side mansion to the Kimeses for a fraction 
of its $4 million-plus worth. 
</P>
<P>
	In the car, police found loaded .9-mm and .22-caliber pistols,  
several wigs and masks, plastic handcuffs, $30,000 in cash, an 
empty stun gun box, a pink liquid similar to a known ``date rape'' 
drug, and cassettes of Mrs. Silverman's telephone conversations -- 
apparently taken from wire taps. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair also are suspected in the 1996 disappearance of a  
banker in the Bahamas and the disappearance of a drifter who was 
working with the Kimeses and vanished around the time the Kazdin 
was killed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
