<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Favre Said Ready for Lions Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Although a week of rest would probably do  
him good, Brett Favre and his battered throwing hand will be ready 
for Sunday's game against the Detroit Lions. 
</P>
<P>
	Favre said he has ``seen dramatic improvement'' in the condition  
of his hand, which has a sprained thumb and a muscle bruise after 
collisions during the preseason and in the Green Bay Packers' 28-24 
win over the Oakland Raiders last Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-time most valuable player doesn't plan on throwing a  
football until Friday, but said his streak of 110 consecutive 
starts won't be broken this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing with injuries is part of the game,'' Favre said.  
``More than likely, the remainder of the season it'll bother me one 
way or another. I'm ready for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Favre hit his hand on Russell Maryland's helmet in the third  
quarter of Green Bay's win over Oakland. He recovered to lead two 
fourth-quarter scoring drives, including an 11-play, 82-yard 
masterpiece in the final 1:51 for the winning points. 
</P>
<P>
	He suffered a sprained thumb during the preseason, and that  
injury still lingers. Favre also has a bruise and several scrapes 
on the hand, which was black-and-blue on Monday but now looks 
almost normal. 
</P>
<P>
	Favre doesn't expect to have the hand drained or to take a  
pain-killing shot, either. 
</P>
<P>
	The quarterback said that although a week off likely would help  
the hand heal more quickly, he wouldn't miss a game. With seven 
more starts he will pass Ron Jaworski for the longest starting 
streak by a quarterback in league history. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I took a week off, it probably would feel a lot better, but  
as long as I can keep slinging it, and not hurt my team, I feel 
like I can play,'' Favre said. ``They know well enough by now that 
I'm not going to come out unless I absolutely have to.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
