<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bahamians Assess Post-Floyd Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Residents and tourists ventured into  
debris-strewn streets today after Hurricane Floyd clobbered the 
Bahamas, washing ashore two barges and flinging trees onto streets 
and highways. 
</P>
<P>
	The huge storm toppled utility poles, ripped roofs off homes and  
pushed a roiling sea into streets Tuesday on the islands east of 
Florida before heading toward the southeastern United States. 
</P>
<P>
	No deaths were reported, although officials had yet to contact  
outlying islands because telephone lines were down, police 
Superintendent Conrad Sweeting said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My understanding is that there is a lot of coastal damage and  
structural damage to homes in New Providence and Grand Bahama,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At an emergency session of Parliament, Prime Minister Hubert  
Ingraham said he was flying to Cat and San Salvador islands and 
other officials were headed to Eleuthera and Abaco. Floyd's winds 
reached 110 mph on Eleuthera, San Salvador and Cat islands, and 
damage was feared to be extensive. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Mackie, operations director of JAMZ radio in Freeport, on  
the western end of Grand Bahama Island, said some areas were 
flooded and stranded residents had to be rescued in boats. Cars 
were floating in one neighborhood, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Nassau, on New Providence Island, major hotels were spared  
significant damage. Many tourists, tired of a storm whose winds 
began Monday night and didn't stop until early today, anxiously 
awaited word on when the airport would reopen. Downed utility poles 
and dangling wires slowed traffic to a crawl on many Nassau 
streets. 
</P>
<P>
	The sprawling Atlantis resort in Paradise Island reported only  
minor damage and said none of its 2,000 guests or 500 workers were 
hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wow, this is amazing,'' Andreas Appleby, 23, of Raleigh, N.C.,  
said while surveying the havoc wreaked in Nassau. ``I can't believe 
all of this damage was caused by one storm!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trees blocked the main highway linking the eastern and central  
parts of New Providence, and two barges were washed ashore near a 
busy street. There were reports of flooding up to 3 feet high in 
areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Several people, including one who fell off a roof, were being  
treated for minor injuries, ZNF government radio reported. Bahamas 
Defense Force personnel reported for duty today to help any relief 
and rescue operations. The U.S. Coast Guard said it was ready to 
respond to search and rescue requests. 
</P>
<P>
	Under brightly sunny skies, Nassau residents inspected smashed  
boats that had been beached. Workers shoveled three feet of sand 
from inside the bar at the Cocktails and Dreams nightclub, where a 
100-foot freighter, the Caribe 1, was beached outside. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
