<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:15 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Sept. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Prices Rise 0.3 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer prices rose 0.3 percent in August as  
gasoline and other energy products shot up for a second straight 
month. But elsewhere inflation remained a no-show with clothing 
prices down for a fourth straight month and airline fares 
retreating after a big jump in July. The Labor Department said 
today the August increase in its Consumer Price Index -- the most 
closely watched inflation gauge -- matched the 0.3 percent July 
advance. Two-thirds of the August price increase was attributed to 
a 2.7 percent surge in energy costs. Food costs rose a much more 
modest 0.2 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Business Inventories Rise 0.3 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department said that inventories  
held by businesses on shelves and backlots rose by 0.3 percent in 
July while business sales rose at an even faster 0.4 percent clip. 
That left the ratio of inventories to sales at a record low of 1.34 
months, meaning it would take that length of time to exhaust 
supplies at the current sales pace. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Up 25,86  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks rose this morning after a tame  
inflation report help calm investors' fears that the Federal 
Reserve would raise interest rates for the third time this year. 
But technology shares lost ground, giving up some of Tuesday's 
sharp gains. Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial 
average was up 25.96 at 10,936.29. Broader stock indicators were 
mixed, with the Nasdaq composite index down 22.00 at 2,846.29 after 
climbing more than 23 points on yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 11 a.m. EDT:  
