<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parts of Bell Networks Ordered Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Revising part of its market-opening rules,  
federal regulators decided Wednesday that major local telephone 
companies must still make available to rivals certain pieces of 
their networks. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Federal Communications Commission also granted the  
carriers -- including the regional Bell companies and GTE -- some 
relief by placing limits on what they are required to share and 
excluding equipment used for high-speed Internet services. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 5-0 vote, the FCC said Bell companies must continue to make  
available six items, including the wires that run from local phone 
company offices to homes and businesses. These are the most crucial 
network elements because they would be very expensive to duplicate. 
Bells must also provide a device that connects the lines to wiring 
inside customers homes. 
</P>
<P>
	But the commission determined that the Bell companies don't need  
to hand over operator and directory assistance services, since 
competitors could get those from other sources, such as third-party 
contractors. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission also declined to force the Bells and GTE to lease  
competitors equipment used for high-speed Internet services, like 
devices in central telephone offices that act as the counterparts 
to home modems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not going to regulate just for regulation's sake,''  
said FCC Chairman Bill Kennard. ``We're taking a lighter touch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Major local phone companies gave the plan mixed reviews. While  
pleased they would not have to make available their advanced 
services equipment, some said the FCC didn't go far enough to 
reduce their burdens. 
</P>
<P>
	``The FCC has taken only baby steps in the direction of  
deregulation,'' said Alan Ciamporcero, GTE's vice president of 
federal regulatory affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	``When competitors have already shown they can invest in new  
facilities, federal regulation shouldn't encourage them to 
piggyback on the facilities of others,'' said U S West spokesman 
David Fish. 
</P>
<P>
	Long-distance companies and upstarts supported the portions of  
the ruling that would enable them to get into the local phone 
market without having to build their own facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	But MCI WorldCom and AT&AMP;T said their efforts to roll out data  
services -- particularly to underserved and rural areas -- might be 
hampered because of the FCC's decision not to make available 
advanced equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard said he hoped the ruling would do just the opposite, by  
giving both incumbent and new companies an incentive to invest in 
advanced services and get them out more quickly to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to see high-speed Internet access in every home ...  
soon,'' Kennard said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC originally developed a list of items -- which did not  
include advanced services -- that local companies had to make 
available in 1996. The Supreme Court eventually sent the rules back 
to the commission, saying the FCC did not adequately consider 
whether competitors could obtain the pieces from another source. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
