<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Who Will Win Country Music Awards? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Ask Martie Seidel of the Dixie Chicks if  
her group will be named the top entertainer in country music this 
year, and she immediately starts talking like Garth. 
</P>
<P>
	Not Garth Brooks. Garth from Wayne and Garth, the goofy duo made  
famous on ``Saturday Night Live.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not worthy,'' Seidel said. ``I just don't think we're  
worthy of that at this point. I'd be embarrassed if we won that 
one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She may have to grin and bear it. After two years of domination  
by Brooks, the most prestigious annual award in the country music 
industry is likely to go elsewhere in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The CMA Awards will be handed out Sept. 22 in a ceremony  
broadcast live on CBS. About 6,800 members of the country music 
industry nominate and select the winners. 
</P>
<P>
	Here's a rundown of the nominations and some predictions about  
who will win: 
</P>
<P>
	ENTERTAINER: Garth Brooks, Dixie Chicks, Tim McGraw, George  
Strait, Shania Twain. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks probably won't win three in a row because voters  
generally have given the award in two-year blocks. Vince Gill won 
in 1993-94, Brooks in 1991-92, Strait in 1989-90, and Hank Williams 
Jr. in 1987-88. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Brooks currently is pursuing pop chart success, which will  
turn off some Nashville-centric voters. The veteran Strait is 
always a threat, but voters are more likely to award somebody fresh 
as they look to the next century. 
</P>
<P>
	That would make it a hard-to-call race between the Chicks,  
McGraw and Twain. The odds say McGraw will win because he's been 
the most steady and least controversial of the three. Twain 
probably deserves it the most, for outlasting charges she was a 
flash-in-the-pan and becoming a crossover phenomenon. 
</P>
<P>
	But the guess here is the Dixie Chicks. The flashy-dressing trio  
were the hit of this year's Lillith Fair, yet have been vocal about 
staying true to the country format. They continue their audacity 
with their new album ``Fly,'' which has a happy song about killing 
an abusive man, and another called ``Sin Wagon'' that talks about 
``mattress dancing.'' Mattress dancing is what you think it is. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	FEMALE VOCALIST: Faith Hill, Martina McBride, Jo Dee Messina,  
Shania Twain, Trisha Yearwood. 
</P>
<P>
	Twain, who has never won a CMA Award, should win this one. Only  
Faith Hill has had a big enough year to challenge her. And all 
those gossips who whispered that Twain didn't tour to support her 
``The Woman in Me'' CD because she doesn't sing well have had time 
to digest their crow. 
</P>
<P>
	Twain is a star, and was out on the road proving it for most of  
1999. She's here to stay, and CMA voters will finally acknowledge 
it. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MALE VOCALIST: Vince Gill, Alan Jackson, Tim McGraw, George  
Strait, Steve Wariner. 
</P>
<P>
	Strait has won this award for the past three years. Gill won it  
from 1991-95. Jackson missed his best time to win it because of the 
domination of the other two. Wariner has had an amazing comeback, 
but a nomination is as far as he'll probably get. Put your money on 
the hardworking, well-respected McGraw. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SINGLE: ``Amazed,'' Lonestar; ``Choices,'' George Jones; ``Don't  
Laugh at Me,'' Mark Wills; ``Please Remember Me,'' Tim McGraw; 
``Wide Open Spaces,'' Dixie Chicks. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be too perfect for Jones to cap his comeback from a  
near-fatal car wreck in March by winning this award. No matter, 
``Choices'' is the best song of this bunch, though ``Please 
Remember Me'' is a great Rodney Crowell ballad and the yearning in 
Natalie Maines' voice on ``Wide Open Spaces'' will win over many 
voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it's got to be The Possum for his ode to ``living and  
dying, with the choices I've made.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	ALBUM: ``A Place in the Sun,'' Tim McGraw; ``Always Never the  
Same,'' George Strait; ``The Key,'' Vince Gill; ``Two Teardrops,'' 
Steve Wariner; ``Where Your Road Leads,'' Trisha Yearwood. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Key'' is the best album of Gill's career and should have  
been a much bigger hit. Gill, longtime host of the CMA Awards, is 
beloved in the industry for his charity work and his willingness to 
lend his talent to help other artists. 
</P>
<P>
	McGraw and Strait are strong contenders in this category, but  
Gill will win. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HORIZON AWARD (for career progress): Kenny Chesney, Sara Evans,  
Jo Dee Messina, The Wilkinsons, Chely Wright. 
</P>
<P>
	Tough category to call. For sheer success, Chesney should win on  
the strength of his single, ``How Forever Feels,'' which stayed at 
No. 1 for six weeks. Wright and Evans haven't made as much career 
progress, but Messina and The Wilkinsons could make it a close race 
with Chesney, who will probably win by a hair. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	VOCAL GROUP: Alabama, Diamond Rio, Dixie Chicks, Lonestar, The  
Wilkinsons. 
</P>
<P>
	No contest. Dixie Chicks.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	VOCAL DUO: Brooks &AMP; Dunn, The Kinleys, The Lynns, Montgomery  
Gentry, The Warren Brothers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kinleys and Montgomery Gentry have livened up this category  
for the first time in years. But not enough to unseat Brooks &AMP; 
Dunn, who should win for the eighth straight time. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MUSIC VIDEO: ``Don't Laugh at Me,'' Mark Wills; ``How Forever  
Feels,'' Kenny Chesney; ``I'll Go On Loving You,'' Alan Jackson; 
``Just to Hear You Say That You Love Me,'' Faith Hill with Tim 
McGraw; ``Wide Open Spaces,'' Dixie Chicks. 
</P>
<P>
	This will be a chance to acknowledge Jackson with an award.  
Also, the video was great and the half-spoken/half sung ``I'll Go 
On Loving You'' was an innovative single that deserves recognition. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SONG (for songwriter): ``Don't Laugh at Me,'' Allen Shamblin,  
Steve Seskin; ``Husbands and Wives,'' Roger Miller; ``If You Ever 
Have Forever in Mind,'' Vince Gill, Troy Seals; ``Please Remember 
Me,'' Rodney Crowell, Will Jennings; ``This Kiss,'' Annie Roboff, 
Robin Lerner, Beth Nielsen Chapman. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong category. Roger Miller, a legendary performer still  
beloved in Nashville seven years after his death, could be the 
sentimental choice of many voters for his ``Husbands and Wives,'' 
which was revived by Brooks &AMP; Dunn. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	VOCAL EVENT: ``Old Dogs,'' Waylon Jennings, Mel Tillis, Bobby  
Bare, Jerry Reed; ``No Place That Far,'' Sara Evans and Vince Gill; 
``My Kind of Woman/My Kind of Man,'' Vince Gill and Patty Loveless; 
``Trio II,'' Emmylou Harris, Linda Ronstadt, Dolly Parton; ``Same 
Old Train,'' Clint Black, Joe Diffie, Merle Haggard, Emmylou 
Harris, Alison Krauss, Patty Loveless, Earl Scruggs, Ricky Skaggs, 
Marty Stuart, Pam Tillis, Randy Travis, Travis Tritt, Dwight 
Yoakam. 
</P>
<P>
	Another tough choice, but the pick here is ``Trio II,'' which  
would be a nice touch since Parton is being inducted into the 
Country Music Hall of Fame during the awards ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MUSICIAN: Eddie Bayers, Paul Franklin, Dann Huff, Brent Mason,  
Randy Scruggs. 
</P>
<P>
	Scruggs (son of banjo great Earl Scruggs) is the winner because  
he put out ``Crown of Jewels,'' a great overlooked album, and CMA 
voters know him better than the studio musicians who make up the 
rest of the field. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
