<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Questions With Alessandro Nivola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- First, there's the name.  
</P>
<P>
	Alessandro Nivola.  
</P>
<P>
	``My name has been a real source of confusion to just about  
everyone,'' the 27-year-old actor said. ``The first roles I was 
always called in for were bricklayers. And now since I've done so 
much work in England, people are confused about my nationality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the record, his father is from the Italian island of  
Sardinia, where Alessandro is as common as John in the United 
States. And Nivola is a traditional name. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just one more thing to make it more difficult for people  
to categorize what kind of person I am,'' the handsome, clean-cut 
actor said. ``It keeps more possibilities open for different types 
of work -- I look so Waspy but I speak Italian.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Second, how much pressure did he feel when he shared the stage  
this summer with Gwyneth Paltrow? He appeared with Paltrow in 
Shakespeare's ``As You Like It'' at the Williamstown Theater 
Festival in Williamstown, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a real scene up there especially because Gwyneth was in  
the show,'' Nivola said. ``We had (Steven) Spielberg showing up. 
One day, I think Kevin Kline, Paul Newman, Joanne Woodward and Mia 
Farrow all came to the show. Every day there was such pressure on, 
but I don't think anyone had as much pressure as she did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four years ago, Nivola was ``discovered'' while doing ``A Month  
in the Country'' with Helen Mirren and F. Murray Abraham on 
Broadway. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coming back to the theater in Williamstown, I suddenly  
realized that I'm not the new guy anymore. There were young interns 
and non-equity actors there who were asking me about my career,'' 
he said. ``I was always `the kid.' People always treated me like 
the young guy who was open, openhearted and open for information 
and wanting to learn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nivola's upcoming films include ``Best Laid Plans,'' co-starring  
Reese Witherspoon and Josh Brolin; Kenneth Branagh's film version 
of Shakespeare's ``Love's Labours Lost''; and ``Mansfield Park,'' 
an adaptation of a Jane Austen novel. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mansfield Park'' and the Branagh film were shot in England.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'd always wanted to travel the world and I've really been  
fortunate that way. I've worked all over Europe, and I never 
expected to do it as much I have,'' he said. ``However, now I feel 
just a little bit tired by it and I would like to work in L.A., or 
New York, or around the corner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Best Laid Plans,'' Nivola plays a frustrated worker at a  
recycling plant who drags his girlfriend (Witherspoon) and an old 
buddy (Brolin) into a web of crime and deception. 
</P>
<P>
	Nivola doesn't seem a likely candidate for the part of a  
scheming thief. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a certain thrill to be able to convince people that  
I was capable of that kind of bad behavior,'' Nivola said during an 
interview at a Manhattan hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	1. Growing up you lived throughout the Northeast, where is home  
for you now? 
</P>
<P>
	Nivola: `Where is home?' is a very confusing question. I have a  
little place in L.A. that I rented when I went out to do 
`Face/Off.' I got evicted from my place in New York so I got kind 
of stuck out there. Since then I've done three of my last four 
films in England, so I've spent a lot of time in London. I just 
come and go to L.A. I get my mail there. 
</P>
<P>
	2. What do you do when you're not working?  
</P>
<P>
	Nivola: My whole life over the past few years has been consumed  
with being an actor, which is what I always wanted to do so that's 
good. But it hasn't left a lot of time for anything else. I play 
soccer obsessively. There's this group of middle-aged Italian guys 
who play out in L.A. -- they have uniforms and everything. I go out 
and play with them on weekends. I also love to read. 
</P>
<P>
	3. Are you a Shakespeare buff?  
</P>
<P>
	Nivola: The plays are just brilliant -- there is great language  
and great dialogue. And the plays are so modern. The language is 
difficult, but the themes and what people are really saying is 
always just so timely. You wouldn't believe some of the lines -- you 
are just shocked and you think `Is that really an Elizabethan 
line?' You think this is just so understandable. 
</P>
<P>
	4. Were you nervous about returning to the stage this summer?  
</P>
<P>
	Nivola: It had been four years since I'd done a play, and for  
Gwyneth it was five or six. It's completely different doing a play. 
The stage is more demanding, you have to get into shape for it -- 
especially your voice. But it is incredibly rewarding. 
</P>
<P>
	5. Do you feel like you are making a name for yourself?  
</P>
<P>
	Nivola: In the first few years I was in New York, I probably  
worked harder at being an actor than I ever have and probably ever 
will again -- hopefully. It was a constant thing of trying to get 
work and then be good at it. Now, luckily, the main part of the 
work is doing the work, not getting it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
