<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles Shake Up Offensive Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Eagles made more changes to  
their ineffective offensive line Wednesday, promoting veteran Jeff 
Dellenbach to the starting lineup and moving Jermane Mayberry yet 
again, this time from guard to tackle. 
</P>
<P>
	In what seems like a weekly rite of passage since late in  
training camp, there were two new teammates to introduce: guard 
David Diaz-Infante and tight end Justin Swift, both signed Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest moves, including the release of lineman John Michels,  
were part of coach Andy Reid's steadfast effort to jumpstart his 
sputtering offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're either going to hop on the bus or you're not going to  
hop on the bus,'' Reid said Wednesday. ``And if you're not, then 
you're not going to hang with this group here. I'm going full-steam 
ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The message is clear.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't get the job done, you're gone,'' rookie guard  
Doug Brzezinski said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dellenbach, a 15-year veteran signed a week ago, will start at  
right guard Sunday against Tampa Bay. Mayberry, who has been moved 
several times since training camp, goes to right tackle to replace 
rookie John Welbourn, who is out for the year following knee 
surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Diaz-Infante, who won two Super Bowls with Denver before being  
released last week, essentially replaces Michels in the rotation. 
Oliver Ross was promoted from the practice squad to back up 
Mayberry. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade of defensive end Jon Harris to Green Bay for Michels  
looks a little strange now. Reid said Diaz-Infante, who was 
available when the Eagles acquired Michels, is an ``upgrade'' over 
Michels. So why was Michels acquired in the first place? 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to evaluate John in here as a player after his knee  
surgery,'' Reid said. ``I felt that John could be a starter for me 
if I needed one. I didn't necessarily feel that way after the 
surgery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reid, who set the tone for a no-nonsense approach by cutting  
veterans Jerry Crafts and George Hegamin late in camp, stopped 
short of saying the line is set. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is how I'd like it right here, if it works,'' Reid said.  
``Again, I'm going to keep a close eye on that position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It hasn't been easy to miss. The Eagles (0-1), coming off a  
demoralizing 25-24 loss to Arizona in the season opener, have been 
hampered by an ineffective offense in five games including the 
preseason. 
</P>
<P>
	They took a 21-0 lead in the first quarter against the  
Cardinals, courtesy of three turnovers that gave them the ball 
inside the 20. They couldn't move the ball the rest of the game and 
lost on Chris Jacke's 31-yard field goal as time expired. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 15:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Lower; Dow Falls 108.91 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors brushed off a government report that  
showed little evidence of rising inflation and drove stocks lower 
Wednesday. The dollar's weakness against the Japanese yen continued 
to undercut stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 108.91 points, or by 1  
percent, to close at 10,801.42. The index had tumbled from an early 
gain of 103 points, with the selloff gaining momentum in the final 
hour of trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also closed lower. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 fell 18.32 to 1,317.97. The technology-heavy Nasdaq 
composite index fell 54.12 to 2,814.17, more than reversing 
Tuesday's gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite the fact that we're still hitting new records with  
some regularity, the broad market is not participating,'' said 
Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; 
Co. in Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department's report of a modest increase in its  
Consumer Price Index -- the most closely watched inflation gauge -- 
initially pushed stocks higher Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The index rose 0.3 percent in August, matching the July advance.  
Excluding large gains in the gasoline and energy categories, prices 
rose a mere 0.1 percent in August, well below what Wall Street 
economists had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``With only one sector showing a noticeable shift in price, the  
CPI has to be viewed as a fine report on inflation,'' said Michael 
Moran, chief economist at Daiwa Securities America Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was not enough to convince investors that the Fed will  
hold off on raising interest rates for the third time this year as 
it tries to prevent inflation from escalating. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors believe we've lost the wind at our backs in terms of  
low inflation and low interest rates,'' said Lynn Yturri, who runs 
the One Group Equity Income Fund for Banc One Investment Advisors. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's continued weakness in the dollar also drove the  
market lower. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York Wednesday afternoon, the dollar bought 104.23 yen,  
down from 105.79 yen late Tuesday. At one point earlier in the day, 
the dollar dropped to 103.20 yen, the lowest level against the 
Japanese currency since early 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors fear a weaker dollar because it makes imports more  
expensive, setting the stage for a rise in inflation. It can also 
lead foreign investors to pull out of U.S. stocks to seek more 
attractive returns elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	The inflation-sensitive bond market swung sharply, with yields  
on 30-year Treasury bonds dropping to 6.08 percent after the 
release of the consumer price report, then shooting as high as 
Tuesday's late rate of 6.12 percent. Yields were 6.10 percent as 
stock markets closed for the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Oracle fell 2 13/16 to 42 5/8 after the company's fiscal  
first-quarter earnings, reported after markets closed Tuesday, 
failed to meet the most optimistic predictions of Wall Street 
analysts. Oracle earned 16 cents per share, in line with published 
estimates, but short of the ``whisper'' number, an unofficial 
forecast circulated among Wall Street traders. 
</P>
<P>
	A $10.66 billion merger inspired little enthusiasm on Wall  
Street. Cell phone maker Motorola fell 6 11/16 to 86 1/2 after saying 
it will acquire General Instrument, the leading maker of cable TV 
set-top boxes. Shares of General Instrument declined 3 29/128 to 47 
35/128. 
</P>
<P>
	Belski said the Nasdaq's decline was to be expected after the  
index bounded to a new closing high of 2,887.06 last Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``A limited number of technology stocks have led the Nasdaq  
higher,'' he said. Some of the leading technology shares already 
have risen so far that ``they are prone to pullbacks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft fell 2 1/2 to 92 9/16 and Sun Microsystems dropped 3 to  
82 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts attributed the late slide in stocks to selling in  
advance of Friday's quarterly ``triple witching'' day, when options 
and futures on stocks and stock indexes expire. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 929.15 million 
shares, compared with 881.27 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.91 to 436.33.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Germany's DAX index fell 0.3 percent, Britain's FT-SE  
100 lost 0.8 percent, and France's CAC-40 lost 0.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets in Japan were closed for a national holiday.  





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
