<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corcoran Art School Makes Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One of the oldest U.S. schools of visual  
design, the Corcoran School of Art, said Tuesday it was changing 
its name and adding new degree programs, equipment and buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Corcoran College of Art and Design has opened a ``Georgetown  
campus'' in an old elementary school in an upscale neighborhood of 
the nation's capital. The facility was bought from the District of 
Columbia for $1.5 million and is part of a $3.5 million renovation. 
</P>
<P>
	By 2004, the college expects to have a new building adjacent to  
its current site near the White House. Frank Gehry, architect of 
the new Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, Spain, recently won a contest 
to plan the addition. 
</P>
<P>
	In 2001, the college expects to grant its first associate  
degrees in fine arts and photography. In 2003, it will graduate its 
first bachelor's degrees in photojournalism, and in 2004 its first 
in arts education. The school already offers bachelor's degrees in 
fine arts, graphic design and photography. 
</P>
<P>
	The Corcoran School of Design was founded in 1890. That was 20  
years after the Corcoran Gallery of Art was established as the 
capital's first art museum by William Wilson Corcoran, a financier 
and collector. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
