<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 15:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Starts Olympics Countdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- When Sydney was awarded the 2000  
Olympics six years ago, Helen Russell was among the thousands 
celebrating downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, she was back for more -- this time, one year away  
from the Sept. 15, 2000, opening ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will help make people more aware that this is approaching  
and to get ready,'' the 34-year-old Russell said as she collected 
commemorative pins during celebrations at Darling Harbour. ``It 
seemed such a long way away six years ago when we were standing 
outside the Opera House screaming at 3 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a wake-up call to the city.''  
</P>
<P>
	``Australians like a party,'' she said. ``I think Sydney is  
about the greatest place on Earth to live and I think the rest of 
the world can come and see what a great place this is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Darling Harbour will be the site of Olympic volleyball,  
weightlifting, boxing, wrestling, fencing and judo. For 16 hours, 
crowds watched sports demonstrations and mingled athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Spectators in Sydney roared while watching a live broadcast of a  
ceremony from Lausanne, Switzerland, where -- to a fanfare of 
Aboriginal music -- the International Olympic Committee celebrated 
the one-year countdown by sending out the first invitations to the 
world's athletes. More than 10,000 athletes are expected to take 
part in the Sept. 15-Oct. 1 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Olympic Movement is full of confidence in the capacity of  
the organizing committee to hold a successful games next year,'' 
IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch said. ``I am convinced the 
games of the 27th Olympiad will be a great success for the 
athletes, for Australia and for the Olympic Movement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, U.S. Olympic hopefuls gathered outside the studios  
of NBC, which will televise the games. Among them were softball 
pitcher Dot Richardson, high jumper Amy Acuff and pole vaulter 
Stacy Dragila. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, meanwhile, the track and field competition schedule  
was announced and Michael Johnson learned he will get a chance to 
replicate his historic sprint double of 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Amateur Athletic Federation, the sport's  
governing body, arranged the schedule specifically so top stars 
could compete in more than one event. 
</P>
<P>
	IAAF spokesman Giorgio Reineri said particular attention was  
given to accommodating Johnson and Marion Jones, the sport's top 
female star who will have the opportunity to bid for gold in the 
100, 200, long jump and both relays. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who set a world record of 19.32 seconds in the 200 in  
Atlanta, struggled with injuries and other setbacks for much of the 
next three years. But he reasserted his greatness at last month's 
World Championships in Seville, Spain, breaking the 11-year-old 
world record in the 400 with a clocking of 43.18. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm certainly pleased that the schedule will allow me to do  
the double again,'' Johnson said. ``It's an extremely difficult 
thing to do, but it's not uncharted territory anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm running faster now than I was at the Olympics three years  
ago,'' Johnson said. ``I don't think there's anyone who can beat me 
if I'm on top of my game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The timetable also clears the way for doubles by American  
sprinter Maurice Greene, the world champion in the 100 and 200; 
Ethiopia's Haile Gebrselassie, world and Olympic champion at 10,000 
and world record-holder at 5,000; and Russia's Svetlana Masterkova, 
the 1996 Olympic champion in the 800 and 1,500. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sydney schedule includes a rest day between the  
qualification rounds and finals of the triple jump, as well as 
other jumping events. The timetable also allows at least one rest 
day between semifinals and finals of races of 800 meters and more, 
and the 400 meter hurdles. 
</P>
<P>
	In Australia's capital of Canberra, a meeting of 60 indigenous  
leaders convened by the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander 
Commission decided not to jeopardize the success of the games 
through protests. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, because we're a sport-loving people ourselves, we  
want to be at the games, we want a successful games, we want to see 
Cathy Freeman reach her full potential and get gold,'' former ATSIC 
chairwoman Lowitja O'Donoghue said, referring to the Aboriginal 
track star. 
</P>
<P>
	Council for Aboriginal Reconciliation chairwoman Evelyn Scott  
said the success of Australian athletes was paramount. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not about to jeopardize the livelihood of our Australian  
athletes be they indigenous or non-indigenous,'' she said. 
``They've worked all their lives for this, to win gold in their own 
country.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
