<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> KC's Tight End Returns to Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Tight end Tony Gonzalez returned to  
practice for the first time in three weeks Wednesday, hopeful he'll 
be ready for Kansas City's home opener against Denver on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez, one of the most important elements in the Chiefs'  
offensive plans, had been out since injuring his right knee in an 
exhibition game against Jacksonville on Aug. 26. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went out and practiced today and felt pretty good,'' said  
the 6-foot-4, 250-pounder. ``It was a little gimpy on the corner, 
when I was turning. I took myself out toward the end of practice, 
about the last 10 plays. A little sore. I didn't want to push it on 
the first day of practice. I just want to take care of it until 
Sunday and then let it go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez' absence was sorely felt in Sunday's season opener at  
Chicago, where the Chiefs lost 20-17 to a team they were favored to 
beat. The decision not to play him was not made until just before 
game time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just sitting there and watching was the worst,'' he said.  
``The doctor said don't go with it. But it just killed me sitting 
there, just watching, especially when you know you can help your 
team out. It was tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Gonzalez is ready, he'll give quarterback Elvis Grbac another  
option. 
</P>
<P>
	``He makes a tremendous amount of difference,'' Denver safety  
Tyrone Braxton said. ``Elvis looks to him more. He's a good 
blocker, a physical blocker. He helps out their offense 
tremendously. I remember Elvis last year would look to him in 
crucial situations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A first-round pick in 1997, Gonzalez caught 33 passes for 368  
yards and two touchdowns as a rookie. Last year, he had 59 catches 
for 621 yards and two scores and the Chiefs are hoping he'll reach 
stardom. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tony's a playmaker. Each team has a certain amount of  
playmakers and you need them out there all the time,'' center Tim 
Grunhard said. ``We missed him last week. There are big plays he 
could have made. I'm hoping he can be out there this week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Chiefs are also hoping to get defensive lineman Dan Williams  
back. Williams, who sat out last season in a contract dispute, has 
missed the past five weeks with a knee injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm basically just trying to come out here and do more and  
more each day and see how it holds up,'' said Williams, who led the 
Chiefs with 10 sacks in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm basically just trying to get back to a functional point. I  
feel I am back to a functional point. That being said, I've just 
got to come out and do the best I can.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 22:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska Looks for Balancing Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Alaska's political leaders on Wednesday  
began the search for a way to balance the budget without reducing 
the the annual dividend people get from the state's permanent fund, 
a proposal voters rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	A plan to fill the gap between state spending and normal revenue  
with earnings from the $26 billion oil-royalty savings account went 
down in defeat Tuesday, with 83 percent voting no in an advisory 
election. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund's treasured dividend would have been cut several  
hundred dollars to about $1,340 in 2001. Alaskans expect to receive 
more than $1,700 when the checks go out next month. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we got was a 2-by-4 upside the head,'' Republican state  
Sen. Gary Wilken said Wednesday. ``Now we just have to decide what 
it means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition to the plan devised by the Republican-controlled  
Legislature and endorsed by Democratic Gov. Tony Knowles came from 
a mismatched coalition of hard-line conservatives and liberal 
environmentalists. 
</P>
<P>
	The conservatives want deep spending cuts before tapping the  
fund or changing Alaska's status as only one of two states with 
neither an income tax nor a general sales tax. Taxes and royalties 
on oil production cover most of the cost of state government, but 
dwindling oil revenue has prompted budget cuts in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to discuss reprioritizing what we do as a state and  
stop doing some things we can'tafford anymore,'' said Republican 
Rep. Scott Ogan, who opposed the plan in the Legislature and headed 
a group that campaigned for a no vote in the election. 
</P>
<P>
	The liberal end of the coalition argued for more taxes on  
Alaska's profitable industries, including oil and tourism. 
</P>
<P>
	``Alaskans have said loud and clear they want this Legislature  
to consider all potential revenue sources, including increased 
industry taxes, when they go to balance the budget next year,'' 
said Paula Phillips, a spokeswoman for Alaska Conservation Voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with many lawmakers, Knowles interpreted the vote as a  
call for a financial plan that relies less heavily on earnings from 
the fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``There needs to be other more fair and balanced sources of  
revenues,'' Knowles said. ``I don't know whether its going to be an 
income tax, a sales tax or some kind of a broad-based tax.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state now balances the budget by tapping a reserve account  
that now contains less than $3 billion. Without some new source of 
money, officials worry that reserve could be empty within a few 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Knowles offered no specifics, but said he hoped to have a new  
proposal ready by the time he gives his State of the State speech 
in January. He opened this year's session by proposing an income 
tax that GOP lawmakers summarily dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	An avid booster of the oil industry, Knowles seemed dubious  
about the idea of raising oil taxes. Such a move could make the 
state less attractive to developers, driving away investment and 
jobs, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 14:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise on Tame Inflation Report / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose Wednesday after a government  
report showed inflation remaining tame. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 9/32  
point, or $2.81 1/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, fell to 6.10 percent from Tuesday's 6.12 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said the consumer price index rose 0.3  
percent in August, in line with economists' expectations and 
matching July's increase. The core reading of consumer prices, 
which excludes volatile food and energy costs, rose 0.1 percent, 
lower than forecasts for a 0.2 percent gain. 
</P>
<P>
	The low inflation rate seemingly lessens the chance that the  
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates for a third time this 
year at its meeting Oct. 5. Bonds, which pay a fixed rate of return 
to investors, are less attractive during periods of rising interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of short-term Treasury securities rose 2/32 point to 3/32  
point, and intermediate maturities rose 7/32 point to 9/32, 
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.73 percent as the  
discount fell 0.07 percentage point from Tuesday to 4.61 percent. 
Six-month yields were 5.07 percent, as the discount fell 0.04 
percentage point from Tuesday to 4.87 percent. One-year yields were 
5.23 percent as the discount fell by 0.03 percentage point from 
late Tuesday to 4.96 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.43 3/4 percent from Tuesday's 5.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds was unchanged at 113 1/8. The average yield to 
maturity was unchanged at 5.86 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 13:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tim Couch To Start for Browns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEREA, Ohio (AP) -- The Tim Couch Era has arrived in Cleveland  
much sooner than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch, the No. 1 pick in the draft, will replace Ty Detmer as  
Cleveland's starting quarterback Sunday when the expansion Browns 
play at Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland was rocked 43-0 in its opener by the Pittsburgh  
Steelers. The Browns gained just 40 total yards and made only two 
first downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Browns coach Chris Palmer made the switch because he thinks  
Detmer would be better coming off the bench if Couch gets in 
trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not disappointed in Ty,'' Palmer said today. ``It wasn't  
all his fault. I'd like to think Ty would be able to a better job 
as a reliever than Tim as a reliever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer said Couch, who threw an interception on his first  
passing attempt Sunday night, could be the starter for the rest of 
the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch skipped his final season at Kentucky and signed a $48  
million contract with the Browns. He was impressive during 
preseason, completing 10 straight passes and throwing a touchdown 
pass to rally Cleveland past Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	But he looked shaky in his final few performances, and the  
Browns wanted to bring him along slowly this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really looking forward to the opportunity,'' Couch said.  
``Hopefully, I can go out and move the chains and put some points 
on the board.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
