<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Concern Over Small Firefighter Pool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When a lightning storm sparked a swarm of  
small fires in northern California's Plumas National Forest last 
month, officials had no choice but to let some of them burn. 
</P>
<P>
	``We definitely didn't have the staffing we needed,'' said Kent  
Swartzlander, who oversees federal fire crews in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had to let nine fires go on our district. We knew they were  
there, but we just didn't have the people to fight them,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Days later, when enough fire crews had been brought in from  
other state, local and federal departments, two of those nine fires 
had merged to become a major blaze covering thousands of acres, 
Swartzlander said. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke Tuesday at a House hearing on what federal officials  
say is one of the major impediments to fighting Western wildfires: 
a shrinking pool of firefighters and managers to actually battle 
the forest-eating flames. 
</P>
<P>
	This year has been particularly bad for wildfires, with 4.4  
million acres burned through August -- more than twice the total for 
an average year. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal agencies that manage most of those burning  
landscapes have fewer people and resources to fight those fires, 
according to a report last month from Congress' General Accounting 
Office. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of qualified federal wildland firefighter teams has  
dropped by more than one-third since 1992 as firefighters retire or 
leave for higher-paying jobs with other fire departments, the study 
said. Congress has given federal land-management agencies only 
about 85 percent of the firefighting money they need for the past 
three years, the GAO report said. 
</P>
<P>
	That puts forests, grasslands, homes and other firefighters at  
risk from monster blazes fueled by vegetation that grew during 
decades of fire suppression, officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to get on the fires as quickly and contain  
them when they're small,'' said Rep. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho. 
</P>
<P>
	Chenoweth is backing a bill sponsored by Rep. Richard Pombo,  
R-Calif., that would raise wages and other benefits for federal 
firefighters. Swartzlander, president of a federal firefighters' 
group, and others have complained that federal firefighters often 
get paid much less than their local counterparts when fighting the 
same fire. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
