<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola To Buy General Instrument </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Motorola Inc. made a bold bet today on the  
future of cable television, announcing it will pay about $11 
billion in stock to acquire General Instrument Corp., the largest 
producer of cable TV set-top boxes. 
</P>
<P>
	General Instrument's set-top box operations dominate one of the  
key technologies that is revolutionizing home entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	With the new equipment available today, the televisions of  
tomorrow can offer many more ``broadband'' cable services, 
including Internet access, interactive video games and telephone 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola, best known for making cellular phones and pagers, is  
looking for a stronger presence in the fast-growing market for 
broadband services. 
</P>
<P>
	General Instrument is the market leader in set-top boxes,  
controlling 72 percent of the North American market, according to 
Allied Business Intelligence Inc., a technology research company. 
Allied estimates the number of set-top boxes in North American 
homes is expected to skyrocket from about 20 million today to 113 
million over the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	But the strongest demand is expected to come from overseas  
markets and ``will be the key to our growth and our business,'' 
said Edward D. Breen, chairman and chief executive officer of 
General Instrument, who will head Motorola's new broadband 
division. 
</P>
<P>
	``This allows us to participate in the fastest-growing segments  
of the telecommunications industry,'' said Christopher B. Galvin, 
the chairman and chief executive of Schaumburg, Ill.-based 
Motorola. 
</P>
<P>
	For General Instrument, a deal with Motorola will mean more  
marketing power, better supply contracts and a broader product 
line. 
</P>
<P>
	Galvin said he does not anticipate a large number of job cuts in  
the combination. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal announced today, Motorola will offer 0.575 share  
of its stock for each of General Instrument's shares. That would 
represent a value of about $11 billion at Tuesday's closing prices. 
</P>
<P>
	But investors in both companies seemed to have concerns about  
the terms. Many shareholders in Horsham, Pa.-based General 
Instrument don't think they are getting enough money, while 
Motorola shareholders are worried the dilution to the value of 
their stock. 
</P>
<P>
	In morning trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Motorola fell  
6 percent or by $5.75, to $87.43 3/4 a share, while General 
Instrument's stock was off about 5 percent, or by $2.68 3/4, at 
$47.81 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Breen defended the price General Instrument shareholders are  
getting, claiming it represents a premium to where the stock was 
trading just a few weeks ago before speculation of a deal pushed 
shares higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the most strategic move our company has ever made,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The boards of both companies have approved the deal, which is  
subject to approval by shareholders and antitrust regulators. It is 
expected to be completed early next year, the companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's announcement could put pressure on other cable equipment  
companies to find partners. Scientific-Atlanta Inc., the No. 2 
maker of set-top boxes, has seen its stock climb this week as 
investors bet the company will be the next target. 
</P>
<P>
	The consolidation among these companies reflects the merger  
frenzy among the nation's cable TV operators. AT&AMP;T Corp., Cox 
Communications Inc., and Charter Communications Holdings LLC are 
among the cable firms that have announced major acquisitions in the 
past six months. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
