<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Utility Vows Improvements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Commonwealth Edison has promised to spend $1.5  
billion improving its service after summer power outages shut down 
the Chicago Board of Trade and left thousands of people without 
electricity during a heat wave. 
</P>
<P>
	An internal review and a separate improvement plan sent to Mayor  
Richard M. Daley and the Illinois Commerce Commission by 
Commonwealth Edison's parent company, Unicom Corp., blamed many of 
the outages on company blunders. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation found an inflexible system that didn't allow  
the company to easily switch power among substations, said David 
Helwig, interim senior vice president of the utility's transmission 
and distribution operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Unicom promised more aggressive inspection and maintenance,  
better monitoring of equipment, additional capacity in key 
locations and improved system flexibility. The plan includes $1.5 
billion in improvements to its distribution system over the next 
two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The company serves about 3.4 million customers in the Chicago  
area. 
</P>
<P>
	The troubles started July 30 with a blackout that left about  
100,000 customers without power for up to three days in 
temperatures of more than 100 degrees. Several outages followed, 
including one Aug. 12 when problems at a substation forced a 
shutoff of power to Chicago's busiest business district, and 
mechanical problems Aug. 22 that caused a blackout that threatened 
to spoil frozen plant and animal tissue in the Field Museum of 
Natural History. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
