<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greene Wins 100-Meter Race in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Already the world's fastest human, Maurice Greene  
is setting his sights on another title. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, the world-record holder in the 100 meters and winner of  
three gold medals at the World Championships, won the event 
Wednesday at the Super Track and Field meet. 
</P>
<P>
	``My main focus is to win the Olympic gold,'' said Greene, who  
edged fellow American Curtis Johnson in 10.35 seconds. Greene said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That comes first, not a record. Right now, I have a goal of  
9.76 and the coach said I am capable of running faster, but I take 
small steps at a time. The most important is to win the Olympic 
gold. That's something I haven't done and I want to do.'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	With his season over, Greene plans to return home to rest and  
visit his grandmother in Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am happy I had a very good year,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	To say the least. He kept the world record with a time of 9.79  
seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a dream come true,'' he said of being the world's  
fastest runner. ``Now I can say I was a No. 1 once. Records are 
made to be broken and anything can happen in a 100-meter. I am 
thankful and try to be the best. I believe I am the best and as 
long as I keep believing in myself, I can improve myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 100-meter hurdles, American Larry Wade edged world-record  
holder Colin Jackson with a time of 13.50 seconds. Jackson placed 
second in 13.55 seconds, with Japan's Satoru Mizuno third in 13.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazuhiko Yamazaki of Japan won the 400-meter hurdles in 48.98  
seconds, followed by Joey Woody, who finished second in 49.16. 
Torrence Zellener of the Unites States was third. 
</P>
<P>
	Bulgaria's Petya Pendareva swept the 100- and 200-meter races.  
Pendareva took the 200 in 23.27, before winning the 100 in 11.36 
seconds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
