<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 23:10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Will Fight Pale in Comparison? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- The Oscar De La Hoya-Felix Trinidad  
welterweight showdown will be the biggest grossing non-heavyweight 
fight in history. 
</P>
<P>
	Money talks, of course, but it doesn't always tell the entire  
story. 
</P>
<P>
	As an event, the modestly billed ``Fight of The Millennium,''  
doesn't match some fights involving the Fabulous Four of the 1980's 
-- Leonard, Hearns, Hagler and Duran. At least going in. 
</P>
<P>
	When any combination of the Fab Four got together, the public  
paid attention. De La Hoya-Trinidad has certainly attracted 
attention, but there doesn't seem to be the electricity generated 
by such fights as Sugar Ray Leonard vs. Roberto Duran on June 20, 
1980 at Montreal and Leonard vs. Thomas Hearns on Sept. 16, 1981, 
at Caesars Palace in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, if the current pay-per-view situation existed in the  
1980s, at least three fights would have outgrossed Saturday night's 
match at Mandalay Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	They were the Duran-Leonard, Leonard-Hearns fights and the  
Leonard-Marvelous Marvin Hagler match April 6, 1987 at Caesars 
Palace. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other fights that would have been pay-per-view hits would  
have been the Leonard-Duran rematch Nov. 25, 1980, in the Superdome 
at New Orleans and the Hagler-Hearns bout April 15, 1985, at 
Caesars Palace. 
</P>
<P>
	Pay-per-view has made big fights available to many more people,  
but it also has changed the sport in another way. Fighters, with 
huge purses guaranteed, have become less accessible to the media 
and, through the media, to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	But that's the way of the sports world. Besides, what really  
counts is what happens in the ring, not in a news conference or an 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya (WBC champion) and Trinidad (IBF champion), each 26  
and unbeaten, figure to give the paying public its money's worth. 
They've already earned their money -- De La Hoya is guaranteed $15 
million and Trinidad $10 million -- by selling out the 12,000-seat 
arena at Mandalay Bay and by making the fight what Mark Taffet of 
TVKO said will be one of the five top pay-per-view events ever. 
</P>
<P>
	It might not be as great a fight as the 1981 welterweight title  
match between Leonard and Hearns, to which it is being incessantly 
compared -- but it doesn't have to be in order to be a darn good 
fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonard-Hearns I was such an attraction that it was shown on  
closed-circuit television at 298 sites with 1.5 million seats and 
on pay-per-view in 24 cities, with one million available homes. It 
also was telecast to 50 countries and drew a live crowd of about 
24,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonard made about $13 million and Hearns a little more than $5  
million. Can you imagine what they could make today with 
pay-per-view blanketing the United States?. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a truly great fight, a fight of ebb and flow. Hearns, the  
WBA champion, stalked Leonard for the first five rounds, then was 
badly hurt by the WBC champion in the sixth and seventh rounds. 
With Leonard looking for a knockout, Hearns outboxed him until 
Leonard knocked him down in the 13th round, then stopped him in the 
14th. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a fight that will always be discussed by boxing buffs.  
Hopefully, Saturday night's will be such a fight. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 07:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kennedy Honors Go to Robards, Borge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Actors Sean Connery and Jason Robards will be  
saluted for lifetime achievement at this year's Kennedy Center 
Honors, along with singer-songwriter Stevie Wonder, dancer Judith 
Jamison and pianist-comedian Victor Borge. 
</P>
<P>
	The 22nd annual awards, announced Tuesday, will be presented  
Dec. 4 at a dinner at the State Department. The next day President 
Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton will throw a White House 
reception for the recipients, followed by a gala performance at the 
Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, taped for television 
broadcast later in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Robards, 77, and Connery, 69, are being honored for a wide range  
of acting. Connery, a Scot, first became known for his role during 
three decades as James Bond, Agent 007, in films based on Ian 
Fleming's novels. 
</P>
<P>
	Robards, born in Chicago, has performed in stage dramas from  
Shakespeare to Harold Pinter. He has won two Academy Awards, for 
his portrayals of The Washington Post's Ben Bradlee in 1976's ``All 
the President's Men'' and novelist Dashiell Hammett in ``Julia'' in 
1977. 
</P>
<P>
	Borge, who turned 90 last January, made his debut as Borge  
Rosenbaum, a soloist at 14 with the Philharmonic Orchestra of his 
native Copenhagen. Already celebrated in the Nordic countries for 
his musical humor before he was 30, he fled the Nazi advance with 
his American wife and was soon performing with Ed Sullivan, Rudy 
Vallee and Bing Crosby. 
</P>
<P>
	Wonder, a songwriter and singer, is ``a musical genius who has  
been an integral part of American popular culture for the past four 
decades,'' said James A. Johnson, Kennedy Center chairman. At 49, 
he is the youngest of the five being honored. 
</P>
<P>
	Blind since birth, Wonder signed a contract at 11 in 1963 with  
Motown where as ``Little Stevie Wonder'' he began turning out hit 
records. He was instrumental in the movement to honor the Rev. 
Martin Luther King Jr. with a national holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamison, 56, is a dancer, choreographer and teacher who has led  
the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater since its founder died in 
1989. She was his biggest star for 15 years. Ailey was honored by 
the Kennedy Center in 1988. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
