<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial Roundup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here are excerpts from editorials in newspapers in the United  
States and abroad: 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 11  
</P>
<P>
	The Dominion Post of Morgantown, W.Va., on politics:  
</P>
<P>
	American politics often resembles a Greek tragicomedy -- except  
all that should make us cry has us snickering in disgust, and the 
more we laugh at the absurdity of the body politic, the worse it 
gets. 
</P>
<P>
	From Anywhere, USA, to Washington, D.C., the halls of government  
seem replete with manipulators, liars and thieves running the show. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the Greeks, the bad guys in these power plays aren't the  
ones drinking the poison to illustrate a moral point, though. 
Rather, the condition of American politics is poisoning us all. 
</P>
<P>
	We suffer from growing cynicism and lowest-common-denominator  
expectations for our leaders. We are, in essence, in a general 
state of ennui. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 13  
</P>
<P>
	The Daily Oklahoman, on the Waco investigation:  
</P>
<P>
	Former Sen. John C. Danforth of Missouri is a good choice to run  
a new investigation into allegations of governmental misconduct in 
the 1993 Waco standoff that ended with the fiery deaths of 86 
Branch Davidians, including 24 children. 
</P>
<P>
	The 63-year-old, three-term Republican left Congress in 1996  
with a reputation fairness and compassion, no doubt because of law 
and divinity degrees he earned three decades ago at Yale. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Although Danforth's charge is to investigate official  
misconduct, his overarching mission is to restore public confidence 
in the Justice Department and the FBI, both badly tarnished by the 
Waco siege and fire. ... 
</P>
<P>
	We hope his investigation will settle, as quickly as possible,  
corrosive questions that should've been answered long ago, which 
instead have bred more cynicism about the government's exercise of 
power and authority. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 7  
</P>
<P>
	The News-Journal of Daytona Beach, Fla., on state drug plan:  
</P>
<P>
	Florida wants to do a lot more than ``just say no'' to drugs.  
</P>
<P>
	The ambitious goal of state drug czar James McDonough -- to cut  
drug use in half within five years -- is pure fantasy. But his plan 
for a balanced attack that emphasizes education and treatment over 
punishment is a long way from the state's earlier chaotic anti-drug 
tactics. ... 
</P>
<P>
	There's a lot to like in this half-billion dollar plan. ...  
</P>
<P>
	The main challenge with this plan may be keeping the emphasis on  
education and treatment. The Legislature has a long-term addiction 
to harsh punishment instead of rehabilitation for everything from 
youthful crimes to sexual offenders. If Gov. Jeb Bush and McDonough 
can keep the Legislature focused on education and treatment, they 
may be able to turn the corner on the state's surging drug problem. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 9  
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle Times, on PTSA for gays:  
</P>
<P>
	Inspiration for the PTA arose from a conference for married  
mothers in 1897. It took only two years for the women to realize 
they should make fathers feel welcome, too. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a century later, one particular group of people still  
feels profoundly unwelcome at school: parents or students who are 
gay or lesbians, or parents whose teenagers are gay or lesbian. The 
state Parent-Teacher Association will put Washington on the map 
when it formally approves what appears to be a first in the nation, 
the Gay Lesbian PTSA of Greater Puget Sound. ... 
</P>
<P>
	If it becomes a politically charged advocacy group, the Gay and  
Lesbian PTSA of Greater Puget Sound could polarize schools more 
than unify them. But if does what it intends -- provide support -- it 
will help children and their families bring strength to their 
schools. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 8  
</P>
<P>
	The Advocate of Baton Rouge, La., on secrecy in government:  
</P>
<P>
	The culture of secrecy is alive and well on Capitol Hill. ...  
</P>
<P>
	The agencies that generated mountains of classified documents  
over the last 50 years have been ordered to declassify many of the 
documents for access by citizens. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Some senators are pressing the White House to require that all  
the material declassified so far be re-examined to make sure that 
sensitive details about the U.S. nuclear arsenal don't slip out. 
...
</P>
<P>
	No one is in favor of giving away nuclear weapons files .... But  
the lesson of declassification in the 1990s is that those sensitive 
files aren't being declassified. ... 
</P>
<P>
	We hope that the anti-disclosure provisions are removed from the  
defense bill before it becomes law. It is overkill, and will set 
back ... access to knowledge about government activities. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 11.  
</P>
<P>
	The State of Columbia, S.C., on peace in the Balkans:  
</P>
<P>
	Although we can give thanks for NATO bombing that stopped Serb  
massacres in Kosovo, one thing seems sadly clear: There won't be 
any quick fix to the blood feud between Serbs and Kosovars. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Not only do many members of these two ethnic groups despise each  
other, Serbs as a group show little remorse over their Nazi-like 
actions upon an entire class of citizens. ... That's the 
pessimistic and, we suspect, accurate portrayal of Serb society 
given by Blaine Harden, a journalist with extensive experience in 
the Balkans, in a recent issue of The New York Times magazine. ... 
</P>
<P>
	One of the few repentant Serbs who talked to Harden explained  
why many of her countrymen still deny Serb atrocities in Kosovo: . 
...
</P>
<P>
	``For them, Albanians are not really human beings. The Serbs  
believe they are the chosen people. It is racism. I hate to say it, 
but it is like what the Germans did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Serbs are not the only culprits. Many Kosovars too, judging from  
recent clashes in Kosovo with Serbs, are showing the same sort of 
blind hatred toward their neighbors. It all means this is one 
trouble spot that will be with us for years to come. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 9  
</P>
<P>
	Akron (Ohio) Beacon Journal, on death of Allen Funt:  
</P>
<P>
	In 1947, when Allen Funt hid his first microphone (then movie  
camera), he found a way to introduce Americans to each other in a 
way we found embarrassing and captivitating. That he also made it 
hilarious accounts for the longevity of ``Candid Camera'' and the 
multiplicity of its seemingly endless knock-offs. 
</P>
<P>
	Funt, who died (Sept. 5) at age 84, understood that a spoonful  
of giggles makes almost anything easier to take. 
</P>
<P>
	Funt's puckish sense of humor and keen eye brought us closer to  
each other. He taught us all to say, ``Smile! You're on Candid 
Camera.'' Best, he helped us all to see that, no matter how serious 
life can seem, it's often best when the joke is on us. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 13  
</P>
<P>
	St. Petersburg (Fla.) Times, on the Clinton's new home:  
</P>
<P>
	Imagine you owe millions of dollars in legal bills and don't  
have the assets to even make a good start at paying off your debts. 
Your current job pays well -- $200,000 a year -- but you know you're 
going to lose it, along with the federally subsidized housing that 
comes with it, in little more than a year. Your wife has no paying 
job and is no sure thing to win the position she is currently 
seeking. 
</P>
<P>
	What do you do?  
</P>
<P>
	Well, if you're Bill and Hillary Clinton, you buy a $1.7-million  
house. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry McAuliffe, a longtime Friend of Bill, has become a  
Financier of Bill, guaranteeing the $1.35-million home loan the 
Clintons otherwise would have had no chance of qualifying for. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Not just any home would meet Mrs. Clinton's political needs as  
she seeks to establish residency in New York and burnish her Senate 
credentials. ... 
</P>
<P>
	A first family with a steadier moral compass would behave as  
most ordinary citizens do: Buy only as much house as they can 
afford, and avoid any sweetheart deals from friends that might one 
day want special favors in return. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 14  
</P>
<P>
	The Sun of London, on the woman who spied against Britain:  
</P>
<P>
	Melita Norwood was ... was giving nuclear secrets to the enemy.  
And she shows no remorse for her actions. She must be prosecuted. 
So we welcome Home Secretary Jack Straw's new inquiry into the case 
-- as a start. 
</P>
<P>
	Ministers, MPs and the public have been left out in the cold too  
long. ... Even the prime minister, the man with ultimate 
responsibility for the defense of the realm, knew nothing of this 
case until last week. 
</P>
<P>
	That is scandalous. MI5 try to cover their murky tracks with  
talk of confusing the Soviets, unmasking other spies. ... But how 
come the BBC can make a program using files not shown to the prime 
minister and the home secretary?'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 13  
</P>
<P>
	Le Matin of Lausanne, Switzerland, on German politics:  
</P>
<P>
	Gerhard Schroeder is clocking up the electoral defeats. Last  
week it was Saarland and Brandenburg. (This week) it was 
Rhineland-Westphalia and Thuringia, a region of the former East 
Germany where the former communists even managed to dethrone 
Schroeder's own party as the second force. ... 
</P>
<P>
	A year after his outstanding victory, the chancellor has lost  
his credibility, and he will have trouble getting approval for the 
austerity program he announced without warning at the beginning of 
the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	In spite of the electoral fiascos, Schroeder wants to hold his  
course. ... But to get the bitter pill swallowed, he has to 
negotiate with the opposition Christian Democrats, whom he can no 
longer do without. ... He must also convince his own social 
democratic friends, who are publicly opposing his liberal 
``English-style'' policies. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 13  
</P>
<P>
	Frankfurter Rundschau of Germany, on Clinton-Jiang meeting:  
</P>
<P>
	U.S. President Bill Clinton and China's national leader Jiang  
Zemin have negotiated a compromise on neutral territory in 
Auckland. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton moved toward his Chinese colleague on the question of  
Taiwan. The United States would not change its position that there 
is only one China. What appears to be only continuity, is a 
disguised signal to the politicians in Taipei, the definition of 
one statehood closely followed by a one-sided declaration of 
independence. That Beijing threatens to use weapons in such a case 
has more or less a ritual character, as does Washington's warnings 
of a Taiwan war. 
</P>
<P>
	With his political dealing Jiang Zemin, so-to-say, was handed  
some hard cash. The conservatives who wanted to use the WTO theme 
to make the reform Premier Zhu Rongji regret his alleged overdone 
trust in an inconstant Clinton, are now missing a weapon. Zhu can 
negotiate - but Jiang will be watching his every move. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sept. 14  
</P>
<P>
	Corriere della Sera of Milan, Italy, on Russia:  
</P>
<P>
	For many hours after the bomb explosion in Moscow, the city  
looked astounded while sirens howled, traffic lessened, and crowds 
of astonished men and women formed on street corners. 
</P>
<P>
	Boris Yeltsin could, for a moment, behave again like a Czar.  
From television sets he called for the union of all forces and the 
consolidation of power to fight against ``a terrorism that has 
declared war on the Russian population.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He summoned his political opponent (Moscow Mayor Yuri) Luzhkov  
at the Kremlin and talked to him like a president talks to a mayor. 
...
</P>
<P>
	The ``bomb-effect'' is upsetting the political priorities on the  
wave of a sensitive shakeup. 
</P>
<P>
	It is turning public opinion away from the shadow of the  
financial scandals, as well as restoring a role to Yeltsin that 
makes it difficult to put electoral tactics for the upcoming 
elections ahead of the patriotic unity against the massacres. 
  	   	
</P>
