<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Emmy Awards Top Nielsen Ratings / TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The ceremony honoring television's best and  
brightest bombed -- on TV. Fox's telecast of the Emmy Awards drew 
the lowest ratings for television's big night since 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Sunday telecast's estimated 17.4 million viewers was  
easily the most-watched program of the week, a lull before the 
upcoming storm of season premieres. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time a Fox entertainment program has ranked No.  
1 during the week in all of Nielsen Media Research's measurements. 
But the audience was still 1.9 million people smaller than the one 
watching NBC's Emmy telecast last year. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS, led last week by its twin ``60 Minutes'' broadcasts,  
narrowly won the week with a 6.7 rating and 12 share. Fox had a 6.6 
rating and 11 share, and was easily the most popular network among 
the advertiser-prized 18-49 audience. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC was third with a 6.3 rating and 11 share, ABC had a 5.7  
rating and 10 share, and the WB and UPN tied with 2.2 ratings and 4 
shares. Pax TV had a 0.9 rating and 2 share. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox also got a jolt of negative attention from Sen. Joseph  
Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat, and former U.S. Education 
Secretary William Bennett. The two gave Fox its ``Silver Sewer 
Award'' for its ``tireless, tasteless and ongoing efforts to drag 
down network programming standards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two politicians criticized the new Fox series, ``Get Real,''  
for showing a mother finding her teen-aged son in bed with his 
girlfriend. The show premiered last week to lackluster ratings, 
finishing in 50th place for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox issued a statement saying its programs had been rated  
appropriately under the industry's voluntary standards to warn 
viewers of content. The network said it respected viewers' freedom 
to choose their own entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's ``World News Tonight'' and the ``NBC Nightly News'' tied  
for first in the evening news ratings race with 7.0 ratings and 16 
shares. The ``CBS Evening News'' had a 6.0 rating and 13 share. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the 
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of Sept. 6-12, the top 10 shows, their networks and  
ratings were: 
</P>
<P>
	``Emmy Awards,'' Fox, 11.7; ``Dateline NBC-Tuesday,'' NBC, 9.1;  
``60 Minutes II,'' CBS, 8.8; ``60 Minutes,'' CBS, 8.6; ``ER,'' NBC, 
8.5; ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' special, CBS, 8.5; ``Frasier,'' 
NBC, 8.5; ``Friends,'' NBC, 8.3; ``20/20-Friday,'' ABC, 8.0; 
``JAG,'' CBS, 8.0. 






  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 15:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Outer Banks Faced Dennis, Now Floyd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAGS HEAD, N.C. (AP) -- North Carolina's Outer Banks barely had  
time to recover from Hurricane Dennis before Hurricane Floyd forced 
another evacuation. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis blew away sand dunes and chewed up a half-mile of road on  
Hatteras Island before coming ashore as a tropical storm two weeks 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've never really gotten out of the mode from the  
preparations that were in place from Dennis,'' said Dare County 
spokeswoman Dorothy Holt. ``So we're really just sort of moving 
into Floyd from Dennis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the thousands of visitors on the Outer Banks -- a long  
whisker of islands just off the coast -- obeyed an evacuation order, 
according to emergency management spokeswoman Martha Wickre. Most 
businesses closed. 
</P>
<P>
	On Hatteras Island, Herb Anderson was keeping his fingers  
crossed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got everything tied up, boarded up and nailed down,''  
Anderson said at the marina where he works. 
</P>
<P>
	On Ocracoke Island, which was evacuated Tuesday, pub owner Buffy  
Warner said he couldn't recall a time when so many locals had left 
in the face of a storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Even by North Carolina standards, Floyd was considered unusually  
menacing. 
</P>
<P>
	``In terms of strength and speed and force of the wind, it looks  
to be a once in a decade storm, or even longer,'' said state Public 
Safety Secretary Richard Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis began menacing North Carolina's coast Aug. 29, when  
upwards of 100,000 residents and visitors streamed off the state's 
middle and northern barrier islands. A slow-mover, Dennis stayed 60 
miles off shore as it drifted up the coast and then headed out to 
sea. Then it stalled and began backtracking. 
</P>
<P>
	It battered the Outer Banks for days with gale-force winds and  
14-foot waves, preventing evacuees from returning. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm came ashore at Cape Lookout on Sept. 3, drenching the  
middle of the state with more than 8 inches of rain. 
</P>
<P>
	The one-two punch of Dennis and Floyd on North Carolina's  
coastline evoked memories of 1996, the year of Hurricanes Bertha 
and Fran. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm smart enough to know when Mother Nature's going to win,''  
said Paul Raspet, a college student stuck in traffic Wednesday 
while trying to leave the mainland coastal city of Wilmington. ``I 
saw what Fran did. I saw pine trees ripped out by the roots and 
thrown like toothpicks. I'm not going to take any chances and go as 
far west as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fran struck Sept. 5-6, 1996, causing 24 weather-related deaths,  
not all in North Carolina, and about $6 billion in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Fran followed Bertha, which struck July 12 in the same region.  
It caused $1 billion to $2 billion in damage and killed 10 people, 
two in North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time in 41 years that two hurricanes struck the  
North Carolina coast during the same season. 
</P>
<P>
	David Loewenthal of the National Weather Service office in  
Raleigh said the region's recent rate of hurricanes is way above 
normal, but he does not blame any global weather trends. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a coincidence,'' he said. ``Let's hope the  
coincidence ends soon.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 13:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hockey Hall To Honor Gretzky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EVELETH, Minn. (AP) -- The U.S. Hockey Hall of Fame will honor  
hockey great Wayne Gretzky at the hall's 26th annual induction 
dinner and ceremony Dec. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to inducting three new people, the board of  
directors will unveil a new annual award for an international 
citizen who has made a significant contribution to the growth of 
ice hockey in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The new award will be called the Wayne Gretzky Award. Gretzky,  
who will attend the ceremony, will be the first recipient, 
president Jim Findley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1999 inductees will be announced later this month and will  
be enshrined at the dinner. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 20:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Jordan Enters Chicago Tourney  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Michael Jordan met his match on Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	The retired basketball star, who helped the Chicago Bulls win  
six NBA titles with his extraordinary skills, looked decidedly 
ordinary during Wednesday's opening round of the $150,000 Chicago 
Open golf tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan, who entered the tournament as an amateur, shot an 84, 13  
strokes over par, and admitted he was overmatched as he seldom was 
on the basketball court. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pretty sure I'm out of my league, but it was fun,'' Jordan  
said. ``What I take away from it is that you have to maintain a 
certain focus. Not just for five or 10 minutes. It's four hours of 
solid focus, and every little putt means something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The gallery of 100 or so cared nothing about the score, however.  
This was Michael Jordan, after all. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just exciting to see him,'' said Teri Kozina, who had her  
6-year-old son, Eric, in tow as she watched Jordan's round. She and 
her son watched his practice round on Tuesday, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got so carried away watching him practice, we had to make  
ourselves go back and give dad some support,'' Kozina said. 
</P>
<P>
	Her husband, Gus, is a Chicago-area amateur who played in the  
tournament Wednesday. He shot 86. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other Jordan-watchers were former NBA player Quinn Buckner  
and Chicago Cubs Hall of Famer Ernie Banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks, who made a special trip to Birmingham, Ala., when Jordan  
tried his hand at minor-league baseball, said he was on the golf 
course Wednesday to give Jordan moral support. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is my second go-round,'' Banks said. ``Mike's always been  
so successful, I'm sure he'd do well as a pro if he wanted to. I 
think he has a lot of talent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buckner was more of a realist, saying he doesn't think Jordan is  
ready for the big time on the links. Golf pro Dewey Lewis agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got a long, long way to go,'' said Lewis, who once gave  
Jordan golf lessons. ``Right now, he plays like what he is -- a good 
country club player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The second round of the 54-hole event is scheduled Thursday and  
only the top scorers advance to Friday's final round. Jordan knows 
he's through after the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the game of golf,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0289 </DOCNO>
