<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. State Bar Honors Gerald Ford </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- President Gerald Ford, who worked as  
a lawyer here after graduating college, has been honored by the 
Michigan State Bar for his public service. 
</P>
<P>
	In remarks Wednesday at the association's luncheon, Michigan  
Gov. John Engler said Ford has integrity that transcends partisan 
politics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think any president in living memory has been  
considered more trustworthy by both sides of the aisle,'' Engler 
said. ``We are proud of you, and we are proud you are one of our 
own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former president received two standing ovations.  
</P>
<P>
	Ford, who worked in Grand Rapids after attending Yale Law  
School, said he appreciated the recognition by his colleagues. In a 
speech, he criticized term limits, saying they negate voters' 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't like ... public officials or what they're doing,  
it's up to you, not the Constitution, to replace them with people 
more to your own liking,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
