<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Fall on Fed Concern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Stocks fell in Europe Wednesday as traders worried  
about a possible interest rate increase by the Fed next month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies fell 1.07  
points, or 0.3 percent, to close at 311.33. 
</P>
<P>
	A report Tuesday showing strong consumer spending in the United  
Staets helped fan fears that the Fed may raise rates when it meets 
again in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``The chance of a rate rise by the Fed in October is still on  
the table,'' said Mark Wall, equities economist at Deutsche Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in  
countries that joined the single currency, closed down 0.82 points 
at 328.85. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index fell 9.33 points to 3,816.53,  
while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed down 9.22 points at 3700.92. 
</P>
<P>
	In European markets, Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 0.3 percent,  
with software company SAP down 3.8 percent. However, energy 
companies Veba and Viag were higher, after a report, on which the 
companies declined to comment, claimed a merger of the two would 
result in an even split of their boards. 
</P>
<P>
	The Paris and London bourses were the worst performers, with a  
drop of 0.8 percent in both the CAC-40 and FTSE 100 indexes. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, heavyweight oil stocks came under pressure, with BP  
Amoco and Shell closing down. Crude oil futures came under pressure 
amid profit-taking and some bearish comments from Venezuelan 
President Hugo Chavez, who said oil prices shouldn't rise too much. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
