<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Traffic Jams As Residents Flee Floyd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- First came the hurricane warnings. Then  
came the traffic. Hours and hours and hours of it. 
</P>
<P>
	Around the Southeast, the bumper-to-bumper traffic jams from the  
biggest peacetime evacuation in U.S. history spawned fierce 
criticism of both politicians and emergency planners. 
</P>
<P>
	In South Carolina, first-term Gov. Jim Hodges was blamed by  
those who said he waited too long to turn Interstate 26 into a 
one-way road inland. The highway backed up quickly after Hodges 
ordered an evacuation at noon Tuesday that affected an estimated 
800,000 people in coastal areas. Traffic continued at a crawl 
Wednesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	State Rep. John Graham Altman, a Charleston Republican and a  
consistent critic of the Democratic governor, accused Hodges of 
``incompetence and ineptitude of epic proportions'' and called I-26 
a ``Hodges parking lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Altman suggested future evacuations be taken out of the  
governor's hands, ``because he can't handle it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One evacuee, Pat Wylie, said it took his brother-in-law 10 1/2  
hours Tuesday to get from Charleston to Greenville -- a trip that 
usually takes 3 1/2 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the politicians had a clue,'' he said. ``They  
evacuated everybody, and they had no plan for the numbers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charleston Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr., was more blunt. ``What  
you're doing is running the risk of killing my people. It was 
terrible,'' he said in an uncharacteristic attack on Hodges, a 
fellow Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	Hodges said the disaster plan developed by the state after  
Hurricane Hugo struck in 1989 did not call for opening both sides 
of the highway. He said experts had questioned the safety of 
opening the highway's eastbound lanes to westbound traffic -- 
concerns that were echoed by state transportation officials Tuesday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `I hear what you're saying, but I think the bigger  
public safety issue right now is those people stranded on the 
Interstate,''' the governor said. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 2.6 million people in South Carolina, Florida and  
Georgia were urged to flee the storm. 
</P>
<P>
	In Florida, traffic backed up 30 miles or more as 1.3 million  
people left their homes. One motorist reported taking five hours 
for a usual 30-minute drive across Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	Jebbie Bush, the 15-year-old son of Gov. Jeb Bush, told his  
father it took him eight hours to get from Jacksonville Beach to 
Tallahassee, about twice as long as normal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida Highway Patrol turned down a request by Jacksonville  
Mayor John Delaney to reverse the eastbound lanes of Interstate 10 
to allow for additional westbound traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	In Georgia, Karlene Barron of the state Transportation  
Department said the highways were mostly clear Wednesday, with some 
congestion on I-20 caused by people coming from South Carolina. On 
Tuesday, both sides of I-16 were opened to westbound evacuees. 
</P>
<P>
	In South Carolina, some people gave up, pulling over to sleep in  
their cars on the shoulder of the road. Every mile or two a car was 
parked along the side of I-95. Someone even left behind a boat with 
two outboard engines. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephanie Simmons, 22, of Charleston, said it took the 10 people  
in her van 12 hours to reach a Columbia shelter. She said she was 
disgusted to see people urinating along the road as they waited in 
traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was funny when people started walking along  
offering toilet paper to people with young children,'' Simmons 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaints were so numerous that The (Charleston) Post and  
Courier created a bulletin board on its Internet site so people 
could vent their frustrations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not once did I hear of any instructions by public officials to  
the general public as to what to expect. I had no idea when I 
joined the exodus that a two-hour drive would become 13 1/2 hours,'' 
one woman wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Hodges waited until almost 7 p.m. Tuesday before ordering that  
I-26 be turned into a one-way highway leading out of Charleston, 
but it took almost three hours to complete the switchover. 
</P>
<P>
	``The truth is that the plan didn't work because there was so  
much traffic on the interstate,'' Hodges said. ``We're dealing with 
a problem that no one has had to deal with before, nothing of quite 
this magnitude.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
