<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 17:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson, Jones Benefit in Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Michael Johnson will get a chance to replicate his  
historic sprint double in Sydney next year, and Marion Jones will 
be able to chase a record five gold medals. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson and Jones were among the main beneficiaries of the track  
and field competition schedule announced Wednesday for the 2000 
Sydney Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The schedule allows Johnson to defend the titles he won in the  
200 and 400 meters at the 1996 Atlanta Games, where he became the 
first man in history to sweep both events at the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, the sport's top female star, will have the opportunity to  
bid for gold in the 100, 200, long jump and both relays. 
</P>
<P>
	The timetable also clears the way for doubles by American  
sprinter Maurice Greene, the world champion in the 100 and 200; 
Ethiopia's Haile Gebrselassie, world and Olympic champion at 10,000 
and world record-holder at 5,000; and Russia's Svetlana Masterkova, 
the 1996 Olympic champion in the 800 and 1,500. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Amateur Athletic Federation, the sport's  
governing body, arranged the schedule specifically so top stars 
could compete in more than one event. 
</P>
<P>
	IAAF spokesman Giorgio Reineri said particular attention was  
given to accommodating Johnson and Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who set a world record of 19.32 seconds in the 200 in  
Atlanta, struggled with injuries and other setbacks for much of the 
next three years. But he reasserted his greatness at last month's 
World Championships in Seville, Spain, breaking the 11-year-old 
world record in the 400 with a clocking of 43.18. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the most highly anticipated races in Sydney would be a  
200-meter showdown between Johnson and Greene, the 100-meter world 
record-holder. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, meanwhile, won the 100 in Seville, but her bid for four  
golds was dashed when she settled for bronze in the long jump, her 
weakest event. Jones' season came to an end when she collapsed with 
back spasms in the 200 semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Sydney schedule, Jones will be able to complete both  
the 100 and 200 before the long jump final. The physical strain of 
jumping was blamed for her injury in the 200 in Seville. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sydney schedule includes a rest day between the qualifying  
rounds and finals of the triple jump, as well as other jumping 
events. 
</P>
<P>
	The timetable allows at least one rest day between semifinals  
and finals of races of 800 meters and more, and the 400 meter 
hurdles. 
</P>
<P>
	Track and field events in Sydney will be held from Sept. 22 to  
Oct. 1, with a day off on Sept. 26. 
</P>
<P>
	``This schedule protects the rights of the athletes to compete  
at the highest level without incurring any risks to their health, 
while offering spectators a balanced distribution of finals 
throughout the nine days of competition,'' IAAF president Primo 
Nebiolo said. 
</P>
<P>
	The schedule was approved Tuesday in Monte Carlo, Monaco, by the  
IAAF's technical delegates and representatives of the Sydney 
organizing committee, ending a protracted dispute between the two 
sides. 
</P>
<P>
	Sydney officials, accusing the IAAF of dragging its feet on the  
schedule, put tickets on sale earlier this summer based on a 
timetable that had not been authorized by the world body. The IAAF 
criticized SOCOG and said it wanted to make several changes, mainly 
to allow for a rest day between the semifinals and finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the final schedule, 11 finals were moved to different days  
than those on the ticket order form. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sydney won its main battle: The date of the women's 400  
final -- Sept. 25 -- remains unchanged. The women's 400 is the 
highest demand event in Australia because Cathy Freeman, 
Australia's two-time world champion, is expected to be a favorite 
for the gold. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made an exception for the 400 meters out of respect for the  
Australian public,'' Reineri said. ``But the principle of having a 
day of rest was respected in all other events.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reineri said the schedule negotiations had nothing to do with  
the IAAF's long-running demands for free tickets and a greater 
share of Olympic TV revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	Those matters will be addressed later this month at a meeting  
between Nebiolo and International Olympic Committee president Juan 
Antonio Samaranch. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
