<DOCNO> APW19990915.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 07:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Eyes Curbs Vs. Web Hate Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After hearing the Internet described as a  
``terrorism tutor,'' the chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee 
advocated pressuring Internet providers to prohibit violent groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders from several civil rights groups told a committee  
hearing Tuesday that hate groups are thriving on the Internet 
because it is inexpensive and widely available. But they opposed 
censorship. 
</P>
<P>
	Hate groups sponsoring computer sites were linked to a gunman  
who carried out a string of drive-by shootings in July in Illinois 
and Indiana and to arsonists who burned three synagogues in June 
around Sacramento, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``In 1999, the Internet can serve as a terrorism tutor,'' said  
Rabbi Abraham Cooper, associate dean at the Simon Wiesenthal Center 
in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Internet providers should be as creative in blocking  
access to sites as they were in creating the network and commended 
Yahoo.com for recently banishing 70 sites hosted by hate groups. 
</P>
<P>
	To encourage Internet providers to banish World Wide Web sites  
inciting violence, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the committee 
chairman, proposed legislation similar to that already in place to 
eliminate child pornography sites. The providers could get 
protection from civil lawsuits in exchange for dropping the sites, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet providers were invited to the hearing but did not  
attend, Hatch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional attention followed an explosion of computer-savvy  
hate groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The Southern Poverty Law Center of Montgomery, Ala., which  
counted one computer hate-group site in 1995, reported 254 in 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 01:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Residents Flee Hurricane Floyd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- They fled by the thousands, or tried  
to. Instead, their mass exodus became a giant gridlock. 
</P>
<P>
	Running from Hurricane Floyd, residents came bearing TVs, VCRs,  
dogs, photos and even a caged cockatiel, buckled into the passenger 
seat. 
</P>
<P>
	They pulled trailers, boats and wooden wagons, only to sit for  
hours Tuesday on Interstate 10 in a stalled line stretching nearly 
200 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is insane,'' said Vicki Drake, whose family was traveling  
in a four-car caravan that included the seat-belted bird. Where 
were they going? Mrs. Drake just laughed. ``We're not sure. Just 
west somewhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	West seemed to be the direction favored by much of Florida as  
Floyd rumbled up the coast, spreading more panic than bad weather. 
Jacksonville was expected to get heavy winds and rainstorms early 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Interstate 10 is the only major westbound highway out of  
Jacksonville, which is the last big city before hitting Georgia's 
state line. The airport began cutting flights Tuesday evening, 
curtailing the biggest escape route on Florida's Atlantic coast. 
Airports in Miami, Orlando and Fort Lauderdale closed hours 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	And so Jacksonville, which hasn't seen a destructive hurricane  
since Dora blew through 35 years ago, became a traffic bottleneck, 
clogged not only by its residents, but by people running from as 
far as Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	At a rest stop on I-10, just west of Jacksonville, the parking  
lot overflowed with hundreds of cars filled to the roofs with 
snatched mementos and supplies, looking like a modern-day version 
of ``The Grapes of Wrath'' complete with cellphones. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rhodes family left Jacksonville Beach at 9 a.m. It took them  
nearly seven hours to travel 35 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Marie Rhodes didn't want to leave, but her grown son, Ben,  
threatened to tie her to the car, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I lived there 50 years through Dora, and the worst that  
happened was my fence blew down,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Her son shook his head and jerked his thumb toward his mother.  
``I told her we weren't messing around with this one,'' he said. 
``This one is bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So they packed photos, clothes, food, the VCR, the CD player and  
all of Ben's compact discs. ``Three boxes of them,'' laughed his 
wife, Colleen. 
</P>
<P>
	Her mother-in-law snorted. ``We brought so much stuff, I said,  
`Why don't we just hook the house up to the bumper.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Many at the rest stop said they'd called ahead to Tallahassee,  
but were told there were no hotel rooms left. 
</P>
<P>
	Local radio stations warned there wasn't a room to be found  
within a 120-mile radius of Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone headed north first,'' said Ben Rhodes. ``Now everyone  
is going west. We don't even know where we are going. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just going that way,'' he said, pointing to the blinking  
rows of tail lights headed towards Tallahassee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990915.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 13:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Terrell Davis Injures Right Wrist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Terrell Davis is unsure about his status for  
Sunday's game after he injured his right wrist in the Denver 
Broncos' 38-21 loss to Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis' wrist was bandaged when he arrived at Mile High Stadium  
Tuesday to film a soup commercial. He also was nursing a scrape on 
his back from the Monday night game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a physical game, but the game wasn't any more physical  
than games I've played in the past,'' said Davis, who gained 61 
yards on 19 carries. 
</P>
<P>
	The running back isn't sure when the wrist injury occurred.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just know that when I left the stadium, (the wrist) was  
stiff then,'' he said. ``When I woke up (Tuesday) morning, it was 
real stiff. I don't think it's broken or anything. But it's stiff, 
and it swelled up a bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis will be a spokesman for Campbell's Chunky Soup, and a  
Davis label will adorn cans of the soup. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
