<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mixed; Gold Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar dropped to its lowest level  
against the Japanese yen in more than 3 1/2 years in European trading 
today, but was higher against other key currencies. Gold prices 
rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 104.34 yen late today, down from 106.33  
yen late Tuesday. It was the lowest close in London since the 
dollar finished at 104.33 yen on Feb. 27, 1996. Earlier, the dollar 
fell as low as 103.20 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The currency has not closed below 104 yen in London since Feb.  
19, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 103.75 yen.  
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0367, down from $1.0382 Tuesday. In  
midday trading in New York, the euro traded at $1.0389. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday,  
included 1.5461 Swiss francs, up from 1.5444; 1.4741 Canadian 
dollars, up from 1.4690. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6048, up from $1.6025. In  
midday trading in New York, the pound was worth $1.6110. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8866 German marks, up from 1.8839; 
6.3274 French francs, up from 6.3182; 2.1257 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.1226; 1.867.72 Italian lire, up from 1,865.03. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold dealers in London fixed a recommended price of $257.40 per  
troy ounce at midmorning, up from $256.90 on Tuesday. In Zurich the 
bid price was $257.10, up from $256.65. Gold rose 70 cents in Hong 
Kong to close at $257.55 
</P>
<P>
	Silver opened in London at $5.13 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.11. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
