<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies' Schilling Out for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Philadelphia ace Curt Schilling, scratched from  
his scheduled start Monday, will not pitch the rest of the season 
because of shoulder trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a reoccurrence of an old problem, I don't want to shut it  
down, it was a decision made by the general manager, the manager, 
the trainer and me,'' Schilling said Wednesday. ``I just never got 
any better. No one knows exactly what the problem is, I just have 
to rest it until it gets better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling (15-6) leads the team in victories, complete games (8)  
and strikeouts (152). He pitched 180 1-3 innings this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I care about those guys, they give up their bodies for the  
team,'' Phillies manager Terry Francona said. ``But we have to do 
what the docs say. It's a biceps problem and some tendinitis and it 
just moved around. He's just not recovering. '' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling's 3.54 ERA is the eighth-best in the league. He is  
second in the NL in complete games behind Arizona's Randy Johnson 
(11). 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling last pitched Sept. 8 against Houston at Philadelphia,  
allowing four runs and five hits in 5 1-3 innings. He was scheduled 
to start against the Astros on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies, 69-77 after snapping an 11-game losing streak  
Wednesday against Houston, have been eliminated from postseason 
consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, Schilling led the majors in strikeouts (300),  
complete games (15) and innings (268 2-3). He became only the fifth 
major league pitcher to strike out 300 in consecutive seasons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
