<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Gets Atlanta Olympics Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Organizers of the 1996 Atlanta Olympics gave a  
House investigating panel Wednesday a revised report on the bidding 
practices they used to win the games. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, prepared by former Attorney General Griffin Bell,  
was delivered to the House commerce subcommittee on oversight and 
investigations, which is examining the Atlanta bid in the wake of 
disclosures that organizers of the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake 
City gave out scholarships or cash to woo IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., chairman of the subcommittee, declined  
to release the report, saying through an aide that he was honoring 
a request from Bell that Atlanta officials be permitted to disclose 
the report Thursday in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	But one source, who asked not to be identified, said the report  
provides a detailed and factual accounting of all the city's bid 
activities, including a list of every gift worth $100 or more that 
Atlanta officials provided IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Echols, a spokesman for the Atlanta organizers, said the  
characterization of the report as ``detailed and factual'' was 
accurate, but he declined to comment further. 
</P>
<P>
	Echols said Bell and other Atlanta officials intend to release  
the report Thursday and discuss its findings. Dave Woodruff, a 
spokesman for Upton, said the Atlanta officials also have agreed to 
release eight boxes of previously secret records that were turned 
over to the subcommittee under subpoena. 
</P>
<P>
	Those records reportedly include documents indicating that  
Atlanta organizers thought IOC members could be bribed into voting 
for the city, although no evidence has surfaced that any such 
bribes were ever offered. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial report the Atlanta organizers submitted to the  
subcommittee in June listed 38 gifts that exceeded the IOC's $200 
limit. But records subpoenaed by the panel turned up evidence of 
other gifts, and Atlanta officials then agreed to provide a more 
complete accounting of their bid activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Echols said Atlanta officials expect the Bell report will  
``bring closure'' to all the questions that have been raised about 
the city's bid in the aftermath of the Salt Lake revelations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
