<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oracle Slips After Earnings Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Shares in Oracle Corp. tumbled after the  
database software developer reported first quarter profits that met 
Wall Street estimates, but fell short of more ambitious 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	For the three months ended Aug. 31, Oracle reported net income  
of $236.7 million, or 16 cents a share, up 21 percent from $195 
million, or 13 cents a share, in the comparable period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose 13 percent, to $1.98 billion from $1.75 billion.  
The results were reported late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Oracle opened at 40 1/8 Wednesday, down 5 5/16 from the previous  
day's closing. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings came weeks after the company's stock rose sharply  
following unexpectedly strong fourth-quarter estimates. That had 
raised expectations Oracle easily would beat first-quarter analyst 
estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Company executives said it had problems closing several large  
deals in a timely fashion. 
</P>
<P>
	Software sales growth slowed significantly from the fourth  
quarter. First-quarter software licenses and other revenue grew 9 
percent from the corresponding period last year, compared with 22 
percent year-over-year growth in the fourth quarter. Database 
revenue grew by 8 percent to $443 million, and applications 
software sales rose 11 percent, to $109 million, compared with the 
first quarter last year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
